igned to Headquarters of the Army of the Potomac, April 1864 to muster out.)\n* [[Overland Campaign]] May\u2013June. Commanded by Lieutenant Colonel [[Samuel E. Chamberlain]], Brigadier General [[Henry E. Davies, Jr.]]'s 1st Brigade, Brigadier General [[David McMurtrie Gregg|David M. Gregg]]'s 2nd Division of MG [[Philip Sheridan|Philip H. Sheridan]]'s Cavalry Corps, Army of the Potomac\n** Todd's Tavern May 5\u20136. \n** Wilderness May 6\u20137.\n** [[Battle of Todd's Tavern]] May 7\u20138.\n** Corbin's Bridge, Spotsylvania, May 8.\n** Davenport Ford May 9.\n** Sheridan's Raid to James River May 9\u201324.\n** North Anna River May 9\u201310.\n** Ground Squirrel Church, Ashland, and [[Battle of Yellow Tavern]] May 11.\n** Brooks' Church, or Richmond Fortifications, May 12.\n** Line of the Pamunkey May 26\u201328.\n** Totopotomoy May 28\u201331.\n** [[Cold Harbor]] May 31-June 1.\n** About Cold Harbor June 1\u20137.\n** Sumner's Upper Bridge June 2.\n** Sheridan's Trevillian Raid June 7\u201324.\n*** [[Battle of Trevilian Station|Trevilian Station]] June 11\u201312.\n*** Newark, or Mallory's Cross Roads, June 12.\n*** Black Creek, or Tunstall Station, and White House, or St. Peter's Church, June 21.\n** St. Mary's Church June 24. \n* Camp at Prince George Court House June 27-July 13.\n* Weldon Railroad and Warwick Swamp July 12. At Lee's Mills until July 26.\n* Demonstration on north side of James River July 27\u201329.\n* [[First Battle of Deep Bottom]] July 27\u201329. \n* Malvern Hill July 28.\n* Lee's Mills July 30.\n* Scouting duty until August 14.\n* Demonstration north of the James River August 14\u201318.\n* Gravel Hill August 14.\n* Strawberry Plains August 14\u201318.\n*[[Battle of Globe Tavern]] (August 18&ndash;21). Commanded by Chamberlain, Colonel William Stedman's 1st Brigade, Gregg's 2nd Division, Cavalry Corps, Army of the Potomac\n** Charles City Cross Roads August 18. \n** Weldon Railroad August 19\u201321.\n* Dinwiddie Road, near Ream's Station, August 23.\n* Ream's Station August 25. \n* Hawkinsville September 14. \n* Jerusalem Plank Road September 16. \n* Belcher's Mills September 17. \n* Poplar Grove Church September 29-October 2. \n* Davis' Farm September 30. \n* Arthur's Swamp September 30-October 1. \n* Vaughan Road October 1. (Veterans left the front for Massachusetts October 25, 1864.) \n* Boydton Plank Road, Hatcher's Run, October 27\u201328. \n* At McCann's Station until November 18. \n* Reconnaissance toward Stony Creek November 7. \n* At Westbrook House until December 1. \n* Stony Creek Station December 1. \n* Bellefield Raid December 7\u201312. \n* Bellefield December 9\u201310.\n\n===1865===\n* At Westbrook House until March 17, 1865. \n* Dabney's Mills, Hatcher's Run, February 5\u20137. \n* Provost duty at City Point until April 2.\n* [[Appomattox campaign]], March 29 \u2013 April 9\n** Company C commanded by Capt Edward A. Flint and Comapny D commanded by Captain Jamesserving in Provost Guard, Headquarters, Army of the Potomac\n** Eight companies commnded by Maj John Tewksbury in Brevet Brigadier General [[Charles H. T. Collis]]'s Independent Brigade, Headquarters, Army of the Potomac\n* Provost duty until May 27. \n* Duty in the defenses of Washington until June 26.\n\n===Detached Duty===\nThird Battalion (Companies I, K, L, and M)\n* Served duty in District of Beaufort, S.C., until August, 1862 Action at [[Pocotaligo, South Carolina]], May 22, 1862 (detachment). \n* Patrol and guard duty and picketing Broad River. \n* Expedition to St. John's Bluff, Fla., September 30-October 13, 1862. \n* Expedition to Pocotaligo, S.C., October 21\u201323. \n* Pocotaligo Bridge October 21. \n* Caston and Frampton's Plantation October 22. \n* Attached to [[X Corps (Union Army)|X Corps]], Department of the South. \n* Company M at Hilton Head, S.C., and outpost duty at Lawton's Plantation until August 1863. \n* A detachment of Company I served at Folly Island, S.C., until July 1863, and Morris Island, S.C., to August 1863. \n* The balance of Company I was on outpost duty at Hilton Head, S.C., June to August 1863. \nThird Battalion was permanently detached from the 1st Massachusetts Cavalry by S. C. 346, War Department, August 4, 1863, and designated Independent Battalion, Massachusetts Cavalry.\n\n==Casualties==\nThe regiment lost a total of 239 men during service; 6 officers and 93 enlisted men killed or mortally wounded, 140 enlisted men died of disease.\n\n==Commanders==\n* Colonel Robert Williams\n* Colonel [[Horace Binney Sargent]]\n* [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]] [[Greely S. Curtis]] - commanded at the Battle of Gettysburg\n* Lieutenant [[Caspar Crowninshield]] - commanded at the Battle of Antietam\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|American Civil War|United States}}\n* [[List of Massachusetts Civil War Units]]\n* [[Massachusetts in the American Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n* Allen, Stanton P. and H. G. Laskey. ''Down in Dixie: Life in a Cavalry Regiment in the War Days, from the Wilderness to Appomattox'' (Boston: Lothrop), 1893.\n* Bowditch, Henry I. ''Memorial [of Nathaniel Bowditch, Lieutenant, First Massachusetts Cavalry, 1839-1863]'' (Boston: J. Wilson & Son), 1865.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=7IkdAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA324&dq=National+Lancers+of+Boston+1st+Massachusetts+Cavalry&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj4n8LO9djmAhUHac0KHcNoCtgQ6AEwAnoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=National%20Lancers&f=false Crowninshield, Benjamin W. and D. H. L. Gleason. ''A History of the First Regiment of Massachusetts Cavalry Volunteers'' (Boston: Houghton, Mifflin and Co.), 1891.]\n* Dyer, Frederick H.  ''A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion'' (Des Moines, IA:  Dyer Pub. Co.), 1908.\n;Attribution\n* {{CWR}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://gettysburg.stonesentinels.com/union-monuments/massachusetts/1st-massachusetts-cavalry/ 1st Massachusetts Cavalry monument at Gettysburg]\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Civil War regiments]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1864", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1st_Massachusetts_Volunteer_Cavalry"}
{"title_page": "Israel\u2013Morocco relations", "text_new": "{{Infobox bilateral relations|Israel - Morocco|Morocco|Israel|map=Morocco Israel Locator.svg}}\n\n'''Moroccan\u2013Israeli relations''' are the official relations between [[Israel]] and [[Morocco]].\n\nWhile Morocco does not recognize Israel as a state and most Moroccans consider Israel as their enemy, the relationship between the two was secretly maintained after the establishment of Israel in 1948 because of the huge amount of Moroccan jews. The Israeli passport is accepted entry to Morocco with a visa granted on arrival.<ref>https://qz.com/1445321/what-its-like-to-travel-on-an-israeli-passport-as-a-palestinian/</ref>\n\n==History==\nMorocco, like many Arab countries, was formally at war with Israel since 1948, which culminated into the [[1948 Anti-Jewish riots in Oujda and Jerada|riots of Oujda and Jerada against Jews]].<ref>http://www.sephardicgen.com/databases/oujdaDjeradaSrchFrm.html</ref> This prompted Jews to flee from the country.\n\nHowever, under the reign of later King, Hassan II, it was characterized as controversial due to Hassan II's closeness with Israel although Moroccans as a people see Israel as their enemy. The close relations between Israeli and Moroccan leaders have become a subject for many years even within Moroccan society.\n\nAt 1975, the outbreak of [[Western Sahara War]] prompted Morocco to seek eventual and secret aids from Israeli intelligence, who had reorganized the [[Royal Moroccan Armed Forces]] and was thought to have helped building the [[Moroccan Western Sahara Wall]], something neither Israel or Morocco acknowledged today.<ref>https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2015/05/western-sahara-struggle-freedom-cut-wall-150528065625790.html</ref> During 1980s, Hassan II attempted to break the deadlock to recognize Israel by meeting with Israeli Prime Minister [[Shimon Peres]] in [[Rabat]] at 1986, but was met with backlash and protests from the Arab League and Moroccans alike, forcing Hassan II to withdraw his attempt.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1986/07/23/world/peres-and-hassan-in-talks-syria-breaks-moroccan-ties.html</ref> Nonetheless, Hassan II maintained bond with Peres, and Peres voiced his condolence when Hassan II died in 1999.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/24/world/hassan-ii-of-morocco-dies-at-70-a-monarch-oriented-to-the-west.html?mtrref=www.google.com&gwh=53DFDDD1F9D29D7D9F1917C99B2C6EED&gwt=pay</ref>\n\n==Today==\nLike late Hassan II, his son [[Mohammed VI of Morocco]] maintains this pragmatic approach and keeps a link between Morocco and Israel. Mohammed VI's advisor, [[Andr\u00e9 Azoulay]], is an instrumental Jewish Moroccan who facilitated the growth of Morocco in both economic and political terms; while also maintaining good ties with Israel.<ref>https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2017/10/231187/andre-azoulay-audrey-azoulay-unesco/</ref>\n\nMorocco also attempted to solve the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict]] by dispatching another Jewish aide close to Israel, Sam Ben Shitrit, to solve the conflict and make peace between the two.<ref>https://www.timesofisrael.com/moroccos-king-dispatches-jewish-aide-to-push-israeli-palestinian-talks/</ref>\n\nRecently, due to the growing push of [[anti-Iranian sentiment]] on both sides, as both countries have problems with the Iranian regime led by conservative Islamists, Morocco and Israel have sought to make their ties closer. Both countries participated in [[February 2019 Warsaw Conference]], aimed to be anti-Iranian. This was followed by suspicions and rumors over Morocco's attempt to normalize relations with Israel, which were caught up by protests.<ref>https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2019/02/266108/morocco-israel-normalization-secret-meeting/</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==Jews in Morocco==\n{{main|History of the Jews in Morocco}}\n\nJews have a long historical presence in Morocco, where they are presently the largest Jewish community in the [[Arab World]]. The Moroccan government has tolerated its Jewish community, even after the establishment of the State of Israel in 1948, facilitating the secret tie between Israel and Morocco. Moroccan-organized Jewish emigration to Israel continued while still manage to maintain strong ties with the Israeli government through its remaining Jews.<ref>https://interactive.aljazeera.com/aje/palestineremix/phone/return-to-morocco.html</ref> Moroccan ''mellahs'' (Jewish Quarters) also exist in some cities.\n\nMorocco is the only Arab nation to have a Jewish museum, which has been praised by Moroccans and Jewish communities alike. A large community of Moroccan Jews live around the world. <ref>https://moroccotravelblog.com/2016/11/05/museum-of-moroccan-judaism-jewish-museum-in-casablanca/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Moroccan Jews]]\n*[[Moroccan Jewish Museum]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00778664/document Questions about jewish migrations from Morocco]\n*[https://journals.openedition.org/bcrfj/4082 Research on Moroccan Jewry]\n\n{{Foreign relations of Israel}}\n{{Foreign relations of Morocco}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Israel-Morocco relations}}\n[[Category:Israel\u2013Morocco relations]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Morocco]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Israel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox bilateral relations|Israel - Morocco|Morocco|Israel|map=Morocco Israel Locator.svg}}\n\n'''Moroccan\u2013Israeli relations''' are the official relations between [[Israel]] and [[Morocco]].\n\nWhile Morocco does not recognize Israel as a state, the relationship between the two was secretly maintained after the establishment of Israel in 1948. For many years, [[Hassan II of Morocco|Hassan II]] had facilitated the secret relationship with Israel, and it was considered as instrumental in stabilizing Morocco and beating possible anti-royal threats within the country.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/the-two-faces-of-king-hassan-ii-1108656.html</ref> This secret relationship continues to play an important role in growing Israeli\u2013Moroccan ties, despite the lack of formal relations. The Israeli passport is accepted entry to Morocco with a visa granted on arrival.<ref>https://qz.com/1445321/what-its-like-to-travel-on-an-israeli-passport-as-a-palestinian/</ref>\n\n==History==\nMorocco, like many Arab countries, was formally at war with Israel since 1948, which culminated into the [[1948 Anti-Jewish riots in Oujda and Jerada|riots of Oujda and Jerada against Jews]].<ref>http://www.sephardicgen.com/databases/oujdaDjeradaSrchFrm.html</ref> This prompted Jews to flee from the country.\n\nHowever, under the reign of later King, Hassan II, it was characterized as controversial due to Hassan II's closeness with Israel. Hassan II was found to have invited [[Mossad]] and [[Shin Bet]] agents in the [[Arab League]] meeting held in [[Casablanca]] at 1965, and this was instrumental leading to the heavy military defeats of [[Egypt]], [[Jordan]] and [[Syria]] to the Israelis at [[Six-Day War]].<ref>https://www.timesofisrael.com/morocco-tipped-off-israeli-intelligence-helped-israel-win-six-day-war/</ref> Prior to the war, king Hassan II had developed a reciprocal relationship with the Israeli intelligence, who had assisted him in carrying out an operation in France to abduct and 'disappear' [[Mehdi Ben Barka]], a Moroccan dissident and left-wing opposition leader who had been based in Paris.<ref>https://en.yabiladi.com/articles/details/58726/history-1965-when-mossad-helped.html</ref> The close relations between Israeli and Moroccan leaders have become a subject for many years even within Moroccan society.\n\nAt 1975, the outbreak of [[Western Sahara War]] prompted Morocco to seek eventual and secret aids from Israeli intelligence, who had reorganized the [[Royal Moroccan Armed Forces]] and was thought to have helped building the [[Moroccan Western Sahara Wall]], something neither Israel or Morocco acknowledged today.<ref>https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2015/05/western-sahara-struggle-freedom-cut-wall-150528065625790.html</ref> During 1980s, Hassan II attempted to break the deadlock to recognize Israel by meeting with Israeli Prime Minister [[Shimon Peres]] in [[Rabat]] at 1986, but was met with backlash and protests from the Arab League and Moroccans alike, forcing Hassan II to withdraw his attempt.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1986/07/23/world/peres-and-hassan-in-talks-syria-breaks-moroccan-ties.html</ref> Nonetheless, Hassan II maintained bond with Peres, and Peres voiced his condolence when Hassan II died in 1999.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/24/world/hassan-ii-of-morocco-dies-at-70-a-monarch-oriented-to-the-west.html?mtrref=www.google.com&gwh=53DFDDD1F9D29D7D9F1917C99B2C6EED&gwt=pay</ref>\n\n==Today==\nLike late Hassan II, his son [[Mohammed VI of Morocco]] maintains this pragmatic approach and keeps the secret link between Morocco and Israel. Mohammed VI's advisor, [[Andr\u00e9 Azoulay]], is an instrumental Jewish Moroccan who facilitated the growth of Morocco in both economic and political terms; while also maintaining good ties with Israel.<ref>https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2017/10/231187/andre-azoulay-audrey-azoulay-unesco/</ref>\n\nMorocco also attempted to solve the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict]] by dispatching another Jewish aide close to Israel, Sam Ben Shitrit, to solve the conflict and make peace between the two.<ref>https://www.timesofisrael.com/moroccos-king-dispatches-jewish-aide-to-push-israeli-palestinian-talks/</ref>\n\nRecently, due to the growing push of [[anti-Iranian sentiment]] on both sides, as both countries have problems with the Iranian regime led by conservative Islamists, Morocco and Israel have sought to make their ties closer. Both countries participated in [[February 2019 Warsaw Conference]], aimed to be anti-Iranian. This was followed by suspicions and rumors over Morocco's attempt to normalize relations with Israel, which were caught up by protests.<ref>https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2019/02/266108/morocco-israel-normalization-secret-meeting/</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==Jews in Morocco==\n{{main|History of the Jews in Morocco}}\n\nJews have a long historical presence in Morocco, where they are presently the largest Jewish community in the [[Arab World]]. The Moroccan government has tolerated its Jewish community, even after the establishment of the State of Israel in 1948, facilitating the secret tie between Israel and Morocco. Moroccan-organized Jewish emigration to Israel continued while still manage to maintain strong ties with the Israeli government through its remaining Jews.<ref>https://interactive.aljazeera.com/aje/palestineremix/phone/return-to-morocco.html</ref> Moroccan ''mellahs'' (Jewish Quarters) also exist in some cities.\n\nMorocco is the only Arab nation to have a Jewish museum, which has been praised by Moroccans and Jewish communities alike. A large community of Moroccan Jews live around the world. <ref>https://moroccotravelblog.com/2016/11/05/museum-of-moroccan-judaism-jewish-museum-in-casablanca/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Moroccan Jews]]\n*[[Moroccan Jewish Museum]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00778664/document Questions about jewish migrations from Morocco]\n*[https://journals.openedition.org/bcrfj/4082 Research on Moroccan Jewry]\n\n{{Foreign relations of Israel}}\n{{Foreign relations of Morocco}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Israel-Morocco relations}}\n[[Category:Israel\u2013Morocco relations]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Morocco]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Israel]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:8440:42b0:3d22:a5d3:8b1c:ee44", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Israel%E2%80%93Morocco_relations"}
{"title_page": "Believe (Cher song)", "text_new": "{{short description|1998 single by Cher}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Believe\n| cover      = Cher-believe-cover.JPG\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Cher]]\n| album      = [[Believe (Cher album)|Believe]]\n| B-side     = \"Believe\" (Xenomania Mix)\n| released   = {{Start date|1998|10|19}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single]]|[[Maxi single|CD maxi-single]]|[[cassette single]]|[[VHS#Uses in marketing|video single]]|[[Gramophone record|7-inch]]|[[12-inch single|12-inch maxi-single]]}}\n| recorded   = July 1998\n| studio     = Dreamhouse Studios, London, United Kingdom\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]]\n| length     = 3:59\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Brian Higgins (producer)|Brian Higgins]]|Stuart McLennen|[[Paul Barry (songwriter)|Paul Barry]]|Steven Torch|Matthew Gray|[[Tim Powell (producer)|Timothy Powell]]|[[Cher]]<ref name=\"Ivors99\">{{cite web |url=http://theivors.com/archive/1990-1998/the-ivors-1998/ |title=The Ivors 1998 - The Ivors |website=TheIvors.com |year=2016 |accessdate=13 Oct 2016}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Mark Taylor (music producer)|Mark Taylor]]|[[Brian Rawling]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Paradise Is Here#Cher version|Paradise Is Here]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[Strong Enough (Cher song)|Strong Enough]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|nZXRV4MezEw|\"Believe\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Believe'''\" is a song recorded by American singer [[Cher]] for her 22nd album, [[Believe (Cher album)|''Believe'']] (1998), released by [[Warner Bros. Records]]. It was released as the [[lead single]] from the album on October 19, 1998. It was written by [[Brian Higgins (producer)|Brian Higgins]], Stuart McLennen, [[Paul Barry (songwriter)|Paul Barry]], Steven Torch, Matthew Gray, [[Tim Powell (producer)|Timothy Powell]],<ref name=\"Ivors99\" /> and Cher,<ref name=\"Bego2004\">{{cite book|author=Mark Bego|title=Cher: If You Believe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XIQcOufdLVUC&pg=PA283|date=15 July 2004|publisher=Taylor Trade Publishing|isbn=978-1-4616-2592-6|pages=283\u2013}}</ref> and was produced by [[Mark Taylor (music producer)|Mark Taylor]] and [[Brian Rawling]].\n\n\"Believe\" departed from Cher's [[pop rock]] style of the time for an upbeat [[dance-pop]] style. It featured a pioneering use of the audio processing software [[Auto-Tune]] to distort Cher's vocals, which became known as the \"Cher effect\". The lyrics describe empowerment and self-sufficiency after a painful breakup.\n\n\"Believe\" reached number one in the United States, the United Kingdom, France, Germany, Australia, Canada, Ireland, Scotland, New Zealand, Spain, Italy, Greece, Norway, Sweden, Denmark, Belgium, Hungary, Switzerland, Poland and the Netherlands. It earned Cher a place in the ''[[Guinness World Records|Guinness Book of World Records]]'' as the oldest female solo artist to top the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart, and became the highest-selling single by a solo female artist in the United Kingdom. It is one of the [[List of best-selling singles|best-selling singles]], with sales of over 11 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Cher/e/B000APVS9M|title=Amazon.co.uk: Cher: Albums, Songs, Biogs, Photos|work=amazon.co.uk|accessdate=14 October 2015}}</ref> Reviewers praised its production and [[catchiness]] and named it one of Cher's most important releases. It was nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year]] and won [[Grammy Award for Best Dance Recording|Best Dance Recording]].\n\nThe music video, directed by [[Nigel Dick]], has Cher performing in a nightclub. Cher has performed the song a number of times, including four of her [[List of Cher concert tours|concert tours]], most recently the [[Here We Go Again Tour]] in 2018. It has been covered by a number of artists, and has been featured in several elements of popular culture. Scholars and academics noted the way in which Cher was able to re-invent herself and remain fresh and contemporary amidst the more [[teen pop]]-based music of the period. They also credited \"Believe\" for restoring Cher's popularity and cementing her position as a [[Pop icon|pop culture icon]].\n\n==Recording==\nA demo of \"Believe\", written by [[Brian Higgins (producer)|Brian Higgins]], Matthew Gray, Stuart McLennen and [[Tim Powell (producer)|Timothy Powell]], circulated at Warner for months. According to producer [[Mark Taylor (music producer)|Mark Taylor]], \"everyone loved the chorus but not the rest of the song\". Warner chairman [[Rob Dickins]] asked the production house Dreamhouse to work on the song. Taylor said their goal was to make a Cher dance record without alienating her fans.<ref name=\"SOS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.soundonsound.com/techniques/recording-cher-believe|title=Recording Cher's 'Believe'|author=Sue Sillitoe|date=February 1999|work=[[Sound on Sound]]|publisher=soundonsound.com|accessdate=December 27, 2018}} (updated with Historical Footnote)</ref> According to Taylor, \"Two of our writers, Steve Torch and [[Paul Barry (songwriter)|Paul Barry]], got involved and eventually came up with a complete song that Rob and Cher were happy with.\"<ref name=\"SOS\" />\n\nThough she is not credited as a songwriter,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/11/arts/cher-resurrected-again-by-a-hit-the-long-hard-but-serendipitous-road-to-believe.html?pagewanted=all|title=Cher Resurrected, Again, by a Hit; The Long, Hard but Serendipitous Road to 'Believe'|last=Strauss|first=Neil|date=March 11, 1999|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=January 15, 2018|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]}}</ref> Cher said she contributed some lyrics: \"I was singing [the song] in the bathtub, and it seemed to me the second verse was too whiny. It kind of pissed me off, so I changed it. I toughened it up a bit. I wrote the lyrics, 'It takes time to move on, it takes love to be strong / I've had time to think it through and maybe I'm too good for you.'\"<ref name=\"Bego2004\" />\n\nThe track was assembled with [[Steinberg Cubase|Cubase VST]] on an early model [[Power Macintosh G3]], with synthesizers including a [[Clavia|Clavia Nord Rack]] and an [[Oberheim|Oberheim Matrix 1000]]. Cher's vocals were recorded on three [[TASCAM|TASCAM DA88]] digital audio recorders with a [[Georg Neumann|Neumann U67]] [[vacuum tube]]-amplified microphone.<ref name=\"SOS\" /> The song was recorded approximately in ten days in July 1998 in London, England.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe effects on Cher's vocals were achieved using extreme settings on the [[pitch correction]] software [[Auto-Tune]], using \"unnaturally rapid corrections\" to remove [[portamento]], the slide between two pitches.<ref name=\":0\" /> Taylor said it was \"the most nerve-wracking part of the project, because I wasn't sure what Cher would say when she heard what I'd done to her voice\".<ref name=\"SOS\" /> Cher approved of the effect and insisted it remain when the record label ask for it to be removed.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/11/arts/cher-resurrected-again-by-a-hit-the-long-hard-but-serendipitous-road-to-believe.html?pagewanted=all|title=Cher Resurrected, Again, by a Hit; The Long, Hard but Serendipitous Road to 'Believe'|author=Neil Strauss |accessdate=March 3, 2009 |work=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=nytimes.com | date=March 11, 1999}}</ref> In an attempt to protect their method, the producers initially claimed it was achieved using a [[vocoder]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The effect was widely imitated and became known as the \"Cher effect\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal |url= http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/musical/2008/06/09/080609crmu_music_frerejones?currentPage=1 |first= Sasha |last= Frere-Jones |date= June 9, 2008 |title= The Gerbil's Revenge |journal= The New Yorker |quote= In the manual accompanying Auto-Tune's fifth-release version, the zero speed setting is described as 'the Cher Effect.' |publisher= Cond\u00e9 Nast |accessdate= May 30, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n\"Believe\" is a [[dance-pop]] song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/4761/20140313/throwback-thursday-believe-cher-song-brought-auto-tune-listen.htm|title=Throwback Thursday: 'Believe' by Cher, the song that brought you Auto-Tune [LISTEN]|work=Music Times|accessdate=14 October 2015}}</ref> The song contains uncredited [[Sampling (music)|samples]] of \"Prologue\" & \"Epilogue\" performed by the [[Electric Light Orchestra]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Cher \u2013 Believe (CD, Album)|url=https://www.discogs.com/Cher-Believe/release/5680537|publisher=[[Discogs]]|accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> It is recorded in the key of [[F-sharp major|F{{Sharp}} major]] with a [[tempo]] of 133 beats per minute.  The song follows a chord progression of F{{Sharp}}\u2013C{{Sharp}}\u2013G{{Sharp}}m\u2013B\u2013F{{Sharp}}\u2013A{{Sharp}}m<small>7</small>\u2013G{{Sharp}}m\u2013D{{sharp}}m, and Cher's vocals span from F{{sharp}}<sub>3</sub> to C{{sharp}}<sub>5</sub>.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Believe|url = http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0048844_U1|website = www.musicnotes.com|accessdate = January 2, 2016}}</ref> \n\n{{Listen\n| filename = Believe - Cher.ogg\n| title = \"Believe\"\n| description = A 15-second sample of \"Believe\". It is noted for its use of a sound effect on the vocals (using the then newly invented [[Auto-Tune]] software), which became known as the \"Cher effect\".\n}}\n\n==Critical reception==\nBill Lamb from [[About.com]] said that the song is a \"perfect piece of dance-pop\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liveabout.com/top-pop-songs-of-1999-4053103|title=Top 10 Pop Songs of 1999|publisher=[[About.com]]|date=February 8, 2019|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> [[AllMusic]] editor Joe Viglione called \"Believe\" a \"pop masterpiece, one of the few songs to be able to break through the impenetrable wall of late 1990s fragmented radio to permeate the consciousness of the world at large.\"<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/song/believe-mt0010839295 Song review by AllMusic] Retrieved October 15, 2013</ref> Michael Gallucci gave a lukewarm review, writing that the [[Believe (Cher album)|''Believe'' album]] is an \"endless, and personality-free, thump session\".<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/believe-mw0000601566 Review by AllMusic] Retrieved October 15, 2013</ref> Larry Flick from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' said that it is \"the best darn thing that Cher has recorded in years\".<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/reviews/single_review_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=749849 Single reviews]. ''Billboard''</ref> [[Matt Stopera]] and Brian Galindo from ''[[BuzzFeed]]'' noted it as \"iconic\".<ref>{{cite web|first1= Matt |last1= Stopera |first2= Brian |last2= Galindo |title= The 101 Greatest Dance Songs of the '90s |website= [[BuzzFeed]] |date= March 11, 2017 |accessdate= March 31, 2020 |url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/mjs538/jump-to-the-rhythm-jump-jump-to-the-rhythm-jump}}</ref> [[Damon Albarn]], frontman of the bands [[Blur (band)|Blur]] and [[Gorillaz]], called the song \"brilliant\".<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t9eocwUfoSoC&pg=PA159&lpg=PA159&dq=rolling+stone+cher+album+guide&source=bl&ots=BiMhpm_PV-&sig=QFz-TO_YXv6TLUZkFio0vM0EJsc&hl=en&sa=X&ei=rh-MULCjGsuJ0QH9uoCoBg&sqi=2&ved=0CDIQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=rolling%20stone%20cher%20album%20guide&f=false |title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide |date= |accessdate=April 1, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' described the song as \"poptronica glaze, the soon-to-be club fave...\" and noted Cher's voice as \"unmistakable\".<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,285682,00.html |title=Believe Review &#124; Music Reviews and News |publisher=EW.com |date=November 13, 1998 |accessdate=April 1, 2014}}</ref> Tom Ewing from [[Freaky Trigger]] wrote that \"Believe\" \"is a record in the \"[[I Will Survive]]\" mode of embattled romantic defiance \u2013 a song to make people who've lost out in love feel like they're the winners.\" He added that \"it's remarkable that it took someone until 1998 to come up with \"do you believe in life after love?\", and perhaps even more remarkable that it wasn't [[Jim Steinman]], but the genius of the song is how aggressive and righteous Cher makes it sound.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freakytrigger.co.uk/popular/2014/07/cher-believe/#debug5|title=CHER \u2013 \"Believe\"|publisher=[[Freaky Trigger]]|date=July 24, 2014|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDeborah Wilker from ''[[Knight Ridder]]'' said that \"her electronically altered vocal\" on \"Believe\" \"is like nothing she's ever done.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=WTsfAAAAIBAJ|title=Cher throws more curves with latest album, 'Believe'|magazine=[[Knight Ridder]]|date=November 10, 1998|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Knight Ridder]]'' also described the song as \"present-tense disco, with Cher an anthemic, [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] manque.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=4m4yAAAAIBAJ|title=Cher's latest disco effort hard to 'Believe'|magazine=[[Knight Ridder]]|date=January 3, 1999|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> ''[[New York Daily News]]'' described the song as a \"club track so caffeinated, it not only microwaved her cold career to scorching-hot but gave dance music its biggest hit since the days of disco.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=V01OAAAAIBAJ|title=REBIRTH|magazine=Bartow Press|date=May 1, 2002|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> They also noted the song's \"killer hook and amazing beat.\"<ref>\"WHO'D EVER 'BELIEVE' IT? CHER IS A HIT AGAIN AGING DIVA SHOWS SHE CAN TURN BACK TIME WITH DISCO TUNE\". ''[[New York Daily News]]''. February 1, 1999. Retrieved March 26, 2020.</ref> [[Neil Strauss]] from ''[[New York Times]]'' wrote that \"the verses are rich and bittersweet, with the added gimmick of breaking up Cher's voice through an effect that makes her sound robotic. And the choruses are catchy and uplifting, with Cher wailing, \"Do you believe in life after love?\" All of it bounces over a bed of 80s-style electronic pop. It is a song with a universal theme\u2014a woman trying to convince herself that she can survive a breakup --\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/11/arts/cher-resurrected-again-by-a-hit-the-long-hard-but-serendipitous-road-to-believe.html|title=Cher Resurrected, Again, by a Hit; The Long, Hard but Serendipitous Road to 'Believe'|magazine=[[New York Times]]|date=March 11, 1999|page=|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Another editor, Jim Sullivan noted the track as a \"hooky, defiant, beat-fest of a song\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=KEtPAAAAIBAJ|title=The beat goes on|magazine=[[New York Times]]|date=July 21, 1999|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Bob Waliszewski of ''[[Plugged In]]'' said that Cher \"musters self-confidence to deal with a failed romance\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pluggedin.com/album-reviews/cher-believe/|title=Believe \u2013 Plugged In Online Album Reviews|author=Waliszewski, Bob|work=[[Plugged In]]|publisher=[[Focus on the Family]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] highlighted \"Believe\" as the best song on the album.<ref>[http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Cher Robert Christgau album reviews] Retrieved October 15, 2013</ref> It was voted as the world's eighth favourite song in a poll released by [[BBC]].<ref name=\"SOS\" /><ref name=\"About Cher\">{{cite web|url=http://cher.com/about-cher/about/ |title=About Cher |url-status=dead |accessdate=January 27, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115062731/http://cher.com/about-cher/about/ |archivedate=January 15, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC favourite song\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/us/features/topten/ |title=The Worlds Top Ten &#124; BBC World Service | publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= | accessdate=July 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n[[File:WKTU-FM's Miracle on 34th Street show - New York - seen on December 11, 1998 Cropped.jpg|left|thumb|upright|220px|Cher performing \"Believe\" on the [[WKTU]]'s \"Miracle on 34th Street\" show in [[New York City]] on December 11, 1998.]]\nThe song, recorded and released in 1998, peaked at number one in 21 countries worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cherconvention.com/Cher.htm |title=\"Believe\" #1 in 23 countries |publisher=Cherconvention.com |accessdate=October 7, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101110055118/http://www.cherconvention.com/Cher.htm| archivedate= November 10, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>  On January 23, 1999, it reached the Top 40 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and reached number one on the chart on March 13, making Cher the oldest female artist (at the age of 52) to perform this feat.<ref>https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/believe-cher</ref> Cher also set the record for a solo artist with the longest span of time between number one hits, since \"[[Dark Lady (song)|Dark Lady]]\" reached number one in 1974. She also set a mark for longest gap after her first number one song \"[[I Got You Babe]]\" released in 1965 with her then-husband Sonny Bono, and beat the record held by former [[The Beatles]]' lead guitarist, [[George Harrison]], who first hit the top of the charts in 1964 with The Beatles' \"[[I Want to Hold Your Hand]]\", and almost 24 years later he had his last number-one song, \"[[Got My Mind Set on You]]\". \"Believe\" also was ranked as the number-one song of 1999 by \"[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]\" on both the \"Billboard\" Hot 100 and [[Hot Dance Club Play]] charts and became the biggest single in her entire career.\n\nIn the United Kingdom, \"Believe\" spent seven weeks at number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.com/number5.html |title=List of UK Number 1's 1990s |publisher=Everyhit.com |accessdate=October 7, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100920210001/http://everyhit.com/number5.html| archivedate= September 20, 2010| url-status= live}}</ref> becoming Britain's biggest-selling single of 1998, and won its writers three [[Ivor Novello Awards]] (for Best Selling UK Single, for Best Song Musically and Lyrically, and for International Hit of the Year) at the 1999 ceremony.<ref name=\"Ivors99\" /> On 1 August 2014, \"Believe\" became the first female solo single to be certified Triple Platinum in the United Kingdom for selling 1,800,000 copies.{{Citation needed|date = May 2015}} As of October 2017, the song has sold 1,830,000 copies in the UK, making it the biggest selling song by a woman there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/official-charts-flashback-1998-cher-believe__20834/|title=Official Charts Flashback 1998: Cher \u2013 Believe|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=October 26, 2017|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe success of the song not only expanded through each country's singles chart, but also most countries' dance charts. In the United States \"Believe\" spent 23 weeks on the U.S. [[Hot Dance Club Play]] chart, five of those weeks at #1, and 22 weeks on the European Hot Dance Charts. \"Believe\" also set a record in 1999 after spending 21 weeks in the top spot of the Billboard [[Hot Dance Singles Sales]] chart, it was still in the top ten even one year after its entry on the chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cherconvention.com/Cher.htm |title=\"Believe\" Dance Singles Sales record |publisher=Cherconvention.com |accessdate=October 7, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101110055118/http://www.cherconvention.com/Cher.htm| archivedate= November 10, 2010| url-status= live}}</ref> On 13 October 2008, the song was voted #10 on Australian VH1's Top 10 Number One Pop Songs countdown. \"Believe\" was nominated for [[Record of the Year]] and [[Best Dance Recording]] at 42nd Grammy Awards, the latter of which it won.<ref>{{cite web | author= Matt Bell (Sound On Sound [SOS]) | year=1999 | title=Recording Cher's 'Believe' | url=https://www.soundonsound.com/sos/feb99/articles/tracks661.htm | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author= Billboard Magazine | year=1999 | title=1999 in Music | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sA0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PP2&lpg=PP2&dq=cher+believe+%231+czech+republic&source=bl&ots=63ATak3io_&sig=e5Aq-Fy6X2id0q2gA9i26575ObA&hl=es-419&sa=X&ei=9kwDVf6PF8O1sAS7xoJw&sqi=2&ved=0CDsQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q&f=false | accessdate=March 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n[[File:Cher-Believe (music video).png|right|thumb|Cher as a supernatural, wearing a glowing headdress in the music video of \"Believe\".]]\nThe official music video for \"Believe\", directed by [[Nigel Dick]], features Cher in a nightclub in a double role as a singer on stage while wearing a glowing headdress and as a supernatural being in a cage (with auto-tuned voice) surrounded by many people to whom she is giving advice. The video largely revolves around a woman who is in the club looking for her boyfriend and is heartbroken when she sees him with another woman. The version on ''[[The Very Best of Cher: The Video Hits Collection]]'' is slightly different from the previous version (the version that is also included on the Mallay Believe Bonus VCD) with additional scenes towards the end that were not in the original video. There are also two 'rough' versions of the video as the song was released in the UK and Europe before a video was completed. The first is a compilation of scenes from the videos of Cher's previous singles \"One by One\" and \"Walking in Memphis\" and the second includes a brief scene of the Believe video where Cher sings the chorus while the rest of the video is composed of scenes from \"One by One\".\n\nThree official remix videos exist for this song. Two of the remix videos were created by Dan-O-Rama in 1999. Both follow different concepts from the original unmixed video. Instead of showing the significance of the lyrics the videos mostly show Cher with different colored backgrounds and people dancing. The two remixes used for these videos were the Almighty Definitive Mix and the Club 69 Phunk Club Mix. The third video entitled Wayne G. Remix was released by Warner Bros. and the concept is similar to the Club 69 Phunk Club Mix video.\n\n==Live performances==\nCher performed the song during the [[Do You Believe? (tour)|Do You Believe?]], [[Living Proof: The Farewell Tour|The Farewell Tour]], [[Cher at the Colosseum]] and the [[Dressed to Kill Tour (Cher)|Dressed to Kill Tour]]. While she would lip-sync the entire song on various television programs, she would only lip-sync the synthesized verses when performing on her Believe and Farewell tours, the Colosseum shows and on the 2002 edition of ''[[VH1 Divas Live]]''. Since 1999, the song has been the encore to all of Cher's concerts until her 2014 [[Dressed to Kill Tour (Cher)|Dressed to Kill Tour]], where the encore is the ballad \"[[I Hope You Find It]]\", a second single from her 25th studio album ''[[Closer to the Truth (Cher album)|Closer to the Truth]]''.<ref name=\"Synopsis\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5944817/cher-delivers-classic-hits-outrageous-costumes-at-dazzling-dressed|title=Cher Delivers Classic Hits, Outrageous Costumes, at Dazzling 'Dressed to Kill' Tour Opener|author=Christina Fuoco-Karasinski|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=March 23, 2014|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> It returned as the encore at her [[Classic Cher]] (2017-2020) shows and stayed in that place for the [[Here We Go Again Tour]] (2018-2020) as well.\n\n==Impact and legacy==\n[[File:Cher Believe D2K.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Cher performing \"Believe\" on the [[Dressed to Kill Tour (Cher)|Dressed to Kill Tour]] in 2014.]]\n''[[VH1]]'' placed \"Believe\" at #60 in their list of '''100 Greatest Dance Songs''' in 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2000/vh1dance.htm|title=Rock On The Net: VH1: 100 Greatest Dance Songs|website=www.rockonthenet.com}}</ref> and at #74 in their list of '''100 Greatest Songs of the 90s''' in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2007/vh190s.htm|title=Rock On The Net: VH1: 100 Greatest Songs of the 90s|website=www.rockonthenet.com}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Publisher\n!Country\n!Accolade\n!Rank\n|-\n|2000\n|[[VH1]]\n|[[United States]]\n|\"100 Greatest Dance Songs\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2000/vh1dance.htm|title=Rock On The Net: VH1: 100 Greatest Dance Songs|website=www.rockonthenet.com|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n|60\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n|[[United States]]\n|\"The 500 Greatest Songs Since You Were Born\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?ID=1770 |title=The 500 Greatest Songs Since You Were Born|accessdate=19 December 2019|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217055432/http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?ID=1770|archivedate=17 December 2007}}</ref>\n|134\n|-\n|2007\n|[[VH1]]\n|[[United States]]\n|\"100 Greatest Songs of the 90s\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2007/vh190s.htm|title=Rock On The Net: VH1: 100 Greatest Songs of the 90s|website=www.rockonthenet.com|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n|74\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[NME]]''\n|[[United Kingdom]]\n|\"50 best-selling tracks of the \u201990s\"<ref>{{cite web|title=50 best-selling tracks of the \u201990s|url=https://www.nme.com/photos/50-best-selling-tracks-of-the-90s-1437045|date=21 May 2012|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n|5\n|-\n|2015\n|Robert Dimery\n|[[United States]]\n|\"1,001 Songs You Must Hear Before You Die, and 10,001 You Must Download (2015 Update)\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Cher - Believe|url=http://acclaimedmusic.net/song/S300.htm|website=Acclaimedmusic|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n|1002\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[BuzzFeed]]''\n|[[United States]]\n|\"The 101 Greatest Dance Songs Of the '90s\"<ref>{{cite web|first1= Matt |last1= Stopera |first2= Brian |last2= Galindo |title= The 101 Greatest Dance Songs of the '90s |website= [[BuzzFeed]] |date= 11 March 2017 |accessdate= 31 March 2020 |url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/mjs538/jump-to-the-rhythm-jump-jump-to-the-rhythm-jump}}</ref>\n|15\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''\n|[[United States]]\n|\"52 Best 1990s Pop Songs\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Estelle|last=Tang|title=52 Best 1990s Pop Songs|magazine=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|date=1 August 2019|accessdate=19 March 2020|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/music/g28505129/best-90s-pop-songs/}}</ref>\n|51\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Insider Inc.|Insider]]''\n|[[United States]]\n|\"100 of the best songs from the '90s\"<ref>{{cite web|first1=Alani|last1=Vargas|first2=|last2=|title=100 of the best songs from the '90s|website=[[Insider Inc.|Insider]]|date=25 April 2019|accessdate=19 March 2020|url=https://www.insider.com/best-songs-90s-2019-4}}</ref>\n|*\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Insider Inc.|Insider]]''\n|[[United States]]\n|\"102 songs everyone should listen to in their lifetime\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/best-life-changing-songs-2017-4#believe-by-cher-86|title=102 songs everyone should listen to in their lifetime|website=[[Insider Inc.|Insider]]|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n|*\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste Magazine]]''\n|[[United States]]\n|\"The Best Songs of 1999\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/08/best-songs-1999.html|title=The Best Songs of 1999|website=Paste|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n|9\n|-\n|}\n<small>(*) indicates the list is unordered.</small>\n\n==In popular culture==\nIt was featured in an episode of BBC's ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'' where [[James May]] had to chauffeur a Cher impersonator, and was also parodied in the season 3 ''[[South Park]]'' episode, \"[[Two Guys Naked in a Hot Tub]]\". In addition, it was featured repeatedly in the ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'' episode [[Living Conditions]] when Buffy's roommate plays it on repeat while ironing her jeans, driving Buffy crazy. It was also featured in an episode of ''[[Friends]]'', \"The One with Chandler's Dad\" in the seventh season during a montage of Las Vegas and also in an episode of ''[[Sex and The City]]'', \"Evolution\". It was also referenced in an article by ''[[The Onion]]'' that alluded to the song's ubiquity in [[1990s in music|the late 1990s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertainment.theonion.com/chers-believe-now-faintly-audible-everywhere-in-america-1819565350|title=Cher's 'Believe' Now Faintly Audible Everywhere In America|website=The Onion|date=October 6, 1999|accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA cover by ''[[Correatown]]'' was used in ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'' season 12, episode 4.\n\nIn 2009, on season 8 of ''[[American Idol]]'', [[Adam Lambert]] arranged and sang a slow ballad version of this in Hollywood week. This was likely why he was requested to sing this at the 2018 Kennedy Centre Honors.\n{{Original research inline|date=February 2019}}\n\nIn 2012, [[Ella Henderson]] performed an acoustic piano rendition of the song during the bootcamp stage of the ninth series of ''[[The X Factor UK]]'' earning praise from all judges and reducing [[Nicole Scherzinger]] to tears. A similar version was included on the iTunes deluxe version of Ella's album ''[[Chapter One (Ella Henderson album)|Chapter One]]''.\n\nOn December 7, 2015, [[Jeffery Austin]] performed a stripped-down, slower version of the song during the Top 9 live semifinals of ''[[The Voice (U.S. TV series)|The Voice]]'' in [[The Voice (U.S. season 9)|season 9]] of the show and in February 2017, contestant Taylor Alexander auditioned with a country version of the song in [[The Voice (U.S. season 12)|season 12]] of U.S. ''The Voice''.\n\nOn January 13, 2016, independent artist [[Madilyn Bailey]] released her version of the song accompanied by video.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l_ia07Ledv0 Madilyn Bailey YouTube channel: Believe Cher // Madilyn Bailey]</ref> Her version peaked at number 125 on the French [[SNEP]] official singles chart.<ref>[https://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Madilyn+Bailey&titel=Believe&cat=s LesCharts.com: Madilyn Bailey - \"Believe\"]</ref> staying 8 weeks in the chart.\n\nIn October 2016, Australian indie group [[DMA's]] recorded an acoustic cover of \"Believe\" for [[Triple J]]'s [[Like a Version]] program, which would later go on to be voted in at Number 6 in Triple J's [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2016|Hottest 100 of 2016]].<ref>{{Citation|last=triple j|title=DMA's cover Cher 'Believe' for Like A Version|date=October 27, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MmwFnoMoDDg|accessdate=January 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/hottest100/16/countdown/|title=1-100 {{!}} Hottest 100 2016 {{!}} triple j|date=November 11, 2016|website=www.abc.net.au|access-date=January 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAdam Lambert sang a [[ballad]] version of \"Believe\" at the 2018 [[Kennedy Center Honors]], at which Cher was an honoree. Cher and most of the audience gave him a [[standing ovation]].\n\n==Track listing==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*;Australian/South African CD single,\n*;European/Mexican/UK CD single #1\n#\"Believe\"&nbsp;\u2014 4:01\n#\"Believe\" ([[Almighty Records|Almighty]] Definitive Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 7:38\n#\"Believe\" ([[Xenomania]] Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 4:20\n\n*;Australian CD maxi single\n#\"Believe\" (Phat 'n' Phunky Club Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 7:44\n#\"Believe\" (Xenomania Mad Tim and the Mekon Club Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 9:16\n#\"Believe\" ([[Club 69]] Phunk Club Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 8:46\n#\"Believe\" (Club 69 Future Anthem Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 9:24\n#\"Believe\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:58\n\n*;European/Mexican/UK CD single #2\n#\"Believe\"&nbsp;\u2014 3:58\n#\"Believe\" (Grip's Heartbroken Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 9:12\n#\"Believe\" (Club 69 Future Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 6:50\n\n*;Japanese CD single\n#\"Believe\"&nbsp;\u2014 3:58\n#\"Believe\" (Almighty Definitive Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 7:35\n#\"Believe\" (Grip's Heartbroken Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 9:12\n\n*;UK/New Zealand Cassette single,\n*;US Cassette/CD/7\" single\n#\"Believe\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:59\n#\"Believe\" (Xenomania Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 4:20\n\n{{col-2}}\n*;UK 12\" single\n#\"Believe\" (Almighty Definitive Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 7:35\n#\"Believe\" (Grip's Heartbroken Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 9:12\n#\"Believe\" (Club 69 Future Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 9:14\n#\"Believe\" (Club 69 Future Dub)&nbsp;\u2014 7:54\n\n*;US 12\" single\n#\"Believe\" (Club 69 Phunk Club Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 8:43\n#\"Believe\" (Club 69 Future Anthem Dub)&nbsp;\u2014 7:13\n#\"Believe\" (Phat 'n' Phunky Club Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 7:42\n#\"Believe\" (Grip's Heartbroken Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 9:12\n#\"Believe\" (Club 69 Future Anthem Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 9:20\n#\"Believe\" (Club 69 Phunk Dub)&nbsp;\u2014 7:04\n#\"Believe\" (Xenomania Mad Tim and the Mekon Club Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 9:15\n#\"Believe\" (Almighty Definitive Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 7:36\n\n*;US/Canadian CD maxi single,\n*;Digital download (Remixes)\n#\"Believe\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:59\n#\"Believe\" (Phat 'n' Phunky Club Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 7:42\n#\"Believe\" (Club 69 Phunk Club Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 8:44\n#\"Believe\" (Almighty Definitive Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 7:36\n#\"Believe\" (Xenomania Mad Tim and the Mekon Club Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 9:15\n#\"Believe\" (Club 69 Future Anthem Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 9:20\n#\"Believe\" (Grip's Heartbroken Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 9:12\n#\"Believe\" (Club 69 Future Anthem Dub)&nbsp;\u2014 7:33\n#\"Believe\" (Club 69 Phunk Dub)&nbsp;\u2014 7:04\n#\"Believe\" (Pha