{"title_page": "Iqaluit Airport", "text_new": "{{short description|Airport serving Iqaluit, Nunavut, Canada}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Iqaluit Airport\n| image =Iqaluit-airport.jpg\n| caption = The old terminal\n| IATA = YFB\n| ICAO = CYFB\n| WMO = 71909\n| type = Public\n| owner = Government of Nunavut<ref name=\"NAS\"/>\n| operator = Nunavut Airport Services Ltd.\n| city-served = \n| hub =\n*[[Canadian North]]\n| location = [[Iqaluit]], [[Nunavut]]\n| timezone = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc = [[UTC\u221205:00]]\n| summer = EDT\n| utcs = [[UTC\u221204:00]]\n| elevation-f = 110\n| coordinates = {{coord|63|45|24|N|068|33|22|W|region:CA-NU|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Canada Nunavut\n| pushpin_label = CYFB\n| r1-number = 16/34\n| r1-length-f = 8,605\n| r1-surface = Asphalt\n| stat-year = 2011/2010\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 120,040\n| stat2-header = Aircraft movements\n| stat2-data = 20,178\n| footnotes = Sources: [[Canada Flight Supplement]]<ref name=\"CFS\">{{CFS}}</ref><br>[[Environment Canada]]<ref>[http://climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca/prods_servs/metstat1_e.html Synoptic/Metstat Station Information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627233755/http://climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca/prods_servs/metstat1_e.html |date=2013-06-27 }}</ref><br>Movements from [[Statistics Canada]]<ref name=\"move\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/51-209-x/2011001/t001-eng.htm|title=Aircraft Movement Statistics: NAV CANADA Towers and Flight Service Stations: Annual Report (TP 577): Table 2-2 \u2014 Total aircraft movements by class of operation \u2014 NAV CANADA flight service stations|website=www.statcan.gc.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20121123105343/http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/51-209-x/2011001/t001-eng.htm|archivedate=23 November 2012}}</ref>}}\n'''Iqaluit Airport''' {{Airport codes|YFB|CYFB}} serves [[Iqaluit]], [[Nunavut]], Canada and is located adjacent to the city. It is operated by the [[government of Nunavut]]. It hosts [[Airline|scheduled passenger service]] from [[Ottawa]], [[Montreal]], [[Rankin Inlet]], and [[Kuujjuaq]] on carriers such as [[Canadian North]], and from smaller communities throughout eastern Nunavut. It is also used as a [[forward operating base]] by the [[CF-18 Hornet]]. In 2011, the terminal handled more than 120,000 passengers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edt.gov.nu.ca/apps/UPLOADS/fck/file/Iqaluit_Airport_four_pager.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418160816/http://www.edt.gov.nu.ca/apps/UPLOADS/fck/file/Iqaluit_Airport_four_pager.pdf |archivedate=2014-04-18 }}</ref>\n\nThe airport is classified as an [[airport of entry]] by [[Nav Canada]] and is staffed by the [[Canada Border Services Agency]] (CBSA). CBSA officers at this airport can handle [[general aviation]] aircraft only, with no more than 15 passengers.<ref name=\"CFS\"/>\n\nThe airport serves as a [[diversion airport]] on [[polar route]]s.<ref name=\"Map of Polar Routes Diversion Airports\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/aeromagazine/aero_16/polar_fig3.html|title=Figure 3. Boeing-Conducted Airport Safety And Operational Assessments|website=www.boeing.com|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013235137/http://www.boeing.com/commercial/aeromagazine/aero_16/polar_fig3.html|archivedate=13 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/aeromagazine/aero_16/polar_fig1.html|title=Figure 1. New Cross-Polar Routes Via The North Polar Region|website=www.boeing.com|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923164056/http://www.boeing.com/commercial/aeromagazine/aero_16/polar_fig1.html|archivedate=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe airport is owned by the Government of Nunavut (GN)<ref name=\"NAS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tc.gc.ca/programs/Airports/Status/menu.htm|title=The page has moved - La page a \u00e9t\u00e9 d\u00e9m\u00e9nag\u00e9e|website=www.tc.gc.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224638/http://www.tc.gc.ca/eng/programs/airports-status-menu-441.htm|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref> and operated, under a 30-year contract, by Nunavut Airport Services. The company is a subsidiary of Winnipeg Airport Services Corporation, which in turn is a subsidiary of Winnipeg Airports Authority.<ref>[http://www.waa.ca/waa/wasco Winnipeg Airport Services Corporation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211063920/http://www.waa.ca/waa/wasco |date=2016-12-11 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Military use===\nDuring late July 1941, a [[United States Army Air Forces]] (USAAF) team headed by Captain [[Elliott Roosevelt]] investigated the [[Frobisher Bay]] region for a potential airport for use in trans-Atlantic air traffic. Roosevelt's report designated a marginal site at Cape Rammelsberg for later construction. In mid-October, trawlers ''Lark'', ''Polarbjoern'', and ''Selis'' reached the vicinity, but owing to inaccurate charts (dating from the 1865 expedition of [[Charles Francis Hall]]) could not find the Roosevelt site. Instead, an eight-man crew commanded by USAAF Captain John T. Crowell was offloaded on a smaller island \"about eight miles southeast of the headland Captain Roosevelt had recommended.\"<ref>Forbes, 59\u201365</ref> They operated a weather/radio station over the winter. The expedition reported that \"this island is reported to be some 400 feet high and very level on top providing a natural runway of more than a mile in length.\" The ships left on 5 November.<ref>Hubbard Report</ref>\n\nWhen the station relief and base construction expedition arrived next July, both the Crowell and Roosevelt sites were rejected in favour of a level meadow discovered along the Sylvia Grinnell River on mainland [[Baffin Island]]. On 30 July, ships ''Polaris'' and ''[[Effie M. Morrissey]]'' anchored in what was then called Koojesse Inlet and began surveying the area: \"The terrain was excellent, with level ground extending nearly the entire 6,000 feet needed for an ample runway...The harbor, readily accessible from the bay, offered a good anchorage for ships of any size that would come in.\"<ref>Forbes, 71</ref> The expedition consisted further of the [[USS Bear (1874)|USCGC ''Bear'']], equipped with a seaplane, the transports ''Fairfax'' and ''Eleanor'' and some smaller vessels. Having offloaded the airport construction crews and materials, the expedition left at the end of September.\n[[File:Frobisher Bay, Baffin Island, aeronautical chart section.jpg|thumb|Frobisher Bay airport approaches with original station sites noted. USDOD ONC D-15, 1971]]\n\n===World War II===\nBy summer of 1943, the airbase at Koojesse Inlet had \"grown to look like a populous village\" and was in use by many aircraft.<ref>Forbes, 116</ref> It was designated Crystal II and referred to as ''Chaplet'' in coded communications. It was one of three \"Crystal\" weather sites in the Canadian Arctic Region, [[Kuujjuaq|Fort Chimo]] (now Kuujjuaq), [[Quebec]] being \"Crystal I\", and a station on [[Padloping Island]] being \"Crystal III\". A detachment of the 8th Weather Squadron, [[Air Transport Command (United States Air Force)|Air Transport Command]] (ATC) took up residence at the station on October 1, 1942.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/076/387.xml|title=USAFHRA Document 00076387|website=airforcehistoryindex.org|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724230904/http://airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/076/387.xml|archivedate=24 July 2011}}</ref> The initial mission of the Crystal sites was to provide long-range weather information to the combat forces then building up in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\nAs part of the [[Crimson Route|Crimson East]] air route network, the airfield at Crystal II was referred to by USAAF Air Transport Command as ATC Station #10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/180/777.xml|title=USAFHRA Document 00180777|website=airforcehistoryindex.org|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724230910/http://airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/180/777.xml|archivedate=24 July 2011}}</ref> It was intended to be a transport hub between the Eastern Route, which originated at [[Presque Isle Air Force Base|Presque Isle Army Airfield]], Maine and the Central Route, which originated at [[Detroit Metropolitan Wayne County Airport|Romulus Army Airfield]] (Detroit Airport), Michigan. The original plan, briefed by Captain Roosevelt to USAAF Chief [[Henry H. Arnold|Henry \"Hap\" Arnold]] and others at the [[Argentia]] summit in August 1941, called for Frobisher Bay to be a node in a northern alternate air route, running from [[Churchill, Manitoba]] via [[Southampton Island]] over Frobisher to [[Sondrestrom Air Base|Bluie West Eight]] and [[Bluie East Two]] in Greenland, rejoining the main route in Iceland.<ref>Hansen, 199\u2013200, 211\u2013215</ref> The later success of the main air route via [[Narsarsuaq Air Base|Bluie West One]] and the spring 1943 victory in the [[Battle of the Atlantic]] led to cancelation of the Crimson project in late 1943, and the associated airfields were reduced to weather, communications, and logistics duties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/076/350.xml|title=AFHRA Document 00076350|website=airforcehistoryindex.org|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811063933/http://airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/076/350.xml|archivedate=11 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe use of Frobisher Bay declined with the end of World War II, with jurisdiction of the facility being transferred to [[Military Air Transport Service]] (MATS) in 1948, under its [[Air Weather Service]]. During the 1950s it continued to be used as a transit point by the  \n[[United States]] and Canada. The base was closed in 1963 and converted into a civilian airport.\n\n===Civilian use===\nSince the 1950s, Frobisher Bay had earned a reputation{{by whom|date=July 2018}} as a [[wiktionary:technical stop|technical stop]] for airlines flying the [[Atlantic Ocean|North Atlantic]]. Crews departing westward from [[Glasgow Prestwick Airport|Prestwick]] or [[Shannon Airport|Shannon]] in those years preferred to route via [[Iceland]] (or the [[Azores]]) to [[Gander International Airport|Gander]], thence to [[New York City]] or elsewhere. Weather, however, could dictate a northerly course, which is when Frobisher Bay came into its own. In 1959 [[Pan American World Airways|Pan American]] even had a base there and on at least two occasions had to change engines on [[Douglas DC-7]]Cs at Frobisher Bay.\n\nWith the introduction of the intercontinental [[Boeing 707]] and [[Douglas DC-8]], fewer airlines stopped at Iqaluit. The place remained prominent as a regional airport, continued in its strategic role of sustaining the [[Distant Early Warning Line]] (DEW), supported the occasional military exercise or scientific expedition, and was a key stopover on the North Atlantic ferry route.\n\nThrough the 1960s, [[Nordair]] was the main airline serving Frobisher Bay from Montreal, {{Convert|1100|NM}} to the south. [[Douglas DC-4]]s operated into the 1970s and [[Lockheed Corporation|Lockheed]] [[Lockheed Constellation|Super Constellation]]s between 1964 and 1969. In 1968 Nordair introduced the [[Boeing 737|Boeing 737-200]] on the Frobisher Bay run. At the same time, Bradley Air Services had been expanding. By the 1970s, the company's fleet of [[de Havilland Canada]] [[de Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter|DHC-6 Twin Otter]]s and [[Douglas DC-3]]s was serving many small [[Arctic]] communities from YFB, carrying passengers, mail, groceries, and other essentials. Bradley became known as First Air in 1973 and soon added [[Hawker Siddeley HS 748|BAe 748]]s.\n\nIn the 1980s, Canada's airline industry was in transition, with [[Air Canada]] and [[Canadian Airlines]] rapidly buying up regional operators. Air Canada acquired Nordair in 1977, and then sold it in 1984 to Canadian Airlines. Jet service to Iqaluit Airport continued, but under the [[Canadian North]] banner, which was, after the buyout of Canadian Airlines by Air Canada, to continue operations as an independent airline, jointly owned by the [[Inuit]] of the [[Northwest Territories]] and Nunavut. Between 1985 and 1988 First Air added four [[Boeing 727]]s to link Montreal and Ottawa with Iqaluit. Meanwhile, Canadian Airlines failed, and was taken over by Air Canada in 2000. In 1995 First Air purchased the small [[Yellowknife]]-based carrier, Ptarmigan Airways; then, in 1997, Northwest Territorial Airways (NWT Air), Air Canada's Yellowknife subsidiary. In acquiring NWT Air First Air obtained two 737-200 [[Combi aircraft|Combi]]s and a Lockheed [[Lockheed L-100 Hercules|382 Hercules]].<ref>''Airways'' (June 2006) ''Pages 24-28'' ''YFB and First Air''</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n*2 hangar/cargo terminals (Canadian North) - hangar was terminal building until 1986<ref name=\"chriswindeyer.com\">{{cite web|url=https://chriswindeyer.com/writing/the-new-iqaluit-airport/|title=Protected Blog \u203a Log in|author=|date=|website=chriswindeyer.com|accessdate=4 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107023956/https://chriswindeyer.com/writing/the-new-iqaluit-airport/|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*1 two-storey terminal building c. 1986<ref name=\"chriswindeyer.com\"/>\n*1 main runway\n*three aprons\n*1 FBO (Frobisher Bay Touchdown Services)\n*administration and control tower (former terminal)\n\nIqaluit International Airport Fire Department operates one crash tender for local fire suppression and has support from [[Iqaluit Fire Department]] when needed.\n\n==Terminal==\nThe main terminal (c.1986) has:\n*Check-in desks\n*3 gates\n*1 baggage claim belt\n*Gift shop\n*Travel agent\n*Tourist help desk\n*Car rental\n*Taxi service/rank\n*Baby/parent room\n*Disabled access/facilities\n*30 short term parking spaces\n* display cases for local artwork\n\nAs a result of increased traffic, limited post-security waiting area<ref name=\"case study\">{{cite journal |first=Catherine |last=Kloepfer |title=An airport public\u2013private partnership in the Canadian Arctic |url=https://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/hsp/cam/2017/00000011/00000002/art00004 |publisher=Journal of Airport Management |year=2017 |volume=11 |issue=2 |pages=136\u2013146 |journal= |access-date=2019-04-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421044303/https://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/hsp/cam/2017/00000011/00000002/art00004 |archive-date=2019-04-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> and subsiding taxiway,<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Greg A. |last1=Oldenborger |first2=Anne-Marie |last2=LeBlanc |title=Geophysical characterization of permafrost terrain at Iqaluit International Airport, Nunavut |journal=Journal of Applied Geophysics |year=2015 |volume=123 |pages=36\u201349 |doi=10.1016/j.jappgeo.2015.09.016}}</ref> the Nunavut government planned an overhaul of the airport that was expected to cost $250\u2013300 million. The project was a [[public\u2013private partnership]] with the GN borrowing their half of the cost. Nunavut Airport Services will operate the airport for 30 years. Upgrades included:\n* new {{convert|100,000|ft2|abbr=on}} terminal building constructed by [[Bouygues]]<ref>[http://www.bouygues.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/bouygues_2015_registration_document1.pdf 2015 Registration Document] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604033152/http://www.bouygues.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/bouygues_2015_registration_document1.pdf |date=2016-06-04 }} page 36</ref>\n* retrofitting the current terminal which will become solely an administration building and control tower\n* expanding parking lots\n* new combined services building to house all airport and safety vehicles\n* a second taxiway \n* apron and repaving the runway.\n\nThe construction began in 2014 and was completed on August 8, 2017, with flight service beginning the following day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/story/2012/07/06/north-iqaluit-airport-rennovations.html |title=Iqaluit airport to be overhauled by 2017 |publisher=CBC |date=2012-07-06 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707161441/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/story/2012/07/06/north-iqaluit-airport-rennovations.html |archivedate=2012-07-07 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674new_public-private_iqaluit_airport_to_cost_up_to_300_million/ |title=New public-private Iqaluit airport to cost up to $300 million |newspaper=Nunatsiaq News |date=2012-07-06 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216004226/http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674new_public-private_iqaluit_airport_to_cost_up_to_300_million/ |archivedate=2014-12-16 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://nationtalk.ca/story/new-iqaluit-international-airport-terminal-opening/ |title=New Iqaluit International Airport terminal opening |publisher=NationTalk |date=2017-08-08 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029065843/http://nationtalk.ca/story/new-iqaluit-international-airport-terminal-opening |archivedate=2017-10-29 }}</ref> On September 5, 2015, during construction, a large fire caused major damage to the roof of the new terminal, costing an estimated $1 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/iqaluit-airport-fire-damage-1.3222831 |title=Iqaluit airport terminal fire damage estimated at $1M |publisher=CBC |date=2015-09-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811101405/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/iqaluit-airport-fire-damage-1.3222831 |archivedate=2016-08-11 }}</ref> Aside from the fire, other challenges encountered in the construction include thawing permafrost, electricity demands, housing for construction workers, extreme cold temperatures and short daylight hours in winter, and advanced planning to take advantage of summer sea lifts to lower the delivery cost of construction materials.<ref name=\"case study\" />\n\nThe new terminal has:\n*16 Check-in desks<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluits_new_airport_big_bold_and_beautiful/|title=Nunatsiaq News 2017-05-29: NEWS: Iqaluit's new airport: big, bold and beautiful|website=www.nunatsiaqonline.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112222908/http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluits_new_airport_big_bold_and_beautiful/|archivedate=12 January 2018}}</ref>\n* 5 gates<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\"/>\n* 2 baggage claim carousel<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\"/>\n* departures conveyor belt to carry baggage to screening area<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\"/>\n* caf\u00e9<ref name=\"cbc.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/iqaluit-airport-opens-1.4239486|title=Iqaluit's new $300M airport opens today - CBC News|website=cbc.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121233311/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/iqaluit-airport-opens-1.4239486|archivedate=21 November 2017}}</ref>\n* Passenger waiting lounge<ref name=\"cbc.ca\"/>\n* Store<ref name=\"cbc.ca\"/>\n* Gift shop<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\"/>\n* Travel agent desk\n* Tourist help desk\n* Car rental desk\n* Taxi service\n* Parenting room\n* Central rotunda<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\"/>\n* Accessible entrance and gates\n* 100 parking spaces<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\"/>\n* Art work: Kenojuak Ashevak's Enchanted Owl - mural in the rotunda and Duffell wall hangings<ref name=\"cbc.ca\"/>\n\n==Other information==\nOver the years several international flights have been diverted to Iqaluit due to technical reasons,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/flight-from-zurich-to-l-a-diverts-to-iqaluit-after-engine-shuts-down-1.3267034|title=Flight from Zurich to L.A. diverts to Iqaluit after engine shuts down|date=1 February 2017|website=ctvnews.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029082757/http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/flight-from-zurich-to-l-a-diverts-to-iqaluit-after-engine-shuts-down-1.3267034|archivedate=29 October 2017}}</ref> [[air rage]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/passenger-diverted-aeroflot-flight-iqaluit-plea-1.3964618|title=Accused passenger from diverted Aeroflot flight tries to plead guilty - CBC News|website=cbc.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217135525/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/passenger-diverted-aeroflot-flight-iqaluit-plea-1.3964618|archivedate=17 February 2017}}</ref> or on-board medical emergencies with no deaths being reported.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/moscow-to-l-a-flight-makes-emergency-landing-in-iqaluit-1.3257521?cmp=rss |title=Moscow to L.A. flight makes emergency landing in Iqaluit |publisher=CBC |date=2015-10-05 |accessdate=2015-10-06 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151113223759/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/moscow-to-l-a-flight-makes-emergency-landing-in-iqaluit-1.3257521?cmp=rss |archivedate=2015-11-13 }}</ref> On 31 May 1996, [[Virgin Atlantic Airways|Virgin Atlantic]] flight 7 from [[London]] to [[Los Angeles]] made an [[emergency landing]] at Iqaluit after a passenger had a heart attack. The landing was executed safely - the first [[Boeing 747]] ever to attempt to land at Iqaluit - but one of the 747's engines hit a fuel pump on the tarmac as it was taxiing, causing serious damage to the aircraft and a potentially dangerous fuel spill. The 397 stranded passengers, including singer [[Gary Barlow]], were flown out after Virgin Atlantic chartered two jets. The passengers, after spending 16 hours in a local [[curling]] rink, were taken to New York to catch connecting flights to Los Angeles. [[Prince Michael of Kent]], who had also been on the flight, was given a [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] escort and departed on an earlier scheduled flight. The original aircraft had its engines repaired and left four days after the accident. The heart-attack victim survived.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/back-issues/week/60607.html#7|title=Unexpected Arctic stop for Brits, Yanks|website=nunatsiaq.com|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514054733/http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/back-issues/week/60607.html#7|archivedate=14 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Airbus A380 in Iqaluit 02.jpg|thumb|Airbus A380 at Iqaluit]]\nThe [[Airbus A380]], the world's largest passenger jet, conducted cold weather testing from Iqaluit Airport during February 2006 - its first North American visit. They were hoping to experience {{convert|-25|C|0}} weather to determine the effects on cabin temperatures and engine performance. Nunavut authorities hope that the importance of these tests will put Iqaluit on the map as a centre for cold-weather testing.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2006/02/10/airbus060310.html |title=Jumbo Airbus getting cold, and more, during Iqaluit tests |publisher=CBC |date=2006-02-10 |accessdate =2010-04-12}}</ref> In February 2013, [[Airbus Military]] used the airport to test the [[Airbus A400M Atlas]] military transport aircraft that is currently being developed.<ref>[http://www.airbusmilitary.com/LatestNews/tabid/176/ArticleID/250/ArtMID/681/Airbus-Military-A400M-undergoes-latest-cold-weather-tests.aspx Airbus Military A400M undergoes latest cold weather tests] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130321215847/http://www.airbusmilitary.com/LatestNews/tabid/176/ArticleID/250/ArtMID/681/Airbus-Military-A400M-undergoes-latest-cold-weather-tests.aspx |date=2013-03-21 }}</ref> The city government sent a delegation to [[Paris Airshow]] in June 2013 to promote Iqaluit as an ideal location for these tests. [[Airbus A350]] followed suit and conducted its cold weather testing in January 2014. Airport staff cited low landing fee, sufficient runway length, and minimal air traffic movement all helped in the decision making.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/airbus-s-new-a350-in-iqaluit-for-cold-weather-testing-1.2512504 |title=Airbus's new A350 in Iqaluit for cold weather testing |date=2014-01-27 |publisher=CBC News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140131194653/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/airbus-s-new-a350-in-iqaluit-for-cold-weather-testing-1.2512504 |archivedate=2014-01-31 }}</ref> Following from these previous successful visits by prototype Airbus aircraft, the company sent the first [[A320neo]] with [[CFM International LEAP]] engines to be tested in January 2016. As part of the type's first visit to [[North America]], the jet performed several circuits in the subzero temperatures before departing back to [[Toulouse\u2013Blagnac Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/airbus-a320neo-cold-test-iqaluit-1.3422936 |title=Airbus cold-weather tests its A320neo in Iqaluit |date=2016-01-28 |publisher=CBC News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205100815/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/airbus-a320neo-cold-test-iqaluit-1.3422936 |archivedate=2017-02-05 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2005 the Government of Nunavut announced that it would spend $40 million to repair the runway, build a new emergency services facility and a new terminal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/51216/news/nunavut/51216_11.html|title=Nunatsiaq News|website=nunatsiaq.com|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20060206222721/http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/51216/news/nunavut/51216_11.html|archivedate=6 February 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012 [[Air Greenland]] announced that a 1-hour, 45-minute flight from [[Nuuk]] to Iqaluit, down from three days when going via Copenhagen or Reykjavik and then on to Ottawa, would begin 18 June 2012, later changed to 15 June. The service was a partnership with [[First Air]] who provided ticketing and other services in Iqaluit. This was the first international flight into Iqaluit since 2001 when First Air discontinued its Iqaluit to [[Kangerlussuaq]] flights. Air Greenland used [[Bombardier Dash 8|Dash 8]] aircraft on the run.<ref name=\"agcbc\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/story/2012/06/07/north-greenland-first-air.html | title=Air Greenland teams with First Air for Iqaluit flights | date=8 June 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120610195403/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/story/2012/06/07/north-greenland-first-air.html | archivedate=10 June 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"agpr\">{{cite news|url=http://www.airgreenland.com/nyhedsvisning/?newsid=1030 |work=Air Greenland |title=Air Greenland opens summer-route to Canada |date=18 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518084537/http://www.airgreenland.com/nyhedsvisning/?newsid=1030 |archivedate=18 May 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluit-nuuk_flights_ready_for_june_15_take-off/|title=Nunatsiaq News 2012-05-28: NEWS: Iqaluit-Nuuk service ready for June 15 take-off|website=www.nunatsiaqonline.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213202304/http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluit-nuuk_flights_ready_for_june_15_take-off|archivedate=13 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluit_welcomes_new_air_link/|title=Nunatsiaq News 2012-01-18: NEWS: Tireless lobbying led to Iqaluit-Greenland air link revival|website=www.nunatsiaqonline.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213025756/http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluit_welcomes_new_air_link/|archivedate=13 February 2018}}</ref> After three years in place the service was discontinued for the 2015 season.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/air-greenland-cuts-nuuk-iqaluit-scheduled-flights-in-2015-1.2985006 | title=Air Greenland cuts Nuuk-Iqaluit scheduled flights in 2015 | date=6 March 2015 | publisher=CBC News | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115142652/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/air-greenland-cuts-nuuk-iqaluit-scheduled-flights-in-2015-1.2985006 | archivedate=15 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n\n===Passenger===\n{{airport-dest-list\n| [[Air Nunavut]] | '''Charter:'''  [[Arctic Bay Airport|Arctic Bay]], [[Cape Dorset Airport|Cape Dorset]], [[Clyde River Airport|Clyde River]], [[Hall Beach Airport|Hall Beach]], [[Igloolik Airport|Igloolik]], [[Mary River Aerodrome|Mary River]], [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Pierre Elliott Trudeau International Airport|Montr\u00e9al\u2013Trudeau]], [[Nuuk Airport|Nuuk]], [[Ottawa Airport|Ottawa]], [[Pangnirtung Airport|Pangnirtung]], [[Pond Inlet Airport|Pond Inlet]], [[Qikiqtarjuaq Airport|Qikiqtarjuaq]], [[Rankin Inlet Airport|Rankin Inlet]], [[Resolute Bay Airport|Resolute]], [[Yellowknife Airport|Yellowknife]]\n| {{nowrap|[[Canadian North]]}} | [[Arctic Bay Airport|Arctic Bay]], [[Cape Dorset Airport|Cape Dorset]], [[Clyde River Airport|Clyde River]], [[Edmonton International Airport|Edmonton]], [[Hall Beach Airport|Hall Beach]], [[Igloolik Airport|Igloolik]], [[Kimmirut Airport|Kimmirut]], [[Kuujjuaq Airport|Kuujjuaq]], [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Trudeau International Airport|Montreal\u2013Trudeau]], [[Ottawa Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport|Ottawa]], [[Pangnirtung Airport|Pangnirtung]], [[Pond Inlet Airport|Pond Inlet]], [[Qikiqtarjuaq Airport|Qikiqtarjuaq]], [[Rankin Inlet Airport|Rankin Inlet]], [[Resolute Bay Airport|Resolute Bay]], [[Yellowknife Airport|Yellowknife]]<ref>[https://canadiannorth.com/plan_your_trip/flight-schedule/?type=full#skedsearchform Full network schedule]</ref>\n| [[Chrono Aviation]] | '''Charter:''' [[Montreal Saint-Hubert Longueuil Airport|Montr\u00e9al/Saint-Hubert Airport]], [[Mary River Aerodrome|Mary River]]\n| {{nowrap|[[Nolinor Aviation]]}} | '''Charter:''' [[Region of Waterloo International Airport|Kitchener/Waterloo]], [[Mary River Aerodrome|Mary River]]\n}}\n\n[[Air Canada]] had operated service to Ottawa and Montreal from March 2010 to August 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluit_flyers_say_theyll_miss_air_canada/|title=Nunatsiaq News 2011-07-05: NEWS: Iqaluit flyers say they'll miss Air Canada|website=www.nunatsiaqonline.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107012133/http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluit_flyers_say_theyll_miss_air_canada/|archivedate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAir Baffin began as chartered service in 1989, as a schedule airline in 1992 and renamed as Air Nunavut in 1996.\n\n[[Air Greenland]] had operated service to Nuuk, Greenland in 2012, 2013 and 2014.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/air-greenland-cuts-nuuk-iqaluit-scheduled-flights-in-2015-1.2985006</ref>\n\n=== Cargo ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Airlines\n!Destinations\n|-\n|[[Canadian North]]\n|[[Ottawa Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport|Ottawa]]\n|-\n|[[Cargojet|Cargojet Airways]]\n|[[Winnipeg James Armstrong Richardson International Airport|Winnipeg]]\n|-\n|[[Purolator Inc.|Purolator Courier]] operated by [[Cargojet|Cargojet Airways]]\n|[[Calgary International Airport|Calgary]]\n|}\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n*On 12 February 1973, [[Douglas C-47|Douglas C-47A]] C-FOOV of [[Kenting Atlas Aviation]] crashed on approach. The aircraft was on a ferry flight to [[Resolute Bay Airport]] when power was lost shortly after take-off from Iqaluit and the decision was made to return. All three people on board survived.<ref name=ASN120273>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19730212-0 |title=CF-OOV Accident description |website=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=26 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20100826181146/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19730212-0 |archivedate=26 August 2010 }}</ref>\n*On 14 August 1996, a [[Canadian Forces]] [[CF-18 Hornet]] left the runway during [[takeoff]], slid down an embankment and ruptured a fuel pipeline. The aircraft caught fire, as did fuel spilling from the pipeline, however the pilot had ejected just as the plane left the runway and only suffered a broken ankle. The pipeline was shut down and the fire brought under control in less than an hour.<ref>[http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/back-issues/week/60816.html#1 Pilot ejects in nick of time as CF-18 crashes while attempting to take off.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107084849/http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/back-issues/week/60816.html |date=2007-11-07 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Can-arpt-wx|CYFB|Iqaluit Airport}}\n*[http://polarpilots.ca: Website of local private pilot group based at CYFB]\n\n{{List of airports in Canada}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Certified airports in the Qikiqtaaluk Region]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Iqaluit]]\n[[Category:WAAS reference stations]]\n[[Category:Transport in Iqaluit]]\n[[Category:National Airports System]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1942]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Airport serving Iqaluit, Nunavut, Canada}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Iqaluit Airport\n| image =Iqaluit-airport.jpg\n| caption = The old terminal\n| IATA = YFB\n| ICAO = CYFB\n| WMO = 71909\n| type = Public\n| owner = Government of Nunavut<ref name=\"NAS\"/>\n| operator = Nunavut Airport Services Ltd.\n| city-served = \n| hub =\n*[[Canadian North]]\n| location = [[Iqaluit]], [[Nunavut]]\n| timezone = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc = [[UTC\u221205:00]]\n| summer = EDT\n| utcs = [[UTC\u221204:00]]\n| elevation-f = 110\n| coordinates = {{coord|63|45|24|N|068|33|22|W|region:CA-NU|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Canada Nunavut\n| pushpin_label = CYFB\n| r1-number = 16/34\n| r1-length-f = 8,605\n| r1-surface = Asphalt\n| stat-year = 2011/2010\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 120,040\n| stat2-header = Aircraft movements\n| stat2-data = 20,178\n| footnotes = Sources: [[Canada Flight Supplement]]<ref name=\"CFS\">{{CFS}}</ref><br>[[Environment Canada]]<ref>[http://climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca/prods_servs/metstat1_e.html Synoptic/Metstat Station Information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627233755/http://climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca/prods_servs/metstat1_e.html |date=2013-06-27 }}</ref><br>Movements from [[Statistics Canada]]<ref name=\"move\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/51-209-x/2011001/t001-eng.htm|title=Aircraft Movement Statistics: NAV CANADA Towers and Flight Service Stations: Annual Report (TP 577): Table 2-2 \u2014 Total aircraft movements by class of operation \u2014 NAV CANADA flight service stations|website=www.statcan.gc.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20121123105343/http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/51-209-x/2011001/t001-eng.htm|archivedate=23 November 2012}}</ref>}}\n'''Iqaluit Airport''' {{Airport codes|YFB|CYFB}} serves [[Iqaluit]], [[Nunavut]], Canada and is located adjacent to the city. It is operated by the [[government of Nunavut]]. It hosts [[Airline|scheduled passenger service]] from [[Ottawa]], [[Montreal]], [[Rankin Inlet]], and [[Kuujjuaq]] on carriers such as [[Canadian North]], and from smaller communities throughout eastern Nunavut. It is also used as a [[forward operating base]] by the [[CF-18 Hornet]]. In 2011, the terminal handled more than 120,000 passengers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edt.gov.nu.ca/apps/UPLOADS/fck/file/Iqaluit_Airport_four_pager.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418160816/http://www.edt.gov.nu.ca/apps/UPLOADS/fck/file/Iqaluit_Airport_four_pager.pdf |archivedate=2014-04-18 }}</ref>\n\nThe airport is classified as an [[airport of entry]] by [[Nav Canada]] and is staffed by the [[Canada Border Services Agency]] (CBSA). CBSA officers at this airport can handle [[general aviation]] aircraft only, with no more than 15 passengers.<ref name=\"CFS\"/>\n\nThe airport serves as a [[diversion airport]] on [[polar route]]s.<ref name=\"Map of Polar Routes Diversion Airports\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/aeromagazine/aero_16/polar_fig3.html|title=Figure 3. Boeing-Conducted Airport Safety And Operational Assessments|website=www.boeing.com|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013235137/http://www.boeing.com/commercial/aeromagazine/aero_16/polar_fig3.html|archivedate=13 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/aeromagazine/aero_16/polar_fig1.html|title=Figure 1. New Cross-Polar Routes Via The North Polar Region|website=www.boeing.com|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923164056/http://www.boeing.com/commercial/aeromagazine/aero_16/polar_fig1.html|archivedate=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe airport is owned by the Government of Nunavut (GN)<ref name=\"NAS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tc.gc.ca/programs/Airports/Status/menu.htm|title=The page has moved - La page a \u00e9t\u00e9 d\u00e9m\u00e9nag\u00e9e|website=www.tc.gc.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224638/http://www.tc.gc.ca/eng/programs/airports-status-menu-441.htm|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref> and operated, under a 30-year contract, by Nunavut Airport Services. The company is a subsidiary of Winnipeg Airport Services Corporation, which in turn is a subsidiary of Winnipeg Airports Authority.<ref>[http://www.waa.ca/waa/wasco Winnipeg Airport Services Corporation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211063920/http://www.waa.ca/waa/wasco |date=2016-12-11 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Military use===\nDuring late July 1941, a [[United States Army Air Forces]] (USAAF) team headed by Captain [[Elliott Roosevelt]] investigated the [[Frobisher Bay]] region for a potential airport for use in trans-Atlantic air traffic. Roosevelt's report designated a marginal site at Cape Rammelsberg for later construction. In mid-October, trawlers ''Lark'', ''Polarbjoern'', and ''Selis'' reached the vicinity, but owing to inaccurate charts (dating from the 1865 expedition of [[Charles Francis Hall]]) could not find the Roosevelt site. Instead, an eight-man crew commanded by USAAF Captain John T. Crowell was offloaded on a smaller island \"about eight miles southeast of the headland Captain Roosevelt had recommended.\"<ref>Forbes, 59\u201365</ref> They operated a weather/radio station over the winter. The expedition reported that \"this island is reported to be some 400 feet high and very level on top providing a natural runway of more than a mile in length.\" The ships left on 5 November.<ref>Hubbard Report</ref>\n\nWhen the station relief and base construction expedition arrived next July, both the Crowell and Roosevelt sites were rejected in favour of a level meadow discovered along the Sylvia Grinnell River on mainland [[Baffin Island]]. On 30 July, ships ''Polaris'' and ''[[Effie M. Morrissey]]'' anchored in what was then called Koojesse Inlet and began surveying the area: \"The terrain was excellent, with level ground extending nearly the entire 6,000 feet needed for an ample runway...The harbor, readily accessible from the bay, offered a good anchorage for ships of any size that would come in.\"<ref>Forbes, 71</ref> The expedition consisted further of the [[USS Bear (1874)|USCGC ''Bear'']], equipped with a seaplane, the transports ''Fairfax'' and ''Eleanor'' and some smaller vessels. Having offloaded the airport construction crews and materials, the expedition left at the end of September.\n[[File:Frobisher Bay, Baffin Island, aeronautical chart section.jpg|thumb|Frobisher Bay airport approaches with original station sites noted. USDOD ONC D-15, 1971]]\n\n===World War II===\nBy summer of 1943, the airbase at Koojesse Inlet had \"grown to look like a populous village\" and was in use by many aircraft.<ref>Forbes, 116</ref> It was designated Crystal II and referred to as ''Chaplet'' in coded communications. It was one of three \"Crystal\" weather sites in the Canadian Arctic Region, [[Kuujjuaq|Fort Chimo]] (now Kuujjuaq), [[Quebec]] being \"Crystal I\", and a station on [[Padloping Island]] being \"Crystal III\". A detachment of the 8th Weather Squadron, [[Air Transport Command (United States Air Force)|Air Transport Command]] (ATC) took up residence at the station on October 1, 1942.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/076/387.xml|title=USAFHRA Document 00076387|website=airforcehistoryindex.org|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724230904/http://airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/076/387.xml|archivedate=24 July 2011}}</ref> The initial mission of the Crystal sites was to provide long-range weather information to the combat forces then building up in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\nAs part of the [[Crimson Route|Crimson East]] air route network, the airfield at Crystal II was referred to by USAAF Air Transport Command as ATC Station #10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/180/777.xml|title=USAFHRA Document 00180777|website=airforcehistoryindex.org|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724230910/http://airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/180/777.xml|archivedate=24 July 2011}}</ref> It was intended to be a transport hub between the Eastern Route, which originated at [[Presque Isle Air Force Base|Presque Isle Army Airfield]], Maine and the Central Route, which originated at [[Detroit Metropolitan Wayne County Airport|Romulus Army Airfield]] (Detroit Airport), Michigan. The original plan, briefed by Captain Roosevelt to USAAF Chief [[Henry H. Arnold|Henry \"Hap\" Arnold]] and others at the [[Argentia]] summit in August 1941, called for Frobisher Bay to be a node in a northern alternate air route, running from [[Churchill, Manitoba]] via [[Southampton Island]] over Frobisher to [[Sondrestrom Air Base|Bluie West Eight]] and [[Bluie East Two]] in Greenland, rejoining the main route in Iceland.<ref>Hansen, 199\u2013200, 211\u2013215</ref> The later success of the main air route via [[Narsarsuaq Air Base|Bluie West One]] and the spring 1943 victory in the [[Battle of the Atlantic]] led to cancelation of the Crimson project in late 1943, and the associated airfields were reduced to weather, communications, and logistics duties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/076/350.xml|title=AFHRA Document 00076350|website=airforcehistoryindex.org|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811063933/http://airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/076/350.xml|archivedate=11 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe use of Frobisher Bay declined with the end of World War II, with jurisdiction of the facility being transferred to [[Military Air Transport Service]] (MATS) in 1948, under its [[Air Weather Service]]. During the 1950s it continued to be used as a transit point by the  \n[[United States]] and Canada. The base was closed in 1963 and converted into a civilian airport.\n\n===Civilian use===\nSince the 1950s, Frobisher Bay had earned a reputation{{by whom|date=July 2018}} as a [[wiktionary:technical stop|technical stop]] for airlines flying the [[Atlantic Ocean|North Atlantic]]. Crews departing westward from [[Glasgow Prestwick Airport|Prestwick]] or [[Shannon Airport|Shannon]] in those years preferred to route via [[Iceland]] (or the [[Azores]]) to [[Gander International Airport|Gander]], thence to [[New York City]] or elsewhere. Weather, however, could dictate a northerly course, which is when Frobisher Bay came into its own. In 1959 [[Pan American World Airways|Pan American]] even had a base there and on at least two occasions had to change engines on [[Douglas DC-7]]Cs at Frobisher Bay.\n\nWith the introduction of the intercontinental [[Boeing 707]] and [[Douglas DC-8]], fewer airlines stopped at Iqaluit. Even so, there always seemed to be some activity.{{according to|date=July 2018}} The place remained prominent as a regional airport, continued in its strategic role of sustaining the [[Distant Early Warning Line]] (DEW), supported the occasional military exercise or scientific expedition, and was still{{when|date=July 2018}} a key stopover on the North Atlantic ferry route.\n\nThrough the 1960s, [[Nordair]] was the main airline serving Frobisher Bay from Montreal, {{Convert|1100|NM}} to the south. [[Douglas DC-4]]s operated into the 1970s and [[Lockheed Corporation|Lockheed]] [[Lockheed Constellation|Super Constellation]]s between 1964 and 1969. In 1968 Nordair introduced the [[Boeing 737|Boeing 737-200]] on the Frobisher Bay run. At the same time, Bradley Air Services had been expanding. By the 1970s, the company's fleet of [[de Havilland Canada]] [[de Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter|DHC-6 Twin Otter]]s and [[Douglas DC-3]]s was serving many small [[Arctic]] communities from YFB, carrying passengers, mail, groceries, and other essentials. Bradley became known as First Air in 1973 and soon added [[Hawker Siddeley HS 748|BAe 748]]s.\n\nIn the 1980s, Canada's airline industry was in transition, with [[Air Canada]] and [[Canadian Airlines]] rapidly buying up regional operators. Air Canada acquired Nordair in 1977, and then sold it in 1984 to Canadian Airlines. Jet service to Iqaluit Airport continued, but under the [[Canadian North]] banner, which was, after the buyout of Canadian Airlines by Air Canada, to continue operations as an independent airline, jointly owned by the [[Inuit]] of the [[Northwest Territories]] and Nunavut. Between 1985 and 1988 First Air added four [[Boeing 727]]s to link Montreal and Ottawa with Iqaluit. Meanwhile, Canadian Airlines failed, and was taken over by Air Canada in 2000. In 1995 First Air purchased the small [[Yellowknife]]-based carrier, Ptarmigan Airways; then, in 1997, Northwest Territorial Airways (NWT Air), Air Canada's Yellowknife subsidiary. In acquiring NWT Air First Air obtained two 737-200 [[Combi aircraft|Combi]]s and a Lockheed [[Lockheed L-100 Hercules|382 Hercules]].<ref>''Airways'' (June 2006) ''Pages 24-28'' ''YFB and First Air''</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n*2 hangar/cargo terminals (Canadian North) - hangar was terminal building until 1986<ref name=\"chriswindeyer.com\">{{cite web|url=https://chriswindeyer.com/writing/the-new-iqaluit-airport/|title=Protected Blog \u203a Log in|author=|date=|website=chriswindeyer.com|accessdate=4 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107023956/https://chriswindeyer.com/writing/the-new-iqaluit-airport/|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*1 two-storey terminal building c. 1986<ref name=\"chriswindeyer.com\"/>\n*1 main runway\n*three aprons\n*1 FBO (Frobisher Bay Touchdown Services)\n*administration and control tower (former terminal)\n\nIqaluit International Airport Fire Department operates one crash tender for local fire suppression and has support from [[Iqaluit Fire Department]] when needed.\n\n==Terminal==\nThe main terminal (c.1986) has:\n*Check-in desks\n*3 gates\n*1 baggage claim belt\n*Gift shop\n*Travel agent\n*Tourist help desk\n*Car rental\n*Taxi service/rank\n*Baby/parent room\n*Disabled access/facilities\n*30 short term parking spaces\n* display cases for local artwork\n\nAs a result of increased traffic, limited post-security waiting area<ref name=\"case study\">{{cite journal |first=Catherine |last=Kloepfer |title=An airport public\u2013private partnership in the Canadian Arctic |url=https://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/hsp/cam/2017/00000011/00000002/art00004 |publisher=Journal of Airport Management |year=2017 |volume=11 |issue=2 |pages=136\u2013146 |journal= |access-date=2019-04-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421044303/https://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/hsp/cam/2017/00000011/00000002/art00004 |archive-date=2019-04-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> and subsiding taxiway,<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Greg A. |last1=Oldenborger |first2=Anne-Marie |last2=LeBlanc |title=Geophysical characterization of permafrost terrain at Iqaluit International Airport, Nunavut |journal=Journal of Applied Geophysics |year=2015 |volume=123 |pages=36\u201349 |doi=10.1016/j.jappgeo.2015.09.016}}</ref> the Nunavut government planned an overhaul of the airport that was expected to cost $250\u2013300 million. The project was a [[public\u2013private partnership]] with the GN borrowing their half of the cost. Nunavut Airport Services will operate the airport for 30 years. Upgrades included:\n* new {{convert|100,000|ft2|abbr=on}} terminal building constructed by [[Bouygues]]<ref>[http://www.bouygues.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/bouygues_2015_registration_document1.pdf 2015 Registration Document] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604033152/http://www.bouygues.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/bouygues_2015_registration_document1.pdf |date=2016-06-04 }} page 36</ref>\n* retrofitting the current terminal which will become solely an administration building and control tower\n* expanding parking lots\n* new combined services building to house all airport and safety vehicles\n* a second taxiway \n* apron and repaving the runway.\n\nThe construction began in 2014 and was completed on August 8, 2017, with flight service beginning the following day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/story/2012/07/06/north-iqaluit-airport-rennovations.html |title=Iqaluit airport to be overhauled by 2017 |publisher=CBC |date=2012-07-06 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707161441/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/story/2012/07/06/north-iqaluit-airport-rennovations.html |archivedate=2012-07-07 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674new_public-private_iqaluit_airport_to_cost_up_to_300_million/ |title=New public-private Iqaluit airport to cost up to $300 million |newspaper=Nunatsiaq News |date=2012-07-06 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216004226/http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674new_public-private_iqaluit_airport_to_cost_up_to_300_million/ |archivedate=2014-12-16 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://nationtalk.ca/story/new-iqaluit-international-airport-terminal-opening/ |title=New Iqaluit International Airport terminal opening |publisher=NationTalk |date=2017-08-08 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029065843/http://nationtalk.ca/story/new-iqaluit-international-airport-terminal-opening |archivedate=2017-10-29 }}</ref> On September 5, 2015, during construction, a large fire caused major damage to the roof of the new terminal, costing an estimated $1 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/iqaluit-airport-fire-damage-1.3222831 |title=Iqaluit airport terminal fire damage estimated at $1M |publisher=CBC |date=2015-09-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811101405/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/iqaluit-airport-fire-damage-1.3222831 |archivedate=2016-08-11 }}</ref> Aside from the fire, other challenges encountered in the construction include thawing permafrost, electricity demands, housing for construction workers, extreme cold temperatures and short daylight hours in winter, and advanced planning to take advantage of summer sea lifts to lower the delivery cost of construction materials.<ref name=\"case study\" />\n\nThe new terminal has:\n*16 Check-in desks<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluits_new_airport_big_bold_and_beautiful/|title=Nunatsiaq News 2017-05-29: NEWS: Iqaluit's new airport: big, bold and beautiful|website=www.nunatsiaqonline.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112222908/http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluits_new_airport_big_bold_and_beautiful/|archivedate=12 January 2018}}</ref>\n* 5 gates<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\"/>\n* 2 baggage claim carousel<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\"/>\n* departures conveyor belt to carry baggage to screening area<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\"/>\n* caf\u00e9<ref name=\"cbc.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/iqaluit-airport-opens-1.4239486|title=Iqaluit's new $300M airport opens today - CBC News|website=cbc.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121233311/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/iqaluit-airport-opens-1.4239486|archivedate=21 November 2017}}</ref>\n* Passenger waiting lounge<ref name=\"cbc.ca\"/>\n* Store<ref name=\"cbc.ca\"/>\n* Gift shop<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\"/>\n* Travel agent desk\n* Tourist help desk\n* Car rental desk\n* Taxi service\n* Parenting room\n* Central rotunda<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\"/>\n* Accessible entrance and gates\n* 100 parking spaces<ref name=\"nunatsiaqonline.ca\"/>\n* Art work: Kenojuak Ashevak's Enchanted Owl - mural in the rotunda and Duffell wall hangings<ref name=\"cbc.ca\"/>\n\n==Other information==\nOver the years several international flights have been diverted to Iqaluit due to technical reasons,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/flight-from-zurich-to-l-a-diverts-to-iqaluit-after-engine-shuts-down-1.3267034|title=Flight from Zurich to L.A. diverts to Iqaluit after engine shuts down|date=1 February 2017|website=ctvnews.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029082757/http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/flight-from-zurich-to-l-a-diverts-to-iqaluit-after-engine-shuts-down-1.3267034|archivedate=29 October 2017}}</ref> [[air rage]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/passenger-diverted-aeroflot-flight-iqaluit-plea-1.3964618|title=Accused passenger from diverted Aeroflot flight tries to plead guilty - CBC News|website=cbc.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217135525/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/passenger-diverted-aeroflot-flight-iqaluit-plea-1.3964618|archivedate=17 February 2017}}</ref> or on-board medical emergencies with no deaths being reported.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/moscow-to-l-a-flight-makes-emergency-landing-in-iqaluit-1.3257521?cmp=rss |title=Moscow to L.A. flight makes emergency landing in Iqaluit |publisher=CBC |date=2015-10-05 |accessdate=2015-10-06 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151113223759/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/moscow-to-l-a-flight-makes-emergency-landing-in-iqaluit-1.3257521?cmp=rss |archivedate=2015-11-13 }}</ref> On 31 May 1996, [[Virgin Atlantic Airways|Virgin Atlantic]] flight 7 from [[London]] to [[Los Angeles]] made an [[emergency landing]] at Iqaluit after a passenger had a heart attack. The landing was executed safely - the first [[Boeing 747]] ever to attempt to land at Iqaluit - but one of the 747's engines hit a fuel pump on the tarmac as it was taxiing, causing serious damage to the aircraft and a potentially dangerous fuel spill. The 397 stranded passengers, including singer [[Gary Barlow]], were flown out after Virgin Atlantic chartered two jets. The passengers, after spending 16 hours in a local [[curling]] rink, were taken to New York to catch connecting flights to Los Angeles. [[Prince Michael of Kent]], who had also been on the flight, was given a [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] escort and departed on an earlier scheduled flight. The original aircraft had its engines repaired and left four days after the accident. The heart-attack victim survived.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/back-issues/week/60607.html#7|title=Unexpected Arctic stop for Brits, Yanks|website=nunatsiaq.com|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514054733/http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/back-issues/week/60607.html#7|archivedate=14 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Airbus A380 in Iqaluit 02.jpg|thumb|Airbus A380 at Iqaluit]]\nThe [[Airbus A380]], the world's largest passenger jet, conducted cold weather testing from Iqaluit Airport during February 2006 - its first North American visit. They were hoping to experience {{convert|-25|C|0}} weather to determine the effects on cabin temperatures and engine performance. Nunavut authorities hope that the importance of these tests will put Iqaluit on the map as a centre for cold-weather testing.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2006/02/10/airbus060310.html |title=Jumbo Airbus getting cold, and more, during Iqaluit tests |publisher=CBC |date=2006-02-10 |accessdate =2010-04-12}}</ref> In February 2013, [[Airbus Military]] used the airport to test the [[Airbus A400M Atlas]] military transport aircraft that is currently being developed.<ref>[http://www.airbusmilitary.com/LatestNews/tabid/176/ArticleID/250/ArtMID/681/Airbus-Military-A400M-undergoes-latest-cold-weather-tests.aspx Airbus Military A400M undergoes latest cold weather tests] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130321215847/http://www.airbusmilitary.com/LatestNews/tabid/176/ArticleID/250/ArtMID/681/Airbus-Military-A400M-undergoes-latest-cold-weather-tests.aspx |date=2013-03-21 }}</ref> The city government sent a delegation to [[Paris Airshow]] in June 2013 to promote Iqaluit as an ideal location for these tests. [[Airbus A350]] followed suit and conducted its cold weather testing in January 2014. Airport staff cited low landing fee, sufficient runway length, and minimal air traffic movement all helped in the decision making.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/airbus-s-new-a350-in-iqaluit-for-cold-weather-testing-1.2512504 |title=Airbus's new A350 in Iqaluit for cold weather testing |date=2014-01-27 |publisher=CBC News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140131194653/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/airbus-s-new-a350-in-iqaluit-for-cold-weather-testing-1.2512504 |archivedate=2014-01-31 }}</ref> Following from these previous successful visits by prototype Airbus aircraft, the company sent the first [[A320neo]] with [[CFM International LEAP]] engines to be tested in January 2016. As part of the type's first visit to [[North America]], the jet performed several circuits in the subzero temperatures before departing back to [[Toulouse\u2013Blagnac Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/airbus-a320neo-cold-test-iqaluit-1.3422936 |title=Airbus cold-weather tests its A320neo in Iqaluit |date=2016-01-28 |publisher=CBC News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205100815/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/airbus-a320neo-cold-test-iqaluit-1.3422936 |archivedate=2017-02-05 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2005 the Government of Nunavut announced that it would spend $40 million to repair the runway, build a new emergency services facility and a new terminal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/51216/news/nunavut/51216_11.html|title=Nunatsiaq News|website=nunatsiaq.com|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20060206222721/http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/51216/news/nunavut/51216_11.html|archivedate=6 February 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012 [[Air Greenland]] announced that a 1-hour, 45-minute flight from [[Nuuk]] to Iqaluit, down from three days when going via Copenhagen or Reykjavik and then on to Ottawa, would begin 18 June 2012, later changed to 15 June. The service was a partnership with [[First Air]] who provided ticketing and other services in Iqaluit. This was the first international flight into Iqaluit since 2001 when First Air discontinued its Iqaluit to [[Kangerlussuaq]] flights. Air Greenland used [[Bombardier Dash 8|Dash 8]] aircraft on the run.<ref name=\"agcbc\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/story/2012/06/07/north-greenland-first-air.html | title=Air Greenland teams with First Air for Iqaluit flights | date=8 June 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120610195403/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/story/2012/06/07/north-greenland-first-air.html | archivedate=10 June 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"agpr\">{{cite news|url=http://www.airgreenland.com/nyhedsvisning/?newsid=1030 |work=Air Greenland |title=Air Greenland opens summer-route to Canada |date=18 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518084537/http://www.airgreenland.com/nyhedsvisning/?newsid=1030 |archivedate=18 May 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluit-nuuk_flights_ready_for_june_15_take-off/|title=Nunatsiaq News 2012-05-28: NEWS: Iqaluit-Nuuk service ready for June 15 take-off|website=www.nunatsiaqonline.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213202304/http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluit-nuuk_flights_ready_for_june_15_take-off|archivedate=13 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluit_welcomes_new_air_link/|title=Nunatsiaq News 2012-01-18: NEWS: Tireless lobbying led to Iqaluit-Greenland air link revival|website=www.nunatsiaqonline.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213025756/http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluit_welcomes_new_air_link/|archivedate=13 February 2018}}</ref> After three years in place the service was discontinued for the 2015 season.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/air-greenland-cuts-nuuk-iqaluit-scheduled-flights-in-2015-1.2985006 | title=Air Greenland cuts Nuuk-Iqaluit scheduled flights in 2015 | date=6 March 2015 | publisher=CBC News | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115142652/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/air-greenland-cuts-nuuk-iqaluit-scheduled-flights-in-2015-1.2985006 | archivedate=15 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n\n===Passenger===\n{{airport-dest-list\n| [[Air Nunavut]] | '''Charter:'''  [[Arctic Bay Airport|Arctic Bay]], [[Cape Dorset Airport|Cape Dorset]], [[Clyde River Airport|Clyde River]], [[Hall Beach Airport|Hall Beach]], [[Igloolik Airport|Igloolik]], [[Mary River Aerodrome|Mary River]], [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Pierre Elliott Trudeau International Airport|Montr\u00e9al\u2013Trudeau]], [[Nuuk Airport|Nuuk]], [[Ottawa Airport|Ottawa]], [[Pangnirtung Airport|Pangnirtung]], [[Pond Inlet Airport|Pond Inlet]], [[Qikiqtarjuaq Airport|Qikiqtarjuaq]], [[Rankin Inlet Airport|Rankin Inlet]], [[Resolute Bay Airport|Resolute]], [[Yellowknife Airport|Yellowknife]]\n| {{nowrap|[[Canadian North]]}} | [[Arctic Bay Airport|Arctic Bay]], [[Cape Dorset Airport|Cape Dorset]], [[Clyde River Airport|Clyde River]], [[Edmonton International Airport|Edmonton]], [[Hall Beach Airport|Hall Beach]], [[Igloolik Airport|Igloolik]], [[Kimmirut Airport|Kimmirut]], [[Kuujjuaq Airport|Kuujjuaq]], [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Trudeau International Airport|Montreal\u2013Trudeau]], [[Ottawa Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport|Ottawa]], [[Pangnirtung Airport|Pangnirtung]], [[Pond Inlet Airport|Pond Inlet]], [[Qikiqtarjuaq Airport|Qikiqtarjuaq]], [[Rankin Inlet Airport|Rankin Inlet]], [[Resolute Bay Airport|Resolute Bay]], [[Yellowknife Airport|Yellowknife]]<ref>[https://canadiannorth.com/plan_your_trip/flight-schedule/?type=full#skedsearchform Full network schedule]</ref>\n| [[Chrono Aviation]] | '''Charter:''' [[Montreal Saint-Hubert Longueuil Airport|Montr\u00e9al/Saint-Hubert Airport]], [[Mary River Aerodrome|Mary River]]\n| {{nowrap|[[Nolinor Aviation]]}} | '''Charter:''' [[Region of Waterloo International Airport|Kitchener/Waterloo]], [[Mary River Aerodrome|Mary River]]\n}}\n\n[[Air Canada]] had operated service to Ottawa and Montreal from March 2010 to August 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluit_flyers_say_theyll_miss_air_canada/|title=Nunatsiaq News 2011-07-05: NEWS: Iqaluit flyers say they'll miss Air Canada|website=www.nunatsiaqonline.ca|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107012133/http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674iqaluit_flyers_say_theyll_miss_air_canada/|archivedate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAir Baffin began as chartered service in 1989, as a schedule airline in 1992 and renamed as Air Nunavut in 1996.\n\n[[Air Greenland]] had operated service to Nuuk, Greenland in 2012, 2013 and 2014.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/air-greenland-cuts-nuuk-iqaluit-scheduled-flights-in-2015-1.2985006</ref>\n\n=== Cargo ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Airlines\n!Destinations\n|-\n|[[Canadian North]]\n|[[Ottawa Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport|Ottawa]]\n|-\n|[[Cargojet|Cargojet Airways]]\n|[[Winnipeg James Armstrong Richardson International Airport|Winnipeg]]\n|-\n|[[Purolator Inc.|Purolator Courier]] operated by [[Cargojet|Cargojet Airways]]\n|[[Calgary International Airport|Calgary]]\n|}\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n*On 12 February 1973, [[Douglas C-47|Douglas C-47A]] C-FOOV of [[Kenting Atlas Aviation]] crashed on approach. The aircraft was on a ferry flight to [[Resolute Bay Airport]] when power was lost shortly after take-off from Iqaluit and the decision was made to return. All three people on board survived.<ref name=ASN120273>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19730212-0 |title=CF-OOV Accident description |website=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=26 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20100826181146/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19730212-0 |archivedate=26 August 2010 }}</ref>\n*On 14 August 1996, a [[Canadian Forces]] [[CF-18 Hornet]] left the runway during [[takeoff]], slid down an embankment and ruptured a fuel pipeline. The aircraft caught fire, as did fuel spilling from the pipeline, however the pilot had ejected just as the plane left the runway and only suffered a broken ankle. The pipeline was shut down and the fire brought under control in less than an hour.<ref>[http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/back-issues/week/60816.html#1 Pilot ejects in nick of time as CF-18 crashes while attempting to take off.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107084849/http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/back-issues/week/60816.html |date=2007-11-07 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Can-arpt-wx|CYFB|Iqaluit Airport}}\n*[http://polarpilots.ca: Website of local private pilot group based at CYFB]\n\n{{List of airports in Canada}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Certified airports in the Qikiqtaaluk Region]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Iqaluit]]\n[[Category:WAAS reference stations]]\n[[Category:Transport in Iqaluit]]\n[[Category:National Airports System]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1942]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Cybereyev", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCivilian use", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iqaluit_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Chronic bee paralysis virus", "text_new": "{{Taxobox\n| virus_group = iv\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| ordo = [[Picornavirales]]\n| familia = N/A\n| genus = N/A\n| species = '''Chronic bee paralysis virus'''\n}}\n'''Chronic bee paralysis satellite virus (CBPV)''', not to be confused with [[slow bee paralysis virus]] (SBPV) or [[acute bee paralysis virus]] (ABPV), commonly affects adult [[Apis mellifera cypria|''Apis mellifera'']] honey bees and causes a chronic paralysis that can easily spread to other members of a colony. Bees infected with CBPV begin to show symptoms after 5 days and die a few days after<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bailey|first=L.|last2=Ball|first2=B. V.|last3=Perry|first3=J. N.|date=January 1983|title=Honeybee Paralysis: Its Natural Spread and its Diminished Incidence in England and Wales|journal=Journal of Apicultural Research|volume=22|issue=3|pages=191\u2013195|doi=10.1080/00218839.1983.11100586|issn=0021-8839}}</ref>. Chronic bee paralysis virus infection is a factor that can contribute to or cause the sudden collapse of honeybee colonies<ref name=\":4\">{{cite journal|last1=Olivier|first1=Violaine|last2=Blanchard|first2=Philippe|last3=Chaouch|first3=Soraya|last4=Lallemand|first4=Perrine|last5=Schurr|first5=Frank|last6=Celle|first6=Olivier|last7=Dubois|first7=Eric|last8=Tordo|first8=No\u00ebl|last9=Thi\u00e9ry|first9=Richard|last10=Houlgatte|first10=R\u00e9mi|last11=Ribi\u00e8re|first11=Magali|title=Molecular characterisation and phylogenetic analysis of chronic bee paralysis virus, a honey bee virus|journal=Virus Research|date=March 2008|volume=132|issue=1\u20132|pages=59\u201368|doi=10.1016/j.virusres.2007.10.014|pmid=18079012}}</ref>. Since honeybees serve comprise a vital force in [[ecological resilience]], it is important to understand factors and diseases that threaten them.\n\nAlthough CBPV infects mainly adult bees, the virus can also infect bees in earlier developmental stages, though developing bees typically have significantly lower viral loads compared to their adult counterparts. Death as a result of CBPV infection in developing bees or brood losses due to viral infection are low or nonexistent<ref name=\"ribiere magali\">{{cite journal|last1=Ribi\u00e8re|first1=Magali|last2=Olivier|first2=Violaine|last3=Blanchard|first3=Philippe|date=January 2010|title=Chronic bee paralysis: A disease and a virus like no other?|journal=[[Journal of Invertebrate Pathology]]|volume=103|pages=S120\u2013S131|doi=10.1016/j.jip.2009.06.013|pmid=19909978}}</ref>.\n\nBees that have been infected with CBPV may harbor millions of viral particles, with half of them concentrated in the head region of the infected honey bee. As a result, the virus has [[Neurotropic virus|neurotropic]] activity, allowing the virus to cause nervous system damage in infected honey bees. Specifically, research has identified that viral particles concentrate primarily in two centers of the brain to replicate after infecting the host. The first replication center is the [[mushroom bodies]], which play a role in sensory processing, memory, learning, and motor control, and the second replication center the central body, the center of the [[supraesophageal ganglion|insect brain]] that primarily control locomotion, behavior, bodily orientation, and arousal<ref name=\"ribiere magali\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|last1=Bailey|first1=L.|last2=Milne|first2=R. G.|title=The multiplication regions and interaction of acute and chronic bee-paralysis viruses in adult honey bees|journal=[[Journal of General Virology]]|date=1 January 1969|volume=4|issue=1|pages=9\u201314|doi=10.1099/0022-1317-4-1-9|doi-access=free}}</ref>.\n\n== Virology ==\nChronic bee paralysis virus shares similarities to the virus families ''[[Nodaviridae]]'' and ''[[Tombusviridae]]'', but CBPV is distinct enough from the two existing families and consequently is considered a new family of viruses. As a result, CBPV has yet to be fully classified.<ref name=Chevin2015>Aurore Chevin, Bruno Coutard, Philippe Blanchard, Anne-Sophie Dabert-Gay, Magali Ribi\u00e8re-Chabert, Richard Thi\u00e9ry: [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4488741/ Characterisation of Structural Proteins from Chronic Bee Paralysis Virus (CBPV) Using Mass Spectrometry], in: Viruses. 2015 Jun; 7(6): 3329\u20133344. [[doi:10.3390/v7062774]], {{PMC|4488741}}, {{PMID|26110588}}</ref><ref name=\"Olivier 59\u201368\" /> \nChronic bee paralysis virus is a [[Positive-sense single-stranded RNA virus|single-stranded positive-RNA]] virus with five fragments, two large fragments and three small fragments<ref name=\"Olivier 59\u201368\">{{Cite journal|last=Olivier|first=Violaine|last2=Blanchard|first2=Philippe|last3=Chaouch|first3=Soraya|last4=Lallemand|first4=Perrine|last5=Schurr|first5=Frank|last6=Celle|first6=Olivier|last7=Dubois|first7=Eric|last8=Tordo|first8=No\u00ebl|last9=Thi\u00e9ry|first9=Richard|last10=Houlgatte|first10=R\u00e9mi|last11=Ribi\u00e8re|first11=Magali|date=March 2008|title=Molecular characterisation and phylogenetic analysis of Chronic bee paralysis virus, a honey bee virus|journal=Virus Research|volume=132|issue=1\u20132|pages=59\u201368|doi=10.1016/j.virusres.2007.10.014|pmid=18079012}}</ref>. The first large fragment is suspected to encode an [[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase]], as it possesses 8 conserved domains of an RNA-dependent RNA polymerase<ref name=\"ribiere magali\" />. The second large fragment is thought to encode for the virus [[Capsid|capsid protein]], which is reported to be a capsid protein of 23.5 kDa and four polypeptides of 75, 50, 30 and 20 kDa<ref>{{Citation|last=Bailey|first=L.|chapter=Viruses Attacking the Honey Bee|date=1976|pages=271\u2013304|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-12-039820-1|doi=10.1016/s0065-3527(08)60507-2|pmid=775948|title=Advances in Virus Research Volume 20|volume=20|series=Advances in Virus Research}}</ref><ref name=\"Olivier 59\u201368\" /><ref>{{Citation|last=Ball|first=Brenda V.|title=HONEY BEE VIRUSES|date=1999|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Virology|pages=743\u2013749|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-12-227030-7|last2=Bailey|first2=Leslie|doi=10.1006/rwvi.1999.0139|chapter=Honey Bee Viruses}}</ref>.The virus capsid is hypothesized to have [[icosahedral symmetry]]<ref name=\"ribiere magali\" />.\n\n\nChronic bee paralysis virus is also found to facilitate the growth and reproduction of a satellite virus, called [[Chronic bee paralysis satellite virus|Chronic bee paralysis associate satellite virus]] (CBVA), which has three small (+) single-stranded RNA fragments. The three small (+) single-stranded RNA fragments appear inconsistently in the Chronic bee paralysis virus, which lends to the idea that the three RNAs are not components of CBPV but of a satellite virus that relies on CBPV activity in order to proliferate<ref name=\":4\" />. Additionally, the three small RNA fragments each have molecular weights of 0.35 x 10<sup>6</sup> (1100 nucleotides), which exactly matches the molecular weights of the three (+) ssRNA fragments of CBVA<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Overton|first=H. A.|last2=Buck|first2=K. W.|last3=Bailey|first3=L.|last4=Ball|first4=B. V.|date=1982-11-01|title=Relationships between the RNA Components of Chronic Bee-Paralysis Virus and those of Chronic Bee-Paralysis Virus Associate|journal=Journal of General Virology|volume=63|issue=1|pages=171\u2013179|doi=10.1099/0022-1317-63-1-171|issn=0022-1317|doi-access=free}}</ref>.\n\n== Infection and transmission ==\nChronic bee paralysis virus is transmitted through two main mechanisms. The first mechanism is viral transmission through bee feces, which remains on the hive floor and can be picked up on the furry legs of other bees and ingested orally<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ribi\u00e8re|first=M.|last2=Lallemand|first2=P.|last3=Iscache|first3=A.-L.|last4=Schurr|first4=F.|last5=Celle|first5=O.|last6=Blanchard|first6=P.|last7=Olivier|first7=V.|last8=Faucon|first8=J.-P.|date=2007-12-01|title=Spread of Infectious Chronic Bee Paralysis Virus by Honeybee (Apis mellifera L.) Feces|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|volume=73|issue=23|pages=7711\u20137716|doi=10.1128/AEM.01053-07|issn=0099-2240|pmid=17933946|pmc=2168079}}</ref>. The second mechanism is through close contact between bees in the hive. [[Worker bee|Worker bees]] are the most susceptible to infection, since they travel the hive most frequently. The infection may spread between hives as a result of indirect contact or direct contact between honey bees<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ribiere|first1=M.|last2=Lallemand|first2=P.|last3=Iscache|first3=A.-L.|last4=Schurr|first4=F.|last5=Celle|first5=O.|last6=Blanchard|first6=P.|last7=Olivier|first7=V.|last8=Faucon|first8=J.-P.|date=12 October 2007|title=Spread of infections chronic bee paralysis virus by honeybee (''Apis mellifera'' L.) feces|journal=[[Applied and Environmental Microbiology]]|volume=73|issue=23|pages=7711\u20137716|doi=10.1128/AEM.01053-07|pmc=2168079|pmid=17933946}}</ref>. [[Research]] shows that mainly adult honey bees can be infected with chronic bee paralysis virus by a topical contact with infected feces or by ingestion of [[Virus|virion]]-containing substances<ref name=\"ribiere magali\" />.\n\n=== Viral replication cycle ===\n\n==== Entry into cell ====\nChronic bee paralysis virus is transmitted to honey bees through a [[Omnipresence|ubiquitous]] [[Parasitism|parasite]] common to honey bee hives, Varroa mites (''[[Varroa jacobsoni]]''). Varroa mites are known to harbor many viruses for which honey bees are susceptible and permissive<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.honeybeesuite.com/chronic-bee-paralysis-virus/|title=Chronic bee paralysis virus|date=2010-08-18|website=Honey Bee Suite|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref>.The parasitic mites attach themselves to honey bees externally and feed off of the [[hemolymph]] of their hosts<ref name=\":2\" />. This exchange of fluids between the parasitic mites and the hosts allows for CBPV particles to enter fluid transfer systems in the honey bee body. The mechanisms by which chronic bee paralysis virus gains entry into honey bee cells is currently unknown.\n\n==== Replication ====\nLike other [[(+)ssRNA|positive sense single-stranded RNA viruses]], Chronic bee paralysis virus replicates in the [[cytoplasm]] of honeybee cells. The first large (+) RNA fragment in the CBPV [[genome]] likely encodes for an [[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase]], which makes many copies of viral RNA. After many copies of the genome have been produced, the honey bee host's cellular processes will translate the viral RNA into functional [[Protein|proteins]] which can cause propagation of the virus inside the host. The virus replicates at the highest levels in the head of the honeybee, reaching an average of 10<sup>7</sup> copies of the virus in an infected worker bee head and as many as 10<sup>11</sup> copies of the virus in an infected [[queen bee]] head. Chronic bee paralysis virus particles have been found to concentrate in two centers; in [[mushroom bodies]] which play a role in sensory processing, [[memory]], and learning as well as in the central body, which plays a vital role in coordinating movement. Loss of flying ability in honey bees as a result of CBPV infection can be attributed to neuron destruction in the central body. Erratic behavior in infected bees may be a result of mushroom body neuron destruction. \n\n==== Symptoms ====\nInfected honeybees will begin to show symptoms of the illness within five days of infection, and the infection presents in two distinct ways, with Type I infection being the more common of the two infection types. \n\nA Type I infected bee presents with a bloated abdomen due to a fluid-filled honey sac and weak or trembling wings. Type I infected honey bees tend to crawl on the ground or cluster near the entrance of the hive, as their weakened wings lead to an inability to fly.\n\nA Type II infected honey bee presents with complete abdominal hair loss, causing it to appear black and greasy. These bees are still able to fly 2-3 days after symptoms begin to appear, but they lose their ability to fly shortly before succumbing to the disease.\n\nA third type of infection that is a major contributor to the spread of the virus is an infection of CBPV in which the infected bee exhibits no symptoms of the illness. The infected bee does not present with any of the classic symptoms of the disease before death, and, as a result, is able to transmit the virus beyond its own hive.\n\n==== Treatment ====\nThere is no known treatment for the disease currently. Often, infections of chronic bee paralysis virus die out on their own, but infected bees, if detected, must be removed from the hive immediately to lessen the chances of the virus spreading. Supplementing a smaller hive that has been severely affected by the virus with healthy bees from another colony can prevent colony collapse in struggling hives. The infection commonly surges in the winters rather than warmer months, for unknown reasons<ref name=\":2\" />.\n\nTreating the hive against Varroa mites has also proven to be an effective preventive method against viral infection<ref name=\":2\" />. While bees should not be medicated against mites as a preventative measure because mites are quick to develop resistance; however, once detected, mites can be eliminated with the use of [[pesticides]]. Common pesticides include [[Apistan]], [[Formic acid|Formic Acid]], [[Thymol|Apiguard]]<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dummies.com/home-garden/hobby-farming/beekeeping/how-to-control-a-varroa-mite-problem-in-your-beehive/|title=How to Control a Varroa Mite Problem in Your Beehive|website=dummies|language=en|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref>. Home remedies for exterminating mites in a bee hive also include dusting the hive floors as well as the honey bees themselves with powdered sugar in order to suffocate the mites<ref name=\":3\" />. \n\n== Testing ==\nChronic bee paralysis virus is classified as an [[Subclinical infection|inapparent infection]] because there are few tell-tale symptoms that appear before the infection has progressed to a fatal degree. As many honey bees can become infected and either show symptoms days after the initial point of infection or fail to show any symptoms throughout the entire course of the illness, CBPV can infect entire hives before the virus is detected. Despite the use of [[infectivity]] and [[Serology|serological tests]], these testing methods are often inaccurate and difficult to reproduce with consistent results.<ref name=\"ribiere magali\" />\n\n== Symbiotic relationships ==\nAlthough Chronic bee paralysis virus mainly infects honey bees, the virus has also been found to replicate in two species of [[carnivore|carnivorous]] [[ant]], ''[[Camponotus vagus]]'' and ''[[Formica rufa]]''.These carnivorous ants become infected with CBPV through two mechanisms: eating decomposing bees who harbor the virus or by independently collecting infected honeydew.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite journal|last1=Celle|first1=Olivier|last2=Blanchard|first2=Philippe|last3=Olivier|first3=Violaine|last4=Schurr|first4=Frank|last5=Cougoule|first5=Nicolas|last6=Faucon|first6=Jean-Paul|last7=Ribi\u00e8re|first7=Magali|date=May 2008|title=Detection of chronic bee paralysis virus (CBPV) genome and its replicative RNA form in various hosts and possible ways of spread|url=https://hal-anses.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-00414769/file/Detection_of_Chronic_bee_paralysis_virus_in_various_hosts_version_HAL_210909.pdf|journal=Virus Research|volume=133|issue=2|pages=280\u2013284|doi=10.1016/j.virusres.2007.12.011|pmid=18243390}}</ref>  While the virus does not cause any symptoms in the carnivorous ants, the [[Commensalism|commensal relationship]] between the virus and the ants allows the ants to serve as a reservoir for viral replication to occur<ref name=\":5\" />. \n\nChronic bee paralysis virus is also similar to [[slow bee paralysis virus]] and [[acute bee paralysis virus]]. Though CBPV does not fall into the same family as the other two viruses, it bears similarities to the other viruses because it causes paralysis as the fatal symptom of the infection. Slow bee paralysis, in contrast to Chronic bee paralysis virus, causes paralysis of the front two pairs of legs on honey bees ([[Apis mellifera cypria|''Apis mellifera'']]), silkworms ([[Bombyx mori|''Bombyx mori'']]'')'', and bumble bees ([[Bombus sylvarum|''Bombis spp.'']]'')''. This paralysis eventually causes death in the infected insects. Slow bee paralysis virus is transmitted to hives through ''[[Varroa destructor]]'' mite infestations. Because of the similarities between the two viruses, Chronic bee paralysis virus is suspected to have the same mode of transmission.\n\nChronic bee paralysis virus is also seen to interact with satellite viruses. The three short RNA segments of the viral genome are thought to be a satellite virus<ref name=\":4\" />. Only in the presence of CBPV can the associated satellite virus proliferate.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q16662559}}\n\n[[Category:Bee diseases]]\n[[Category:Insect viral diseases]]\n[[Category:Positive-sense single-stranded RNA viruses]]\n[[Category:Beekeeping]]\n", "text_old": "{{Taxobox\n| virus_group = iv\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| ordo = [[Picornavirales]]\n| familia = N/A\n| genus = N/A\n| species = '''Chronic bee paralysis virus'''\n}}\n'''Chronic bee paralysis satellite virus (CBPV)''', not to be confused with [[slow bee paralysis virus]] (SBPV) or [[acute bee paralysis virus]] (ABPV), commonly affects adult [[Apis mellifera cypria|''Apis mellifera'']] honey bees and causes a chronic paralysis that can easily spread to other members of a colony. Bees infected with CBPV begin to show symptoms after 5 days and die a few days after<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bailey|first=L.|last2=Ball|first2=B. V.|last3=Perry|first3=J. N.|date=January 1983|title=Honeybee Paralysis: Its Natural Spread and its Diminished Incidence in England and Wales|journal=Journal of Apicultural Research|volume=22|issue=3|pages=191\u2013195|doi=10.1080/00218839.1983.11100586|issn=0021-8839}}</ref>. Chronic bee paralysis virus infection is a factor that can contribute to or cause the sudden collapse of honeybee colonies<ref name=\":4\">{{cite journal|last1=Olivier|first1=Violaine|last2=Blanchard|first2=Philippe|last3=Chaouch|first3=Soraya|last4=Lallemand|first4=Perrine|last5=Schurr|first5=Frank|last6=Celle|first6=Olivier|last7=Dubois|first7=Eric|last8=Tordo|first8=No\u00ebl|last9=Thi\u00e9ry|first9=Richard|last10=Houlgatte|first10=R\u00e9mi|last11=Ribi\u00e8re|first11=Magali|title=Molecular characterisation and phylogenetic analysis of chronic bee paralysis virus, a honey bee virus|journal=Virus Research|date=March 2008|volume=132|issue=1\u20132|pages=59\u201368|doi=10.1016/j.virusres.2007.10.014|pmid=18079012}}</ref>. Since honeybees serve comprise a vital force in [[ecological resilience]], it is important to understand factors and diseases that threaten them.\n\nAlthough CBPV infects mainly adult bees, the virus can also infect bees in earlier developmental stages, though developing bees typically have significantly lower viral loads compared to their adult counterparts. Death as a result of CBPV infection in developing bees or brood losses due to viral infection are low or nonexistent<ref name=\"ribiere magali\">{{cite journal|last1=Ribi\u00e8re|first1=Magali|last2=Olivier|first2=Violaine|last3=Blanchard|first3=Philippe|date=January 2010|title=Chronic bee paralysis: A disease and a virus like no other?|journal=[[Journal of Invertebrate Pathology]]|volume=103|pages=S120\u2013S131|doi=10.1016/j.jip.2009.06.013|pmid=19909978}}</ref>.\n\nBees that have been infected with CBPV may harbor millions of viral particles, with half of them concentrated in the head region of the infected honey bee. As a result, the virus has [[Neurotropic virus|neurotropic]] activity, allowing the virus to cause nervous system damage in infected honey bees. Specifically, research has identified that viral particles concentrate primarily in two centers of the brain to replicate after infecting the host. The first replication center is the [[mushroom bodies]], which play a role in sensory processing, memory, learning, and motor control, and the second replication center the central body, the center of the [[supraesophageal ganglion|insect brain]] that primarily control locomotion, behavior, bodily orientation, and arousal<ref name=\"ribiere magali\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|last1=Bailey|first1=L.|last2=Milne|first2=R. G.|title=The multiplication regions and interaction of acute and chronic bee-paralysis viruses in adult honey bees|journal=[[Journal of General Virology]]|date=1 January 1969|volume=4|issue=1|pages=9\u201314|doi=10.1099/0022-1317-4-1-9|doi-access=free}}</ref>.\n\n== Virology ==\nChronic bee paralysis virus shares similarities to the virus families ''[[Nodaviridae]]'' and ''[[Tombusviridae]]'', but CBPV is distinct enough from the two existing families and consequently is considered a new family of viruses. As a result, CBPV has yet to be fully classified.<ref name=Chevin2015>Aurore Chevin, Bruno Coutard, Philippe Blanchard, Anne-Sophie Dabert-Gay, Magali Ribi\u00e8re-Chabert, Richard Thi\u00e9ry: [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4488741/ Characterisation of Structural Proteins from Chronic Bee Paralysis Virus (CBPV) Using Mass Spectrometry], in: Viruses. 2015 Jun; 7(6): 3329\u20133344. [[doi:10.3390/v7062774]], {{PMC|4488741}}, {{PMID|26110588}}</ref><ref name=\"Olivier 59\u201368\" /> \nChronic bee paralysis virus is a [[Positive-sense single-stranded RNA virus|single-stranded positive-RNA]] virus with five fragments, two large fragments and three small fragments<ref name=\"Olivier 59\u201368\">{{Cite journal|last=Olivier|first=Violaine|last2=Blanchard|first2=Philippe|last3=Chaouch|first3=Soraya|last4=Lallemand|first4=Perrine|last5=Schurr|first5=Frank|last6=Celle|first6=Olivier|last7=Dubois|first7=Eric|last8=Tordo|first8=No\u00ebl|last9=Thi\u00e9ry|first9=Richard|last10=Houlgatte|first10=R\u00e9mi|last11=Ribi\u00e8re|first11=Magali|date=March 2008|title=Molecular characterisation and phylogenetic analysis of Chronic bee paralysis virus, a honey bee virus|journal=Virus Research|volume=132|issue=1\u20132|pages=59\u201368|doi=10.1016/j.virusres.2007.10.014|pmid=18079012}}</ref>. The first large fragment is suspected to encode an [[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase]], as it possesses 8 conserved domains of an RNA-dependent RNA polymerase<ref name=\"ribiere magali\" />. The second large fragment is thought to encode for the virus [[Capsid|capsid protein]], which is reported to be a capsid protein of 23.5 kDa and four polypeptides of 75, 50, 30 and 20 kDa<ref>{{Citation|last=Bailey|first=L.|chapter=Viruses Attacking the Honey Bee|date=1976|pages=271\u2013304|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-12-039820-1|doi=10.1016/s0065-3527(08)60507-2|pmid=775948|title=Advances in Virus Research Volume 20|volume=20|series=Advances in Virus Research}}</ref><ref name=\"Olivier 59\u201368\" /><ref>{{Citation|last=Ball|first=Brenda V.|title=HONEY BEE VIRUSES|date=1999|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Virology|pages=743\u2013749|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-12-227030-7|last2=Bailey|first2=Leslie|doi=10.1006/rwvi.1999.0139|chapter=Honey Bee Viruses}}</ref>.The virus capsid is hypothesized to have [[icosahedral symmetry]]<ref name=\"ribiere magali\" />.\n\n\nChronic bee paralysis virus is also found to facilitate the growth and reproduction of a satellite virus, called [[Chronic bee paralysis satellite virus|Chronic bee paralysis associate satellite virus]] (CBVA), which has three small (+) single-stranded RNA fragments. The three small (+) single-stranded RNA fragments appear inconsistently in the Chronic bee paralysis virus, which lends to the idea that the three RNAs are not components of CBPV but of a satellite virus that relies on CBPV activity in order to proliferate<ref name=\":4\" />. Additionally, the three small RNA fragments each have molecular weights of 0.35 x 10<sup>6</sup> (1100 nucleotides), which exactly matches the molecular weights of the three (+) ssRNA fragments of CBVA<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Overton|first=H. A.|last2=Buck|first2=K. W.|last3=Bailey|first3=L.|last4=Ball|first4=B. V.|date=1982-11-01|title=Relationships between the RNA Components of Chronic Bee-Paralysis Virus and those of Chronic Bee-Paralysis Virus Associate|journal=Journal of General Virology|volume=63|issue=1|pages=171\u2013179|doi=10.1099/0022-1317-63-1-171|issn=0022-1317|doi-access=free}}</ref>.\n\n== Infection and transmission ==\nChronic bee paralysis virus is transmitted though two main mechanisms. The first mechanism is viral transmission through bee feces, which remains on the hive floor and can be picked up on the furry legs of other bees and ingested orally<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ribi\u00e8re|first=M.|last2=Lallemand|first2=P.|last3=Iscache|first3=A.-L.|last4=Schurr|first4=F.|last5=Celle|first5=O.|last6=Blanchard|first6=P.|last7=Olivier|first7=V.|last8=Faucon|first8=J.-P.|date=2007-12-01|title=Spread of Infectious Chronic Bee Paralysis Virus by Honeybee (Apis mellifera L.) Feces|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|volume=73|issue=23|pages=7711\u20137716|doi=10.1128/AEM.01053-07|issn=0099-2240|pmid=17933946|pmc=2168079}}</ref>. The second mechanism is through close contact between bees in the hive. [[Worker bee|Worker bees]] are the most susceptible to infection, since they travel the hive most frequently. The infection may spread between hives as a result of indirect contact or direct contact between honey bees<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ribiere|first1=M.|last2=Lallemand|first2=P.|last3=Iscache|first3=A.-L.|last4=Schurr|first4=F.|last5=Celle|first5=O.|last6=Blanchard|first6=P.|last7=Olivier|first7=V.|last8=Faucon|first8=J.-P.|date=12 October 2007|title=Spread of infections chronic bee paralysis virus by honeybee (''Apis mellifera'' L.) feces|journal=[[Applied and Environmental Microbiology]]|volume=73|issue=23|pages=7711\u20137716|doi=10.1128/AEM.01053-07|pmc=2168079|pmid=17933946}}</ref>. [[Research]] shows that mainly adult honey bees can be infected with chronic bee paralysis virus by a topical contact with infected feces or by ingestion of [[Virus|virion]]-containing substances<ref name=\"ribiere magali\" />.\n\n=== Viral replication cycle ===\n\n==== Entry into cell ====\nChronic bee paralysis virus is transmitted to honey bees through a [[Omnipresence|ubiquitous]] [[Parasitism|parasite]] common to honey bee hives, Varroa mites (''[[Varroa jacobsoni]]''). Varroa mites are known to harbor many viruses for which honey bees are susceptible and permissive<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.honeybeesuite.com/chronic-bee-paralysis-virus/|title=Chronic bee paralysis virus|date=2010-08-18|website=Honey Bee Suite|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref>.The parasitic mites attach themselves to honey bees externally and feed off of the [[hemolymph]] of their hosts<ref name=\":2\" />. This exchange of fluids between the parasitic mites and the hosts allows for CBPV particles to enter fluid transfer systems in the honey bee body. The mechanisms by which chronic bee paralysis virus gains entry into honey bee cells is currently unknown.\n\n==== Replication ====\nLike other [[(+)ssRNA|positive sense single-stranded RNA viruses]], Chronic bee paralysis virus replicates in the [[cytoplasm]] of honeybee cells. The first large (+) RNA fragment in the CBPV [[genome]] likely encodes for an [[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase]], which makes many copies of viral RNA. After many copies of the genome have been produced, the honey bee host's cellular processes will translate the viral RNA into functional [[Protein|proteins]] which can cause propagation of the virus inside the host. The virus replicates at the highest levels in the head of the honeybee, reaching an average of 10<sup>7</sup> copies of the virus in an infected worker bee head and as many as 10<sup>11</sup> copies of the virus in an infected [[queen bee]] head. Chronic bee paralysis virus particles have been found to concentrate in two centers; in [[mushroom bodies]] which play a role in sensory processing, [[memory]], and learning as well as in the central body, which plays a vital role in coordinating movement. Loss of flying ability in honey bees as a result of CBPV infection can be attributed to neuron destruction in the central body. Erratic behavior in infected bees may be a result of mushroom body neuron destruction. \n\n==== Symptoms ====\nInfected honeybees will begin to show symptoms of the illness within five days of infection, and the infection presents in two distinct ways, with Type I infection being the more common of the two infection types. \n\nA Type I infected bee presents with a bloated abdomen due to a fluid-filled honey sac and weak or trembling wings. Type I infected honey bees tend to crawl on the ground or cluster near the entrance of the hive, as their weakened wings lead to an inability to fly.\n\nA Type II infected honey bee presents with complete abdominal hair loss, causing it to appear black and greasy. These bees are still able to fly 2-3 days after symptoms begin to appear, but they lose their ability to fly shortly before succumbing to the disease.\n\nA third type of infection that is a major contributor to the spread of the virus is an infection of CBPV in which the infected bee exhibits no symptoms of the illness. The infected bee does not present with any of the classic symptoms of the disease before death, and, as a result, is able to transmit the virus beyond its own hive.\n\n==== Treatment ====\nThere is no known treatment for the disease currently. Often, infections of chronic bee paralysis virus die out on their own, but infected bees, if detected, must be removed from the hive immediately to lessen the chances of the virus spreading. Supplementing a smaller hive that has been severely affected by the virus with healthy bees from another colony can prevent colony collapse in struggling hives. The infection commonly surges in the winters rather than warmer months, for unknown reasons<ref name=\":2\" />.\n\nTreating the hive against Varroa mites has also proven to be an effective preventive method against viral infection<ref name=\":2\" />. While bees should not be medicated against mites as a preventative measure because mites are quick to develop resistance; however, once detected, mites can be eliminated with the use of [[pesticides]]. Common pesticides include [[Apistan]], [[Formic acid|Formic Acid]], [[Thymol|Apiguard]]<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dummies.com/home-garden/hobby-farming/beekeeping/how-to-control-a-varroa-mite-problem-in-your-beehive/|title=How to Control a Varroa Mite Problem in Your Beehive|website=dummies|language=en|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref>. Home remedies for exterminating mites in a bee hive also include dusting the hive floors as well as the honey bees themselves with powdered sugar in order to suffocate the mites<ref name=\":3\" />. \n\n== Testing ==\nChronic bee paralysis virus is classified as an [[Subclinical infection|inapparent infection]] because there are few tell-tale symptoms that appear before the infection has progressed to a fatal degree. As many honey bees can become infected and either show symptoms days after the initial point of infection or fail to show any symptoms throughout the entire course of the illness, CBPV can infect entire hives before the virus is detected. Despite the use of [[infectivity]] and [[Serology|serological tests]], these testing methods are often inaccurate and difficult to reproduce with consistent results.<ref name=\"ribiere magali\" />\n\n== Symbiotic relationships ==\nAlthough Chronic bee paralysis virus mainly infects honey bees, the virus has also been found to replicate in two species of [[carnivore|carnivorous]] [[ant]], ''[[Camponotus vagus]]'' and ''[[Formica rufa]]''.These carnivorous ants become infected with CBPV through two mechanisms: eating decomposing bees who harbor the virus or by independently collecting infected honeydew.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite journal|last1=Celle|first1=Olivier|last2=Blanchard|first2=Philippe|last3=Olivier|first3=Violaine|last4=Schurr|first4=Frank|last5=Cougoule|first5=Nicolas|last6=Faucon|first6=Jean-Paul|last7=Ribi\u00e8re|first7=Magali|date=May 2008|title=Detection of chronic bee paralysis virus (CBPV) genome and its replicative RNA form in various hosts and possible ways of spread|url=https://hal-anses.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-00414769/file/Detection_of_Chronic_bee_paralysis_virus_in_various_hosts_version_HAL_210909.pdf|journal=Virus Research|volume=133|issue=2|pages=280\u2013284|doi=10.1016/j.virusres.2007.12.011|pmid=18243390}}</ref>  While the virus does not cause any symptoms in the carnivorous ants, the [[Commensalism|commensal relationship]] between the virus and the ants allows the ants to serve as a reservoir for viral replication to occur<ref name=\":5\" />. \n\nChronic bee paralysis virus is also similar to [[slow bee paralysis virus]] and [[acute bee paralysis virus]]. Though CBPV does not fall into the same family as the other two viruses, it bears similarities to the other viruses because it causes paralysis as the fatal symptom of the infection. Slow bee paralysis, in contrast to Chronic bee paralysis virus, causes paralysis of the front two pairs of legs on honey bees ([[Apis mellifera cypria|''Apis mellifera'']]), silkworms ([[Bombyx mori|''Bombyx mori'']]'')'', and bumble bees ([[Bombus sylvarum|''Bombis spp.'']]'')''. This paralysis eventually causes death in the infected insects. Slow bee paralysis virus is transmitted to hives through ''[[Varroa destructor]]'' mite infestations. Because of the similarities between the two viruses, Chronic bee paralysis virus is suspected to have the same mode of transmission.\n\nChronic bee paralysis virus is also seen to interact with satellite viruses. The three short RNA segments of the viral genome are thought to be a satellite virus<ref name=\":4\" />. Only in the presence of CBPV can the associated satellite virus proliferate.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q16662559}}\n\n[[Category:Bee diseases]]\n[[Category:Insect viral diseases]]\n[[Category:Positive-sense single-stranded RNA viruses]]\n[[Category:Beekeeping]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chronic_bee_paralysis_virus"}
{"title_page": "The Burren", "text_new": "{{short description|Glaciated karst landscape region in northwest County Clare, Ireland}}\n{{About|a region in County Clare in the Republic of Ireland ||Burren (disambiguation){{!}}Burren}}\n\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = The Burren\n| alt_name = ''Boireann''\n| iucn_category = \n| photo = Burren 0513.JPG\n| photo_alt = \n| photo_caption = The [[karst landscape]] of the Burren\n| photo_width = \n| map = Ireland\n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = Location of the Burren National Park, SE corner of the Burren\n| map_width = \n| relief =\n| label = Burren National Park (Mullaghmore)\n| label_position = \n| mark =\n| marker_size =\n| location = [[County Clare|Co. Clare]] (and a little of [[County Galway|Co. Galway]]), [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| nearest_city = [[Galway]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|53|00|28|N|9|00|08|W|type:landmark_region:IE|display=inline,title}}\n| coords_ref = \n| region = \n| area_ha = \n| designation =\n| authorized =\n| created =\n| established = \n| designated =\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| visitation_ref =\n| governing_body = \n| administrator =\n| operator =\n| owner =\n| website = \n| url = \n| child = \n| embedded = \n}}\n\n'''The Burren''' ({{Irish place name|Boireann|great rock}}) is a region of environmental interest primarily located in northwestern [[County Clare]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], dominated by glaciated [[karst]] (or sometimes [[glaciokarst]]<ref name=\"BurrenNP_Geol\">[https://www.burrennationalpark.ie/geology] Burren National Park - Geology - \"The Burren is one of the finest examples of a Glacio-Karst landscape in the world. At least two glacial advances are known in the Burren area.\"</ref>) landscape.  It measures, depending on the definition, between {{convert|250|km2|mi2}} and {{convert|560|km2|mi2}}. The name is most often applied to the area within the circle made by the villages of [[Tubber, County Clare|Tubber]], [[Corofin, County Clare|Corofin]], [[Kilfenora]], [[Lisdoonvarna]], and [[Ballyvaughan]], and [[Kinvara]] in extreme south-western Galway, including the adjacent coastline.<ref name=\"GeoParkGuide\">{{cite web|title=The Burren Visitor Guide|url=http://www.burrengeopark.ie/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Burren-Free-Visitor-Guide.pdf|website=Burren and Cliffs of Moher Geopark|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref> \n\nA part of the Burren forms the [[Burren National Park]], the smallest of the six [[National Parks in the Republic of Ireland|National Parks]] in Ireland, while the full Burren and adjacent territory including the [[Cliffs of Moher]] are included in the [[Burren and Cliffs of Moher Geopark]].\n\n==Location==\nWhile the name is generally applied to the limestone uplands of northwestern Clare, and adjacent lowlands, and generally excludes the area of ''Clare shales'' to the southwest, the exact extent of the area is not clearly defined, and geologically it does extend into [[County Galway]] to both the north and northeast (see ''Geology'' below). The southeastern pocket of Co. Galway around Kinvara is usually included, and is the base for many Burren organisations. \nThe Burren is certainly bounded by the [[Atlantic Ocean]] and by [[Galway Bay]], with the [[Aran Islands]] representing a geological extension of the limestone hills that make up most of The Burren.<ref name=\"Explore\">{{cite book|last=Cunningham|first=George|title=Exploring the Burren|publisher=Town House and Country House, Dublin|year=1998|isbn=0-946172-59-5|page=}}</ref>{{rp|5}}\n\nAccording to one definition, the Burren extends south to a line from the coastal resort of [[Lahinch]] to Corofin and is delimited in the east by a line roughly from Kinvara to [[Kilmacduagh monastery]], near [[Gort]]. Note that taken literally, this would includes places like the town of [[Ennistymon]] and the [[Cliffs of Moher]], which would more commonly be considered as neighbouring the Burren.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|5}}  In another definition, the \"Burren Programme\" defines the region as extending well into the Gort plain, encompassing inter alia [[Coole Park]] and the [[Turlough (lake)|turloughs]] around it, while to the south it would extend to [[Ruan, County Clare|Ruan]] and [[Crusheen]], and in the southwest to the edge of [[Doolin]], as well as the routine Lisdoonvarna, Kilfenora and Corofin.<ref name=\"BP\"/>\n\nThus the stated size of the Burren varies between around {{convert|250|km2|mi2}} (the core area of exposed limestone), through {{convert|360|km2|mi2}} (taking in all limestone landscapes) and 560 square kilometers (including the about {{convert|200|km2|mi2}} of downland), depending on the approach taken. Roughly 60% of the uplands show exposed limestone pavement.<ref name=\"NPH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.burrennationalpark.ie/history|title=Burren National Park History|publisher=National Parks and Wildlife Service|accessdate=28 December 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930092125/http://www.burrennationalpark.ie/history|archivedate=30 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|5,16,33}}\n\n==Climate==\nThe Burren has an unusually temperate climate for western Ireland. Average air temperatures range from {{convert|15|C|F}} in July to {{convert|4|-|6|C|F}} in January, while the soil temperature does not usually drop below 6&nbsp;\u00b0C (as an exception, in late 2010, there was a prolonged period of snow). Since grass will grow once the temperature rises above 6&nbsp;\u00b0C, this means that The Burren (like the neighbouring Aran Islands) has one of the longest growing seasons in Ireland or Britain, and supports diverse and rich plant growth.<ref name=\"EFNCPclimate\">European Forum on Nature Conservatism and Pastoralism: [http://www.efncp.org/hnv-showcases/ireland-the-burren/the-burren/facts/ The Burren - Facts] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125015321/http://www.efncp.org/hnv-showcases/ireland-the-burren/the-burren/facts/ |date=2018-01-25 }}</ref>\n\nThe area has around {{convert|1525|mm|in}} of annual rainfall (more than twice the amount observed in eastern Ireland),<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|33}} with an average level of over {{convert|160|mm|in}} monthly from October to January<ref name=\"EFNCPclimate\"/>\n\nLate May is the sunniest time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.met.ie|title=Met \u00c9ireann - The Irish Weather Service|first=Met|last=\u00c9ireann|website=www.met.ie|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701025856/http://www.met.ie/|archivedate=2007-07-01}}</ref> and also a good time to view flowers, with the [[gentians]] and [[Dryas (plant)|avens]] peaking (but orchid species blooming later).{{citation needed|date=December 2011|reason=some orchid species have finished flowering by this date and others are at their flowering peak}}\n\nDuring counter-guerrilla operations in The Burren in 1651-52, [[Edmund Ludlow]] stated, \"''(Burren) is a country where there is not enough water to drown a man, wood enough to hang one, nor earth enough to bury him...... and yet their cattle are very fat; for the grass growing in turfs of earth, of two or three foot square, that lie between the rocks, which are of limestone, is very sweet and nourishing.''\"{{ref|BBC}}{{ref|clarelibrary}}\n\n==Geology==\n[[File:The Burren in the evening sun.JPG|thumb|225px|right|The Burren landscape in the evening sun]]\n[[Image:Burren karst.jpg|thumb|The karst hills of The Burren]]\n[[File:The Burren (2002).jpg|thumb|225px|right|Grikes and clints run along the [[limestone pavement]]]]\n\n===Stratigraphy===\nThe area is formed from a thick succession of [[sedimentary rock]]s, largely limestones but also including [[sandstone]]s, [[mudstone]]s and [[siltstones]]. All of the solid rocks exposed at the surface are of [[Carboniferous]] age though they are underlain at depth by [[Old Red Sandstone]] of [[Devonian]] age which in turn overlies rocks of Lower [[Palaeozoic]] age. None of the pre-Carboniferous rocks is seen at the surface in the area.<ref name=\"auto\">Landscape and Rocks of the Burren: a guide to the geology of the area. Geological Survey of Ireland 2008</ref> The limestones, which date from the [[Visean]] stage of the early Carboniferous, formed as sediments in a tropical sea approximately 325 million years ago. The strata contain fossil [[coral]]s, [[crinoid]]s, [[sea urchin]]s and [[ammonites]]. This bed of limestone is up to 800 metres thick. In the north and west it lies on a shelf of Galway granite which supported the upper layers, preventing shifts like those that created the \"twisted\" hills Knockanes and Mullaghmore. The limestone also extends below Galway Bay out to the Aran Islands and to the east into the Gort plain.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|16,33}}\n\nLater in the Carboniferous (c. 318 million years ago), the limestone was covered by darker sand and mud that later turned into [[shale]] (the lower \"Clare Shales\") and [[sandstone]] (the upper \"Millstone Grit\"). These layers reached a thickness of up to {{convert|330|m|ft}} in north Clare. These top layers protected the underlying limestone from erosion for millions of years before being largely stripped away by glaciers, except in the south west, where they still extend from Doolin to Slieve Elva, Lisdoonvarna, Kilfenora and to the western shore of Lake Inchiquin. One \"island\" of shale is the hill Poulacapple, southwest of Ballyvaughan, where an upland moor has formed on top of the impermeable shale layers.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|16,33}}<ref name=\"Feehan1\">\n{{Citation | last =Feehan | first =John | contribution =The Rocks and Landforms of the Burren | year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell |editor-first1 =J.W. |editor-last2 =Korff | editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =14-23|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas | id = }}</ref>{{rp|17}}\n\nThe local geological succession comprises the following [[geological formation|formations]] some of which are subdivided into various [[Stratigraphic_unit#Lithostratigraphic_units|members]]. The youngest rocks are at the start of the list, the oldest at the bottom. The first three listed are of [[Namurian]] age and are a mix of mudstones, sandstones and siltstones, the remainder are Visean age limestones.\n\n*Central Clare Group\n*Gull Island Formation\n*Clare Shale Formation\n*Slievenaglasha Formation\n**Lissylisheen Member\n**Ballyelly Member\n**Fahee North Member\n**Balliny Member\n*Burren Formation\n**Ailwee Member\n**Maumcaha Member\n**Hawkhill Member\n**Fanore Member\n**Black Head Member\n*Tubber Formation\n**Finavarra Member\n**Castlequarter Member\n**Newtown Member\n**Fiddaun Member\n**Cregmahon Member<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Quaternary===\nGlaciation during the late [[Quaternary]] period (beginning c. one million years ago) facilitated greater denudation. Glaciers expanded and retreated over the region several times. Of the last two periods the first was the more pronounced, covering the whole of the Burren. The last advance of the ice cover was more limited, affecting only the eastern Burren.<ref name=\"Feehan1\"/>{{rp|20-1}}\n\nThe result is that The Burren is one of the finest examples of [[glaciokarst|glacio-karst]] landscape in the world. The effects of the [[last glacial period]] (the Midlandian) are most in evidence, with The Burren overrun by ice during this glaciation.<ref name=\"BurrenNP_Geol\"/> The impact of earlier [[karstification]] (solutional erosion) has been eliminated by the last glacial period. So any surface karstification now seen dates from approximately 10,000 years ago and The Burren karst is thus very recent in geological terms. \n\nSolutional processes have widened and deepened the grikes of the [[limestone pavement]]. Pre-existing lines of weakness in the rock (vertical joints) contribute to the formation of extensive fissures separated by clints (flat pavement like slabs). The rock karstification facilitates the formation of subterranean drainage. This has formed numerous cave systems of which more than 50 kilometers have been mapped.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|33}} The most accessible of these is [[Aillwee Cave]].\n\nDue to the processes mentioned, there are very few permanent surface rivers in the region. The Caher, flowing into the sea at [[Fanore]], is one of the most stable.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|33}} Some of the large valleys, mostly running south to north, that are still visible today are in fact the remains of pre-glacial river valleys. The rivers disappeared from the surface when the upper layers of stone had been stripped away. \n\nAnother characteristic features of The Burren are closed roughly circular depressions with no surface outlets for water (called [[polje]]). Around 100 of these exist, mostly present in the eastern Burren. The most notable are the valleys of Kilcorney, Poulawilan, Caherconnel and Carran, generally stretching from northeast to southwest. The largest is the Carran depression, more than two miles long, up to a mile wide and over 200 feet deep. This is where the pre-glacial rivers of the area first eroded away the upper layers and started to dissolve the exposed limestone. Some of the smaller ones were created when caves underneath collapsed (one example of this is the Glen of Clab).<ref name=\"Feehan1\"/>{{rp|19-20}}\n\nGlaciers also deposited numerous granite and limestone [[Glacial erratic|erratics]] on the pavements. The former were carried south across Galway Bay by the second-to-last glaciation. Granite boulders can be found mostly in the north of the Burren. The final ice cover came from the northeast and mostly deposited limestone erratics. On Slieve Elva these are visible today at elevations of up to {{convert|300|m|ft}} mabove sea level. The characteristic terracing of the hills occurred when vertical joints weathered and large blocks of limestone fell off and were further eroded away.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|33}}<ref name=\"Feehan1\"/>{{rp|16,21}}\n\nTowards the very end of the Ice Age the glaciers ended for a time at Fanore. At that time, Slieve Elva and Knockauns hill alone rose above the surrounding ice fields. The valleys facing Galway Bay had been widened considerably by glacial action, first when the ice moved south from Connemara and then when meltwater sought a runoff. When the ice finally retreated it also left moraines in valley bottoms and the characteristic [[drumlin]]s (most of them on top of the shale and sandstone to the south). The Caher Valley was almost choked up by deposited sand and rocks and these also piled up against the western slopes of Slieve Elva. It was this protective layer of sediment that has made surface streams locally possible once more.<ref name=\"Feehan1\"/>{{rp|21}} \n\nToday, the uplands' highest point is on the hill Slieve Elva, whose shale cover rises up to {{convert|345|m|ft}} above sea level.<ref name=\"JourneyWest\">{{cite book|last=Cunningham|first=George|title=Burren Journey West|publisher=Shannonside Mid Western Regional Tourism Organisation|year=1980|isbn=0-9503080-2-1|page=}}</ref>{{rp|47}}\n\n==Landscape types and habitats==\nIn addition to the limestone pavement, major landscape types, providing the habitats for the flora and fauna, include limestone heath, dry calcareous grasslands, calcareous (calcifying or petrifying) springs, the intermittent water bodies called [[turloughs]], bogs, [[cladium fens]], lakes, wet grasslands, scrub and light woodland, and neutral, and farm-improved, grasslands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://burrenprogramme.com/the-burren/habitats/|title=Habitats|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124005748/http://burrenprogramme.com/the-burren/habitats/|archivedate=2018-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==Flora and fauna==\n[[File:Burren Flora 24 Early Purple Orchid (3585561235).jpg|thumb|Early Purple Orchid]]\n[[File:Burren Flora 01 Mountain Avens (3586050338).jpg|thumb|Mountain Avens]]\n\n===Flora===\nThe Burren is renowned for its remarkable assemblage of plants and animals,<ref>{{cite web|jstor=20494847|title=Noteworthy Plants of the Burren: A Catalogue Raisonn\u00e9|publisher=}}</ref> and over 70% of Ireland's species of flowers are found there.<ref name=\"Burrenbeo Conservation\">Clare, The Burrenbeo Trust: [https://burrenbeo.com/the-burren/conservation/ The Burren - Conservation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123072636/https://burrenbeo.com/the-burren/conservation/ |date=2018-01-23 }}</ref> The region supports [[Arctic\u2013alpine]] and [[Mediterranean Basin]] plants side-by-side, due to the unusual environment.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|35}}\n\nThe region supports many rare Irish species, some of which are only found in this area. Others occur in similar karst areas in western Ireland. Notable plants include ''[[Festuca|Festuca indigesta]]'' seen in 1949 and ''[[Arenaria norvegica]]'' identified only once, in 1961. Two of the 24 types of ''[[Taraxacum]]'' found here are \"practically unique to the Burren\".<ref name=\"Roden\"/>{{rp|32}} 23 of the 28 types of orchids found in Ireland grow in the Burren, including unique forms such as ''[[Dactylorhiza|Dactylorhiza fuchsii subsp. okellyi]]''.<ref name=\"Roden\">{{Citation | last =Roden| first =Cilian| contribution =The Burren Flora| year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell |editor-first1 =J.W. |editor-last2 =Korff | editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =31-41|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas | id = }}</ref>{{rp|32}}\n\nThe grikes (crevices in the limestone) provide moist shelter, supporting a wide range of plants including dwarf shrubs. Where the surface of the limestone pavement is shattered into gravel many of the hardier Arctic or alpine plants can be found, while when the limestone pavement is covered by a thin layer of soil patches of grass are seen, interspersed with herbaceous plants. Among the flowers recorded from the Burren is the [[spring gentian]], an alpine plant with bright blue flowers that are used as a symbol for the area by the national tourist board, [[Failte Ireland]]. The Irish orchid (''[[Neotinea maculata]]'' and 21 other [[List of the orchids of Ireland|species of orchids]] ) and bloody cranesbill (''[[Geranium sanguineum]]'') also occur.<ref>Clements, P. 2011 ''Burren Country, Travels through an Irish Limestone Landscape''. The Collins Press. {{ISBN|9781848891173}}</ref> Other notable flowers are ''[[Anacamptis pyramidalis]]'', ''[[Platanthera chlorantha]]'', ''[[Ophrys insectifera]]'' ''[[Euphrasia salisburgensis]]'', ''[[Lathyrus linifolius]]'', ''[[Carlina vulgaris]]'', ''[[Centaurium erythraea]]'', ''[[Succisa pratensis]]'', ''[[Primula veris]]'', ''[[Filipendula vulgaris]]'', ''[[Parnassia palustris]]'', ''[[Campanula rotundifolia]]'',  ''[[Helianthemum oelandicum]]'', ''[[Polygala vulgaris]]'', ''[[Saxifraga|Saxifraga hypnoides]]'', ''[[Potentilla fruticosa]]'',  ''[[Antennaria|Antennaria dioeca]]'', ''[[Primula vulgaris]]'', ''[[Hypericum androsaemum]]'', ''[[Asperula cynanchica]]'', ''[[Rhinanthus minor]]'', ''[[Blackstonia perfoliata]]'' and ''[[Dryas octopetala]]'' <ref> Webb, D. A.,1962 Noteworthy Plants of the Burren A Catalogue Raison ''Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy'' , Vol. LXII, sect. B, No. 9, pp. 117-134, 1962  (pdf available at [[JSTOR]]) </ref> . Another prominent presence in limestone grikes are around 24 species of fern, such as the Mediterranean ''[[Adiantum capillus-veneris]]''. \n\nThe area is notable for the unusually close vicinity of both plants that hate lime and those that do well on it. Acid-loving plants such as ''[[Calluna]]'' grow well on patches of acidic peat that effectively isolates them from the underlying basic limestone.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|20-1,35-6}}\n\n===Fauna===\nOf the more than 30 species of butterflies and moths found in Ireland only two are not present in the Burren.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|37}} Notable insects present in the Burren include the butterflies the [[pearl-bordered fritillary]] (''Boloria euphrosyne''), [[brown hairstreak]] (''Thecla betulae''), [[marsh fritillary]] (''Euphydryas aurinia'') and [[Leptidea sinapis|wood white]] (''Leptidea sinapis''); the moths, the [[Calamia tridens|Burren green]] (''Calamia tridens'', which is only present in Ireland in this area),<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|37}} [[Gnophos dumetata|Irish annulet]] (''Gnophos dumetata'') and [[transparent burnet]] (''Zygaena purpuralis''); the hoverfly ''[[Doros profuges]]'' and the water-beetle ''[[Ochthebius nilssoni]]''. This last species is known from just five sites in the world, its type locality in northern Sweden and four [[marl]] lakes in The Burren. \n\nThe Burren is one of the main breeding areas in Ireland of the [[European pine marten]].  Also present are badgers, foxes and stoats. The hillsides of the Burren also host herds of feral goats.<ref name=\"Arcy\">{{Citation | last =D'Arcy| first =Gordon| contribution =The Wildlife of the Burren| year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell |editor-first1 =J.W. |editor-last2 =Korff | editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =47-58|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas | id = }}</ref>{{rp|55}} All seven species of bats present in Ireland can be found in The Burren.<ref name=\"Explore\" />{{rp|37}} [[Otter]]s live along the coast, as do [[Grey seal|grey seals]]. [[List of mammals of Ireland|porpoises,dolphins]] and [[Basking shark|basking sharks]] can be spotted off Black Head and various sections of the [[Cliffs of Moher]]. \n\nA wide range of bird species are also found in the Burren, including crows and ravens, [[peregrine falcon|peregrine falcons]], [[kestrel|kestrels]], various gulls, [[guillemot|guillemots]], [[razorbill|razorbills]], [[kittiwake|kittiwakes]], [[fulmar|fulmars]], [[puffin|puffins]] and [[European shag|shags]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Burren Landscape 2.jpg|thumb|225px|right|The Burren landscape with Galway Bay in the background]]\n\n===Prehistory===\n[[File:Poulnabrone_Portal_Tomb_640x480.jpg|thumb|Poulnabrone portal tomb]]\nPollen analysis indicates that in the [[Mesolithic]] period of 8000 to 7000 BC The Burren looked completely different from today, with most of the uplands covered in a mixture of deciduous, pine and yew trees. No clear evidence of Mesolithic settlements or camp sites in the area has yet been discovered. At the limits of the region, near [[Lake Inchiquin]] and at the so-called \"Doolin Axe Factory\", stone artifacts have been discovered that may be Mesolithic in origin. However, by the [[Neolithic]], c. 4000 BC, settlers had clearly arrived and began changing the landscape through deforestation, likely by overgrazing and burning, and the building of stone walls. These people also constructed Megalithic sites like the portal tomb known as [[Poulnabrone dolmen]] and the [[Court cairn|court tombs]] at Teergonean (near Doolin) and Ballyganner (near [[Noughaval]]). Overall, there are around 70 megalithic tombs in the Burren area, more than half of all of these structures found in Clare.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|7-8}}<ref name=\"Arch\">{{cite book|last=Carthy|first=Hugh|title=Burren Archaeology|publisher=The Collins Press|year=2011|isbn=9781848891050|page=}}</ref>{{rp|5}}<ref name=\"Waddell\">{{Citation | last =Waddell| first =John | contribution =The First People - the Prehistoric Burren| year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell |editor-first1 =J.W. |editor-last2 =Korff | editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =59-76|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas | id = }}</ref>{{rp|60}}\n\nThe most numerous type of prehistoric structure (apart from stone walls) in The Burren is the late-Neolithic/early-[[Bronze Age]] [[Wedge-shaped gallery grave|wedge tomb]], mostly dated to the period 2500 to 2000 BC. It accounts for around 90% of the region's megalithic tombs. Many examples of these are found on Roughan Hill near [[Kilnaboy]], including those at [[Parknabinnia (wedge tomb)|Parknabinnia]] and [[Creevagh (wedge tomb)|Creevagh]]. Others are located at [[Gleninsheen (wedge tomb)|Gleninsheen]] and Berneens (Rathborney) and Poulaphuca (Carran). Large stone cairns on many hills, such as the [[Poulawack Cairn]], also date from this period.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|8}}<ref name=\"Waddell\"/>{{rp|63}}\n\nThe economy at that time was likely based on pastoral farming in fairly small groups. As is still done today, the cattle were moved in a reverse of the usual seasonal pattern: cattle are moved to the uplands in the winter, allowing year round grazing.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|8}}\n\nEvidence of [[Beaker culture|Beaker pottery]] was found on Roughan Hill, but in general few signs of the actual settlements of the Neolithic people have been found. This may be due to the fact that their structures were lightly built (from wood or other non-permanent materials).<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|11}} \n\nDuring the Bronze Age, locals also built many ''[[Fulacht fiadh|Fulachtai fiadh]]'', remains of more than 300 survive in the region. Their exact function is still debated, but they probably served as places where water was heated by fire, either for cooking, brewing or bathing purposes.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|8}}\n\nHowever, in contrast to the quantity of archaeological evidence found, the population of The Burren likely declined noticeably between the late Neolithic and the end of the Bronze Age. This was likely largely due to a shift in the climate, possibly related to the volcanic eruption known as \"[[Hekla 4]]\". Around the end of the 3rd millennium BC temperatures dropped and the climate became wetter. Heavy rainfall combined with previous clearing activity to cause serious soil erosion in the uplands. Evidence suggests that much of the soil cover over the limestone karst was in fact removed during the Middle and Late Bronze Age. This reduction in the area of fertile land put pressure on population numbers and probably increased conflicts over scarce resources. Building of new stone walls largely came to an end \u2013 there is a gap in documented building between the late Neolithic/early Bronze Age and early Christian periods. By the end of the Bronze Age, the uplands were largely depopulated.<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|10}}\n\nNevertheless, like the [[Mooghaun North Hoard]] found near Newmarket-on-Fergus, the discovery of a golden Bronze Age gorget in [[Rathborney|Gleninsheen townland]] indicates the (at least temporary) local presence of a late Bronze Age society that was rich, mobile and well-connected via trade networks with other regions.<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|13}} \n\nLike in many places of Ireland, datable [[Iron Age]] sites are rare in The Burren. This may be due to the use of dwellings that did not leave durable traces (wooden buildings or even tents). Some of the extant [[ringfort|r\u00e1ths, cashels or cahers]] may actually have Iron Age origins. However, few have been excavated and those that have been the subject of research, like [[Cahercommaun]], [[Caherconnell Stone Fort|Caherconnel]], [[Cahermore ringfort|Cahermore]] or [[Ballyallaban ringfort|Ballyallaban]], are thought to be early Medieval or later in origin. The large enigmatic enclosure of Turlough Hill (see [[Oughtmama]]) may be Iron Age or earlier. Definite regional findings from this era are limited to a few bronze horse bridles discovered near Corofin and at Ballyalla ([[Kilshanny]]).<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|9}}<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|16}}\n\n===Medieval===\n[[File:Ucht M\u00e1ma Middle and West Churches NW 2015 09 02.jpg|thumb|Early Christian churches at Oughtmama]]\n[[File:Corecomroe Abbey Ruhende Statue.jpg|thumb|Tomb in the sanctuary of Corcomroe Abbey with effigy of Conor O'Brien, King of Thomond]]\n\nIn the Iron Age and early Medieval times, the region was controlled by a family or tribe known as the ''Corco Modhruadh'', meaning \"seed\" or \"people of Modhruadh\". They were one of dozens of minor tribes in Ireland at that time, which occupied a discrete area (''tuath'') and were joined by a common bloodline or origin myths. By the time Christianity arrived locally, their territory had shrunk somewhat, encompassing what later became the Baronies of Burren and Corcomroe as well as some parts of Inchiquin barony (see below).<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|9}}<ref name=\"Gosling\"/>{{rp|78}}\n\nDuring the 5th and 6th centuries, the region appears to have been ruled from the [[Aran Islands]] by the ''E\u00f3ganacht \u00c1rann'', a minor branch of the [[E\u00f3ganachta|E\u00f3ganacht dynasty of Munster]].<ref name=\"Gosling\">{{Citation|last =Gosling|first =Paul|contribution =The Burren in Early Historic Times|year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell|editor-first1 =J.W.|editor-last2 =Korff|editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =77-91|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas|id = }}</ref>{{rp|78}}\n\nThe history of these years is uncertain, but after the decline of the ''E\u00f3ganacht \u00c1rann'' the local ''Corco Modhruadh'' likely fell under the control of the ''[[U\u00ed Fiachrach Aidhne]]'', a tribe from what is now southern Galway, who prospered in the 7th century. The local tribes were then probably subjects of the ''[[E\u00f3ganacht Locha L\u00e9in]]'' until their influence declined in the early 9th century. Whether the ''Corco Modhruadh'' still existed as a distinct group at that point is uncertain, as they and their neighbours ''[[Corcu Baiscind]]'' may have been assimilated into or conquered by the ''[[D\u00e9isi|D\u00e9isi Tuisceart]]'' of eastern Clare, who won a major battle against the ''Corco Modhruadh'' in 744. By the 9th century, the ''Corco Modhruadh'' had been driven into the Burren uplands.<ref name=\"Gosling\"/>{{rp|78}} \n\nThe Burren area is notable for the presence of several potential or likely \"early\" (i.e. pre-12th-century) ecclesiastical or monastic sites. These include Kilfenora, Kilnaboy, [[Temple Cronan]] and the churches of Oughtmama. A broader definition of The Burren would also include [[Dysert O'Dea Monastery]] near Corofin and Kilmacduagh. The large number of extant cashels, almost 500 of which have been identified in The Burren (out of around 45,000 in Ireland), also indicates the presence of a sizeable (early) medieval population that supported and used these churches.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|11}}<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|19}}\n\nAt the end of the first millennium, the ''[[D\u00e1l gCais]]'' expanded into the region, against the resistance of the incumbent [[U\u00ed Lochlainn]] and [[O'Conor]] families. The later regionally dominant [[O'Brien dynasty]] traced its origins to them. Evidence of Viking activity in the region is scant. They settled at Limerick, but in the Burren only a few artifacts of Scandinavian design have been found, centred mostly on Cahercommaun, which apparently was a major producer of wool at the time. A Viking arrowhead was found at the ringfort and a Viking hollow-bead necklace (likely dating from 820 to 850 AD) was discovered in nearby Glencurran Cave.<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|21-4}}\n\nEither at the end of the 12th or early in the 13th century, [[Cistercian]] monks came to the area and established ''Sancta Maria de Petra Fertili'', now known as [[Corcomroe Abbey]].<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|12}}\n\nIn the 12th century, the ''Corco Modhruadh''/Corcomroe territory was made into the newly created [[Diocese of Kilfenora]], of 13 parishes, and the church at Kilfenora became a cathedral.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|9-10}} \n\nAt some point around the 12th century, the territory of \"Corcomroe\" was divided in two for administrative purposes: ''Corco Modhruadh Iartharach'' (\"Western Corcomroe\") and ''Corco Modhruadh Oirthearach'' (\"Eastern Corcomroe\"), also known as ''Boireann'' which in the late 16th century became the English administrative Baronies of [[Corcomroe (barony)|Corcomroe]] and [[Burren (barony)|Burren]], respectively.<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|27}}\n\nThe end of the Medieval period was a difficult era for people in the area. Like much of Europe, the region suffered from the [[Great Famine of 1315\u201317|Great Famine]] (1315-7) and the [[Black Death]]. In addition, infighting between the Gaelic lords contributed to a socio-economic decline of the region. This was also reflected in a regional hiatus in large construction projects during the 13th and most of the 14th century.<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|30}}\n\n===Early Modern===\nFor a long-time the [[Norman invasion of Ireland|Anglo-Norman incursions into Ireland]] had little direct impact on the region. As late as at the [[Battle of Dysert O'Dea]] in 1318 some of the local clans allied to defeat a Norman army led by [[Richard de Clare, Steward of Forest of Essex|Richard de Clare]]. The people and their rulers thus continued to live in fortified houses, often inside the cashels, mostly retaining their [[Gaelic Ireland|Gaelic culture]]. One example of this are the [[Early Irish law|Brehon]] law schools of the O'Davorans at [[Cahermacnaghten]] or the MacClancys at Doolin.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|11-4}}\n\nOnly in the 15th and 16th centuries did the [[tower houses]] as exemplified today by places like [[Newtown Castle]], [[Shanmuckinish Castle]], [[Doonagore Castle]] or [[Ballinalacken Castle]] become widespread. Norman-type castles, such as the one built at [[Quin Abbey|Quin]], were absent in the Burren.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|11-4}} T.J. Westropp counted the remains of around 70 tower houses in the Baronies of Inchiquin, Corcomroe and Burren, with 21 of them located in the latter. Only around half of those 21 survive to any height in the 21st century. The distribution of the tower houses indicates that they were built close to the barony borders, which also represented the boundaries of the territories controlled by clans or families (see below). 11 of the 21 tower houses in the Barony of Burren lie within 1 km of its borders.<ref name=\"Gosling2\">{{Citation|last =Gosling|first =Paul|contribution =The Burren in Medieval Times|year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell|editor-first1 =J.W.|editor-last2 =Korff|editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =119-34|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas|id = }}</ref>{{rp|127,129}}\n\nThe O'Loughlin (\u00d3 Lochlainn) clan ruled ''Boireann'' down to the mid-17th century from their chief residence at [[Gregans Castle]] (the tower house, not the house of the same name). The chief of the family was known in later times as the 'Prince of Burren' and clan members were buried in the family tomb near the altar of Corcomroe Abbey. Their kinsmen, the O'Conor (\u00d3 Conchubhair), clan ruled ''Corco Modhruadh Iartharach'' from [[Dough Castle]] near [[Liscannor]]. The villages and towns found within the medieval territory of Boireann include Lisdoonvarna, Ballyvaughan, New Quay (Newquay) / Burrin (Burren), [[Noughaval]], Bealaclugga (Bellharbour), [[Carran|Carron]] and Fanore / Craggagh.\n\nBoth clans were eventually subjects of the O'Briens, the rulers of [[Thomond]]. Especially in the southwest, the O'Briens sometimes extended their direct influence, taking over houses and territories for themselves. They controlled the castles at [[Dromoland Castle|Dromoland]] and [[Leamaneh Castle|Leamaneh]] and later became the [[Baron Inchiquin|Barons Inchiquin]].<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|12}}\n\n==Culture==\nThe Burren has a long history of traditional Irish music. It is particularly known for the \"West Clare Style\" of [[concertina]] playing, and music festivals in [[Doolin]] and [[Corofin, County Clare|Corofin]].  The area also has a long history as a source of artistic inspiration, and has hosted a number of art galleries.\n\nThe Burren has inspired many non-fiction books, often accompanied by extensive illustration of the landscape.  A series of [[detective fiction]] novels, written by Cora Harrison, features the Burren's [[brehon]] judge (fictional) in the early 1500s, when the area still existed as a distinct Gaelic administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://severnhouse.com/author/Cora+Harrison/9419|title=Severn House|website=severnhouse.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122235021/http://severnhouse.com/author/Cora+Harrison/9419|archivedate=2018-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==Economic activity==\nThe leading economic activities in the Burren are agriculture and tourism.\n\n===Tourism===\nThe Burren has a reputation beyond Ireland, and, most notably with the Cliffs of Moher, but also with the major [[show caves]], [[dolmens]] such as at [[Poulnabrone]] and other prehistoric sites, and centres of cultural activity, attracts tourists from a wide range of countries.  There are a range of hotels, hostels, bed and breakfast facilities, and other accommodation providers.\n\nTourism presents some challenges in such an environmentally sensitive area, as it creates mostly seasonal employment, results in a large share of local houses being used only in the summer, and puts additional strain on environmental resources, thus exacerbating the effect of a significant increase in the number of houses in some areas during the 1990s and 2000s.  This has been a thread in the development and preservation activities previously discussed, and has driven the growth of local ecotourism, and the \"Leave No Trace\" local campaigns.  Concerns have also arisen about the level of day-tourism, especially by coaches, as opposed to overnight-staying tourists, who generate significantly more revenue.\n\n====Ecotourism in the Burren====\n[[Ecotourism]] is an important factor in The Burren, with many organisations involved, including the Burren Ecotourism Network. A key goal is to deal with the challenge of protecting the vulnerable landscape, while at the same time having it provide a fair income for the local inhabitants and allowing it to cope with increased visitor numbers. [[Sustainability|Sustainable]] ecotourism and independent \"'Ecotourism Certification\" for companies are intended to deal with those conflicting demands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theburrencentre.ie/burren-ecotourism/|title=Burren EcoTourism {{!}} The Burren Centre|website=www.theburrencentre.ie|access-date=2 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820015209/http://www.theburrencentre.ie/burren-ecotourism/|archivedate=20 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Gastro-tourism====\nA Burren Food Trail was launched in 2013, and has more than 20 members offering hospitality, and / or food and drink products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burren.ie/food-dining/burren-food-trail/|title=Burren Food Trail - Visit the Burren|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028220623/http://www.burren.ie/food-dining/burren-food-trail/|archivedate=2017-10-28}}</ref> The trail won the Irish prize in the European Destination of Excellence - Tourism and Local Gastronomy competition in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.failteireland.ie/footer/media-centre/the-burren-food-trail-is-cream-of-the-crop.aspx|title=Failte Ireland - The Burren Food Trail is Cream of the Crop|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129140453/http://www.failteireland.ie/footer/media-centre/the-burren-food-trail-is-cream-of-the-crop.aspx|archivedate=2018-01-29}}</ref> In association with the food trail events such as a Slow Food festival and a Food Fayre are organised.  The Food Fayre, part of the Burrenbeo-coordinated Winterage Festival around the October public holiday weekend, and run by the Burren Ecotourism Network and the Burren Food Trail team, reached its sixth year in 2017.\n\n===Agriculture===\nDue to climate and landscape, and techniques evolved over thousands of years, the Burren has a history as a productive agricultural landscape.  Arable farming is limited, and the main animals kept are cattle and goats.\n\nAs summarized by local landscape organisation, the Burrenbeo Trust<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heritagecouncil.ie/our-work-with-others/burren-beo-trust|title=Burren Beo Trust|website=Heritagecouncil.ie|}}</ref>, the traditional local system of cattle husbandry \"involves exploiting the unusual attributes afforded by the region's limestone geology. Up until quite recently, hardy native breeds of beef cattle were used to graze upland grasslands between the months of October and April, requiring scarcely any dietary supplement prior to their removal to finishing grass elsewhere.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/life-society/farming/farming-in-ireland-overvi/farming-in-the-burren/|title=Farming in the Burren|website=www.askaboutireland.ie|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122181644/http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/life-society/farming/farming-in-ireland-overvi/farming-in-the-burren/|archivedate=2018-01-22}}</ref> Thus the agricultural methods used but also protected the landscape.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://burrenbeo.com/the-burren/natural-heritage/agriculture/|title=Agriculture - Burrenbeo Trust|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124070640/https://burrenbeo.com/the-burren/natural-heritage/agriculture/|archivedate=2018-01-24}}</ref>\n\n====Challenges====\nSince the 20th century the spread of intensive farming techniques (including sometimes heavy use of nitrate fertilisers) along with the possibilities offered by heavy equipment to transform limestone pavement into pasture has posed new challenges for the ecosystem and its diversity. Research conducted in the 1990s suggests that by the end of that decade the area of limestone pavement had halved since pre-Famine times, c. 1840, while from the 1970s to the 1990s alone, about 4% of pavements were converted into pasture or covered by roads. \n\nDespite the intensification of agriculture on the uplands{{cn|date=January 2018}}, population numbers fell from around 4,000 at the beginning of the 20th century to roughly 2,500 by the time of the 1991 Census, before rising once more. The number of farmers fell by 8% in the 1990s and average farm size increased to {{convert|100|ha|acre}} by 2001.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|39-40}}<ref name=\"Roden\"/>{{rp|41}}<ref name=\"Dunford\">\n{{Citation | last =Dunford| first =Brendan| contribution =Agricultural Practices and Natural Heritage| year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell |editor-first1 =J.W. |editor-last2 =Korff | editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =234-8|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas | id = }}</ref>{{rp|236}} \n\nA particular issue arose from the increasing spread of brush, notably hazel, but also blackthorn and hawthorn. These colonised more of the limestone area as a result of reduced grazing by cattle and goats. The increasing industrialization of agriculture and the introduction of different breeds of cattle led to shifts in cattle-raising practices \u2013 away from winter grazing, which kept down new growth, and towards supplementary feeding.{{cn|date=January 2018}} In addition, in the past saplings were often pulled from fields by hand to maintain grazing areas. Trees also used to be harvested for firewood, hazel rods were used for thatching as well as for fence- and basket-making. As these practices ceased, the brush advanced. This notably reduces biodiversity in the affected areas.<ref name=\"Dunford\"/>{{rp|236-8}}\n\n====BurrenLIFE====\nIn response to under-grazing, loss of husbandry and land management traditions, and abandonment and consolidation of farms, the BurrenLIFE program, coordinated by the geopark, launched a new sustainable farming initiative.  This began with twenty farms, representative of the diversity of local agriculture, for each of which a specific plan of costed actions was devised.  After refinement, the initiative was extended to 320 farmers over two phases, and another 130 are expected to join a final phase.  Typical recommendations enacted included scrub clearance, restoration of drystone walls, reduction in silage usage and a return to winter grazing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/eu-life-nature-award-burren-life-project-3423137-Jun2017/|title=A new project is saving the unique landscape of the Burren|first=Hayley|last=Halpin|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606122056/http://www.thejournal.ie/eu-life-nature-award-burren-life-project-3423137-Jun2017/|archivedate=2017-06-06}}</ref>\n\n===Balancing needs===\nFor the past decades, the government and private groups have attempted to square the demands of local farmers, tourists and the environment.  In particular, sometimes outdated or leaky septic tanks used by rural houses have contributed to the damage done to groundwater by agricultural practices.{{cn|date=January 2018}} In a limestone environment, the use of percolation and septic tanks may in fact not be a viable alternative to sewage treatment.{{cn|date=January 2018}} However, this is still lacking in much of the area. The sewage of the village of Ballyvaughan, for example, is still pumped untreated into the sea.<ref name=\"ClareFM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clare.fm/news/disappointment-clare-waste-water-treatment-issues-wont-be-dealt-until-2019|title=Disappointment as Clare Waste Water Treatment Issues Won't Be Dealt With Until 2019|publisher=Clare FM|date=24 November 2016|accessdate=3 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104000108/http://www.clare.fm/news/disappointment-clare-waste-water-treatment-issues-wont-be-dealt-until-2019|archivedate=4 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|40}}<ref name=\"Broad\">\n{{Citation | last =Broad| first =Richard| contribution =Beyond the Tourist Boom| year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell |editor-first1 =J.W. |editor-last2 =Korff | editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =232-4|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas | id = }}</ref>{{rp|233}}\n\n===Development initiatives===\nCommunity and local authority programs have been launched over decades, notably a County Council initiative of the mid-2000s, which became ''Burren Connect'' in 2006, and led, in 2011, to the geopark,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sustainability-leaders.com/interview-carol-gleeson-burren-geopark-ireland/|title=Interview with the Geopark Manager on Burren Connect and its predecessor and successor|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122235103/https://sustainability-leaders.com/interview-carol-gleeson-burren-geopark-ireland/|archivedate=2018-01-22}}</ref> which in turn secured funding for the Geopark LIFE program.  The Burrenbeo Trust, Burren Ecotourism Network and [[Burren Way]] Committee are other examples.\n\n==Designations==\nMost of the Burren is today designated as a [[List of Special Areas of Conservation in the Republic of Ireland|Special Area of Conservation]], including almost all upland, and much of the lowland and northern shore areas.<ref name=\"BP\">{{cite web|url=http://burrenprogramme.com/the-programme/objectives/|title=The Burren Programme|publisher=Burren Programme|accessdate=28 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229100446/http://burrenprogramme.com/the-programme/objectives/|archivedate=29 December 2016}}</ref>  There are also designated Areas of Scientific Interest and Natural Heritage Areas.\n\n===Geopark===\nThe [[Burren and Cliffs of Moher Geopark]], formed in 2011 on the basis of earlier community and local authority work, is part of the [[Global Geoparks Network|Global Geoparks Network (GGN)]] and recognised by [[UNESCO]] since that year. Encompassing an expansively defined Burren, including the Cliffs of Moher, it is managed by the [[Clare County Council]] and supported by [[Failte Ireland]] and the [[Geological Survey of Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burrengeopark.ie/the-organisation/|title=Our Organisation - Burren and Cliffs of Moher Geopark - Ireland|website=www.burrengeopark.ie|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628194749/http://www.burrengeopark.ie/the-organisation/|archivedate=2017-06-28}}</ref><ref name=\"Geo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalgeopark.org/aboutGGN/list/IrelandRepublic/6619.htm/|title=Burren and Cliffs of Moher Geopark|publisher=Global Geoparks Network|accessdate=28 December 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925102341/http://www.globalgeopark.org/aboutGGN/list/IrelandRepublic/6619.htm|archivedate=25 September 2016}}</ref> The boundary of the Geopark extends from the vicinity of New Quay on Galway Bay, southeast to the Tubber area, then southwest to Corrofin then roughly west towards Doolin and includes the coastal strip containing the Cliffs of Moher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burrengeopark.ie/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Map-of-the-Burren-and-Cliffs-of-Moher-Geopark.pdf|title=Map of the Burren and Cliffs of Moher Geopark|publisher=Burren Geopark|accessdate=25 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201080735/http://www.burrengeopark.ie/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Map-of-the-Burren-and-Cliffs-of-Moher-Geopark.pdf|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref>  The geopark supports education and community engagement and sustainable tourism and other development, and employs a full-time geologist, Dr. [[Eamon N. Doyle]].\n\n===National Park===\nThe '''Burren National Park''' is one of six [[National Parks in the Republic of Ireland|National Parks]] in the country. Taking in a modest sampling of the southeastern Burren, about {{convert|1500|ha|acre}}, it is made up of land purchased by the Irish government to be set aside for conservation purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burrennationalpark.ie/|title=Burren National Park|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320212025/http://www.burrennationalpark.ie/|archivedate=2017-03-20}}</ref> After a prolonged controversy (see [[Mullaghmore, County Clare|Mullaghmore]] and the [[Burren Action Group]]), the planned construction of a visitor centre was shelved. The National Park currently has an information point at [[Corofin, County Clare|Corofin]]. It is also associated with the preservation area at nearby [[Dromore, County Clare|Dromore Wood]].<ref name=\"NPH\"/>\n\n==Sport and leisure==\nThe Burren's many limestone cliffs, particularly the sea-cliffs at [[Ailladie]], are popular with [[climbing|rock-climbers]]. For [[caving|cavers]], there are a number of charted caves in the area, notably [[Pollnagollum]]. Doolin is a popular \"base camp\" for cavers, and is home to one of the two main cave-rescue stores of the [[Irish Cave Rescue Organisation]].\n\nThe Burren is popular with walkers and trails include the [[Burren Way]], often taken over a five day period, and the Cliffs of Moher Coastal Walk of {{convert|18|km|mi}}.\n\nThe Burren also has a range of local [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] clubs, [[Association Football|soccer]] clubs and other sporting groups.  While the landscape is challenging for maintenance of [[golf]] clubs, there are facilities near Gort and [[Lahinch Golf Club|Lahinch]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:The Burren.jpg|The Burren landscape\nFile:Burren_karst_meadow.jpg|Karst meadow\nFile:Flowers in the burren.jpg|Native flowers and rock formations\nFile:Karst_dome.jpg|Karst dome near Kilkeedy Parish - eastern part of The Burren\nFile:Burren_fence_made_of_rock.jpg|The Burren fence\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Burren Action Group]]\n* [[Wild Atlantic Way]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Notes==\n# {{note|BBC}} [https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A642610 BBC: The Flowers of the Burren, County Clare, Ireland]\n# {{note|clarelibrary}} A similar quote \"''The Burren affordeth not a piece of timber sufficient to hang a man, water in any one place to drown a man, or earth enough in any one part to bury him.''\" can be found in \"The Journal of [[Thomas Dineley]]\", 1681, in the National Library of Ireland. Extracts from his journal, including his account of the Clare section of his journey, were published in the ''Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries'', 6 (1867). These appear in an online version in \"The History and Topography of the County of Clare\" by James Frost Part II. History of Thomond Chapter 28 [http://www.clarelibrary.ie/eolas/coclare/history/dineley_1681/1681_burren.htm Barony of Burren]\n\n==Bibliography==\n===General, Geology, Landscape===\n*Feehan, J., Korff, A. & O'Connell, J.W., ''The Book of the Burren'', Irish Books and Media, 1991\n*D\u2019Arcy & Hayward. ''The Natural History of The Burren''.\n*D'Arcy, Gordon: ''The Breathing Burren'', Cork: Collins Press, 2016\n*Clements, Paul: ''Burren Country: Travels Through an Irish Limestone Landscape'', Cork: Collins Press, 2011 (reprint)\n*[[Sarah Poyntz|Poyntz, Sarah]]: ''Burren Villages'', Cork: Mercier Press, 2006\n*Hennessy, R., McNamara, M., & Hoctor, Z., 2010 ''Stone, Water & Ice: A Geology Trip Through the Burren''. Burren Connect Project, pp.&nbsp;64.\n*Sheehy Skeffington, M., Moran, J., O Connor, \u00c1., Regan, E., Coxon, C. E., Scott, N. E. & Gormally, M. 2006. ''Turloughs \u2013 Ireland\u2019s unique wetland habitat''. In: ''Biological Conservation'' 133:265-290.\n*Anon. ''The Burren: A Guide''. Shannonside Mid-Western Regional Tourism Organization Ltd., Limerick.\n===Flora===\n*D.A. Webb & M.J.P. Scannell. 1983 ''Flora of Connemara and The Burren''. Royal Dublin Society & Cambridge University Press.\n*E. C. Nelson. ''Checklist of Plants of The Burren Region''.\n*E.C. Nelson & W. Walsh. ''The Burren Wildflowers'', Conservancy of The Burren, An Bothan, Ballyvaughan, Co. Clare.\n*McCarthy, P.M. and Mitchell, M.E. 1988. ''Lichens of the Burren Hills and the Aran Islands.''  Galway. Officina Typographica.\n===Fauna===\n*Bilton, D.T., 1988. ''A survey of aquatic Coleoptera in Central Ireland and the Burren''. In: ''Bulletin of the Irish biogeographical Society'' 11: 77-94.\n*Foster, G.N., Nelson, B.H. & O Connor, A. 2009. ''Ireland Red List No. 1 - Water beetles''. National Parks and Wildlife Service, Department of Environment, Heritage and Local Government, Dublin.\n*O'Callagan, E., Foster, G.N., Bilton, D.T. & Reynolds, J.D. 2009 ''Ochthebius nilssoni'' Hebauer new for Ireland (Coleoptera: Hydraenidae), including a key to Irish Ochthebius and Enicocerus. ''Irish Naturalists' Journal'' 30: 19-23\n===Archaeology===\n*Carthy, Hugh: ''Burren Archaeology'', Cork: Collins Press, 2011\n*T. J. Westropp, 1999, ''Archaeology of The Burren: Prehistoric Forts and Dolmens in North Clare'' Clasp Press (reprint)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Burren|The Burren}}\n* [http://www.burrennationalpark.ie/ Burren National Park Website]\n* [https://burrenbeo.com/the-burren/ The Burrenbeo Trust]\n* [http://www.theburrencentre.ie/ The Burren Centre at Kilfenora]\n* [http://caherconnell.com/ Caherconnel Stone Fort]\n\n{{Tourism in County Clare}}\n{{National parks in the Republic of Ireland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burren, The}}\n\n[[Category:National parks of the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of County Clare]]\n[[Category:Parks in County Clare]]\n[[Category:Alpine flora]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Arctic]]\n[[Category:Natural regions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Glaciated karst landscape region in northwest County Clare, Ireland}}\n{{About|a region in County Clare in the Republic of Ireland ||Burren (disambiguation){{!}}Burren}}\n\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = The Burren\n| alt_name = ''Boireann''\n| iucn_category = \n| photo = Burren 0513.JPG\n| photo_alt = \n| photo_caption = The [[karst landscape]] of the Burren\n| photo_width = \n| map = Ireland\n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = Location of the Burren National Park, SE corner of the Burren\n| map_width = \n| relief =\n| label = Burren National Park (Mullaghmore)\n| label_position = \n| mark =\n| marker_size =\n| location = [[County Clare|Co. Clare]] (and a little of [[County Galway|Co. Galway]]), [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| nearest_city = [[Galway]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|53|00|28|N|9|00|08|W|type:landmark_region:IE|display=inline,title}}\n| coords_ref = \n| region = \n| area_ha = \n| designation =\n| authorized =\n| created =\n| established = \n| designated =\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| visitation_ref =\n| governing_body = \n| administrator =\n| operator =\n| owner =\n| website = \n| url = \n| child = \n| embedded = \n}}\n\n'''The Burren''' ({{Irish place name|Boireann|great rock}}) is a region of environmental interest primarily located in northwestern [[County Clare]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], dominated by glaciated [[karst]] (or sometimes [[glaciokarst]]<ref name=\"BurrenNP_Geol\">[https://www.burrennationalpark.ie/geology] Burren National Park - Geology - \"The Burren is one of the finest examples of a Glacio-Karst landscape in the world. At least two glacial advances are known in the Burren area.\"</ref>) landscape.  It measures, depending on the definition, between {{convert|250|km2|mi2}} and {{convert|560|km2|mi2}}. The name is most often applied to the area within the circle made by the villages of [[Tubber, County Clare|Tubber]], [[Corofin, County Clare|Corofin]], [[Kilfenora]], [[Lisdoonvarna]], and [[Ballyvaughan]], and [[Kinvara]] in extreme south-western Galway, including the adjacent coastline.<ref name=\"GeoParkGuide\">{{cite web|title=The Burren Visitor Guide|url=http://www.burrengeopark.ie/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Burren-Free-Visitor-Guide.pdf|website=Burren and Cliffs of Moher Geopark|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref> \n\nA part of the Burren forms the [[Burren National Park]], the smallest of the six [[National Parks in the Republic of Ireland|National Parks]] in Ireland, while the full Burren and adjacent territory including the [[Cliffs of Moher]] are included in the [[Burren and Cliffs of Moher Geopark]].\n\n==Location==\nWhile the name is generally applied to the limestone uplands of northwestern Clare, and adjacent lowlands, and generally excludes the area of ''Clare shales'' to the southwest, the exact extent of the area is not clearly defined, and geologically it does extend into [[County Galway]] to both the north and northeast (see ''Geology'' below). The southeastern pocket of Co. Galway around Kinvara is usually included, and is the base for many Burren organisations. \nThe Burren is certainly bounded by the [[Atlantic Ocean]] and by [[Galway Bay]], with the [[Aran Islands]] representing a geological extension of the limestone hills that make up most of The Burren.<ref name=\"Explore\">{{cite book|last=Cunningham|first=George|title=Exploring the Burren|publisher=Town House and Country House, Dublin|year=1998|isbn=0-946172-59-5|page=}}</ref>{{rp|5}}\n\nAccording to one definition, the Burren extends south to a line from the coastal resort of [[Lahinch]] to Corofin and is delimited in the east by a line roughly from Kinvara to [[Kilmacduagh monastery]], near [[Gort]]. Note that taken literally, this would includes places like the town of [[Ennistymon]] and the [[Cliffs of Moher]], which would more commonly be considered as neighbouring the Burren.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|5}}  In another definition, the \"Burren Programme\" defines the region as extending well into the Gort plain, encompassing inter alia [[Coole Park]] and the [[Turlough (lake)|turloughs]] around it, while to the south it would extend to [[Ruan, County Clare|Ruan]] and [[Crusheen]], and in the southwest to the edge of [[Doolin]], as well as the routine Lisdoonvarna, Kilfenora and Corofin.<ref name=\"BP\"/>\n\nThus the stated size of the Burren varies between around {{convert|250|km2|mi2}} (the core area of exposed limestone), through {{convert|360|km2|mi2}} (taking in all limestone landscapes) and 560 square kilometers (including the about {{convert|200|km2|mi2}} of downland), depending on the approach taken. Roughly 60% of the uplands show exposed limestone pavement.<ref name=\"NPH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.burrennationalpark.ie/history|title=Burren National Park History|publisher=National Parks and Wildlife Service|accessdate=28 December 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930092125/http://www.burrennationalpark.ie/history|archivedate=30 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|5,16,33}}\n\n==Climate==\nThe Burren has an unusually temperate climate for western Ireland. Average air temperatures range from {{convert|15|C|F}} in July to {{convert|4|-|6|C|F}} in January, while the soil temperature does not usually drop below 6&nbsp;\u00b0C (as an exception, in late 2010, there was a prolonged period of snow). Since grass will grow once the temperature rises above 6&nbsp;\u00b0C, this means that The Burren (like the neighbouring Aran Islands) has one of the longest growing seasons in Ireland or Britain, and supports diverse and rich plant growth.<ref name=\"EFNCPclimate\">European Forum on Nature Conservatism and Pastoralism: [http://www.efncp.org/hnv-showcases/ireland-the-burren/the-burren/facts/ The Burren - Facts] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125015321/http://www.efncp.org/hnv-showcases/ireland-the-burren/the-burren/facts/ |date=2018-01-25 }}</ref>\n\nThe area has around {{convert|1525|mm|in}} of annual rainfall (more than twice the amount observed in eastern Ireland),<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|33}} with an average level of over {{convert|160|mm|in}} monthly from October to January<ref name=\"EFNCPclimate\"/>\n\nLate May is the sunniest time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.met.ie|title=Met \u00c9ireann - The Irish Weather Service|first=Met|last=\u00c9ireann|website=www.met.ie|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701025856/http://www.met.ie/|archivedate=2007-07-01}}</ref> and also a good time to view flowers, with the [[gentians]] and [[Dryas (plant)|avens]] peaking (but orchid species blooming later).{{citation needed|date=December 2011|reason=some orchid species have finished flowering by this date and others are at their flowering peak}}\n\nDuring counter-guerrilla operations in The Burren in 1651-52, [[Edmund Ludlow]] stated, \"''(Burren) is a country where there is not enough water to drown a man, wood enough to hang one, nor earth enough to bury him...... and yet their cattle are very fat; for the grass growing in turfs of earth, of two or three foot square, that lie between the rocks, which are of limestone, is very sweet and nourishing.''\"{{ref|BBC}}{{ref|clarelibrary}}\n\n==Geology==\n[[File:The Burren in the evening sun.JPG|thumb|225px|right|The Burren landscape in the evening sun]]\n[[Image:Burren karst.jpg|thumb|The karst hills of The Burren]]\n[[File:The Burren (2002).jpg|thumb|225px|right|Grikes and clints run along the [[limestone pavement]]]]\n\n===Stratigraphy===\nThe area is formed from a thick succession of [[sedimentary rock]]s, largely limestones but also including [[sandstone]]s, [[mudstone]]s and [[siltstones]]. All of the solid rocks exposed at the surface are of [[Carboniferous]] age though they are underlain at depth by [[Old Red Sandstone]] of [[Devonian]] age which in turn overlies rocks of Lower [[Palaeozoic]] age. None of the pre-Carboniferous rocks is seen at the surface in the area.<ref name=\"auto\">Landscape and Rocks of the Burren: a guide to the geology of the area. Geological Survey of Ireland 2008</ref> The limestones, which date from the [[Visean]] stage of the early Carboniferous, formed as sediments in a tropical sea approximately 325 million years ago. The strata contain fossil [[coral]]s, [[crinoid]]s, [[sea urchin]]s and [[ammonites]]. This bed of limestone is up to 800 metres thick. In the north and west it lies on a shelf of Galway granite which supported the upper layers, preventing shifts like those that created the \"twisted\" hills Knockanes and Mullaghmore. The limestone also extends below Galway Bay out to the Aran Islands and to the east into the Gort plain.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|16,33}}\n\nLater in the Carboniferous (c. 318 million years ago), the limestone was covered by darker sand and mud that later turned into [[shale]] (the lower \"Clare Shales\") and [[sandstone]] (the upper \"Millstone Grit\"). These layers reached a thickness of up to {{convert|330|m|ft}} in north Clare. These top layers protected the underlying limestone from erosion for millions of years before being largely stripped away by glaciers, except in the south west, where they still extend from Doolin to Slieve Elva, Lisdoonvarna, Kilfenora and to the western shore of Lake Inchiquin. One \"island\" of shale is the hill Poulacapple, southwest of Ballyvaughan, where an upland moor has formed on top of the impermeable shale layers.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|16,33}}<ref name=\"Feehan1\">\n{{Citation | last =Feehan | first =John | contribution =The Rocks and Landforms of the Burren | year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell |editor-first1 =J.W. |editor-last2 =Korff | editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =14-23|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas | id = }}</ref>{{rp|17}}\n\nThe local geological succession comprises the following [[geological formation|formations]] some of which are subdivided into various [[Stratigraphic_unit#Lithostratigraphic_units|members]]. The youngest rocks are at the start of the list, the oldest at the bottom. The first three listed are of [[Namurian]] age and are a mix of mudstones, sandstones and siltstones, the remainder are Visean age limestones.\n\n*Central Clare Group\n*Gull Island Formation\n*Clare Shale Formation\n*Slievenaglasha Formation\n**Lissylisheen Member\n**Ballyelly Member\n**Fahee North Member\n**Balliny Member\n*Burren Formation\n**Ailwee Member\n**Maumcaha Member\n**Hawkhill Member\n**Fanore Member\n**Black Head Member\n*Tubber Formation\n**Finavarra Member\n**Castlequarter Member\n**Newtown Member\n**Fiddaun Member\n**Cregmahon Member<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Quaternary===\nGlaciation during the late [[Quaternary]] period (beginning c. one million years ago) facilitated greater denudation. Glaciers expanded and retreated over the region several times. Of the last two periods the first was the more pronounced, covering the whole of the Burren. The last advance of the ice cover was more limited, affecting only the eastern Burren.<ref name=\"Feehan1\"/>{{rp|20-1}}\n\nThe result is that The Burren is one of the finest examples of [[glaciokarst|glacio-karst]] landscape in the world. The effects of the [[last glacial period]] (the Midlandian) are most in evidence, with The Burren overrun by ice during this glaciation.<ref name=\"BurrenNP_Geol\"/> The impact of earlier [[karstification]] (solutional erosion) has been eliminated by the last glacial period. So any surface karstification now seen dates from approximately 10,000 years ago and The Burren karst is thus very recent in geological terms. \n\nSolutional processes have widened and deepened the grikes of the [[limestone pavement]]. Pre-existing lines of weakness in the rock (vertical joints) contribute to the formation of extensive fissures separated by clints (flat pavement like slabs). The rock karstification facilitates the formation of subterranean drainage. This has formed numerous cave systems of which more than 50 kilometers have been mapped.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|33}} The most accessible of these is [[Aillwee Cave]].\n\nDue to the processes mentioned, there are very few permanent surface rivers in the region. The Caher, flowing into the sea at [[Fanore]], is one of the most stable.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|33}} Some of the large valleys, mostly running south to north, that are still visible today are in fact the remains of pre-glacial river valleys. The rivers disappeared from the surface when the upper layers of stone had been stripped away. \n\nAnother characteristic features of The Burren are closed roughly circular depressions with no surface outlets for water (called [[polje]]). Around 100 of these exist, mostly present in the eastern Burren. The most notable are the valleys of Kilcorney, Poulawilan, Caherconnel and Carran, generally stretching from northeast to southwest. The largest is the Carran depression, more than two miles long, up to a mile wide and over 200 feet deep. This is where the pre-glacial rivers of the area first eroded away the upper layers and started to dissolve the exposed limestone. Some of the smaller ones were created when caves underneath collapsed (one example of this is the Glen of Clab).<ref name=\"Feehan1\"/>{{rp|19-20}}\n\nGlaciers also deposited numerous granite and limestone [[Glacial erratic|erratics]] on the pavements. The former were carried south across Galway Bay by the second-to-last glaciation. Granite boulders can be found mostly in the north of the Burren. The final ice cover came from the northeast and mostly deposited limestone erratics. On Slieve Elva these are visible today at elevations of up to {{convert|300|m|ft}} mabove sea level. The characteristic terracing of the hills occurred when vertical joints weathered and large blocks of limestone fell off and were further eroded away.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|33}}<ref name=\"Feehan1\"/>{{rp|16,21}}\n\nTowards the very end of the Ice Age the glaciers ended for a time at Fanore. At that time, Slieve Elva and Knockauns hill alone rose above the surrounding ice fields. The valleys facing Galway Bay had been widened considerably by glacial action, first when the ice moved south from Connemara and then when meltwater sought a runoff. When the ice finally retreated it also left moraines in valley bottoms and the characteristic [[drumlin]]s (most of them on top of the shale and sandstone to the south). The Caher Valley was almost choked up by deposited sand and rocks and these also piled up against the western slopes of Slieve Elva. It was this protective layer of sediment that has made surface streams locally possible once more.<ref name=\"Feehan1\"/>{{rp|21}} \n\nToday, the uplands' highest point is on the hill Slieve Elva, whose shale cover rises up to {{convert|345|m|ft}} above sea level.<ref name=\"JourneyWest\">{{cite book|last=Cunningham|first=George|title=Burren Journey West|publisher=Shannonside Mid Western Regional Tourism Organisation|year=1980|isbn=0-9503080-2-1|page=}}</ref>{{rp|47}}\n\n==Landscape types and habitats==\nIn addition to the limestone pavement, major landscape types, providing the habitats for the flora and fauna, include limestone heath, dry calcareous grasslands, calcareous (calcifying or petrifying) springs, the intermittent water bodies called [[turloughs]], bogs, [[cladium fens]], lakes, wet grasslands, scrub and light woodland, and neutral, and farm-improved, grasslands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://burrenprogramme.com/the-burren/habitats/|title=Habitats|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124005748/http://burrenprogramme.com/the-burren/habitats/|archivedate=2018-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==Flora and fauna==\n[[File:Burren Flora 24 Early Purple Orchid (3585561235).jpg|thumb|Early Purple Orchid]]\n[[File:Burren Flora 01 Mountain Avens (3586050338).jpg|thumb|Mountain Avens]]\n\n===Flora===\nThe Burren is renowned for its remarkable assemblage of plants and animals,<ref>{{cite web|jstor=20494847|title=Noteworthy Plants of the Burren: A Catalogue Raisonn\u00e9|publisher=}}</ref> and over 70% of Ireland's species of flowers are found there.<ref name=\"Burrenbeo Conservation\">Clare, The Burrenbeo Trust: [https://burrenbeo.com/the-burren/conservation/ The Burren - Conservation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123072636/https://burrenbeo.com/the-burren/conservation/ |date=2018-01-23 }}</ref> The region supports [[Arctic\u2013alpine]] and [[Mediterranean Basin]] plants side-by-side, due to the unusual environment.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|35}}\n\nThe region supports many rare Irish species, some of which are only found in this area. Others occur in similar karst areas in western Ireland. Notable plants include ''[[Festuca|Festuca indigesta]]'' seen in 1949 and ''[[Arenaria norvegica]]'' identified only once, in 1961. Two of the 24 types of ''[[Taraxacum]]'' found here are \"practically unique to the Burren\".<ref name=\"Roden\"/>{{rp|32}} 23 of the 28 types of orchids found in Ireland grow in the Burren, including unique forms such as ''[[Dactylorhiza|Dactylorhiza fuchsii subsp. okellyi]]''.<ref name=\"Roden\">{{Citation | last =Roden| first =Cilian| contribution =The Burren Flora| year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell |editor-first1 =J.W. |editor-last2 =Korff | editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =31-41|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas | id = }}</ref>{{rp|32}}\n\nThe grikes (crevices in the limestone) provide moist shelter, supporting a wide range of plants including dwarf shrubs. Where the surface of the limestone pavement is shattered into gravel many of the hardier Arctic or alpine plants can be found, while when the limestone pavement is covered by a thin layer of soil patches of grass are seen, interspersed with herbaceous plants. Among the flowers recorded from the Burren is the [[spring gentian]], an alpine plant with bright blue flowers that are used as a symbol for the area by the national tourist board, [[Failte Ireland]]. The Irish orchid (''[[Neotinea maculata]]'' and 21 other [[List of the orchids of Ireland|species of orchids]] ) and bloody cranesbill (''[[Geranium sanguineum]]'') also occur.<ref>Clements, P. 2011 ''Burren Country, Travels through an Irish Limestone Landscape''. The Collins Press. {{ISBN|9781848891173}}</ref> Other notable flowers are ''[[Anacamptis pyramidalis]]'', ''[[Platanthera chlorantha]]'', ''[[Ophrys insectifera]]'' ''[[Euphrasia salisburgensis]]'', ''[[Lathyrus linifolius]]'', ''[[Carlina vulgaris]]'', ''[[Centaurium erythraea]]'', ''[[Succisa pratensis]]'', ''[[Primula veris]]'', ''[[Filipendula vulgaris]]'', ''[[Parnassia palustris]]'', ''[[Campanula rotundifolia]]'',  ''[[Helianthemum oelandicum]]'', ''[[Polygala vulgaris]]'', ''[[Saxifraga|Saxifraga hypnoides]]'', ''[[Potentilla fruticosa]]'',  ''[[Antennaria|Antennaria dioeca]]'', ''[[Primula vulgaris]]'', ''[[Hypericum androsaemum]]'', ''[[Asperula cynanchica]]'', ''[[Rhinanthus minor]]'', ''[[Blackstonia perfoliata]]'' and ''[[Dryas octopetala]]'' <ref> Webb, D. A.,1962 Noteworthy Plants of the Burren A Catalogue Raison ''Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy'' , Vol. LXII, sect. B, No. 9, pp. 117-134, 1962  (pdf available at [[JSTOR]]) </ref> . Another prominent presence in limestone grikes are around 24 species of fern, such as the Mediterranean ''[[Adiantum capillus-veneris]]''. \n\nThe area is notable for the unusually close vicinity of both plants that hate lime and those that do well on it. Acid-loving plants such as ''[[Calluna]]'' grow well on patches of acidic peat that effectively isolates them from the underlying basic limestone.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|20-1,35-6}}\n\n===Fauna===\nOf the more than 30 species of butterflies and moths found in Ireland only two are not present in the Burren.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|37}} Notable insects present in the Burren include the butterflies the [[pearl-bordered fritillary]] (''Boloria euphrosyne''), [[brown hairstreak]] (''Thecla betulae''), [[marsh fritillary]] (''Euphydryas aurinia'') and [[Leptidea sinapis|wood white]] (''Leptidea sinapis''); the moths, the [[Calamia tridens|Burren green]] (''Calamia tridens'', which is only present in Ireland in this area),<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|37}} [[Gnophos dumetata|Irish annulet]] (''Gnophos dumetata'') and [[transparent burnet]] (''Zygaena purpuralis''); the hoverfly ''[[Doros profuges]]'' and the water-beetle ''[[Ochthebius nilssoni]]''. This last species is known from just five sites in the world, its type locality in northern Sweden and four [[marl]] lakes in The Burren. \n\nThe Burren is one of the main breeding areas in Ireland of the [[European pine marten]].  Also present are badgers, foxes and stoats. The hillsides of the Burren also host herds of feral goats.<ref name=\"Arcy\">{{Citation | last =D'Arcy| first =Gordon| contribution =The Wildlife of the Burren| year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell |editor-first1 =J.W. |editor-last2 =Korff | editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =47-58|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas | id = }}</ref>{{rp|55}} All seven species of bats present in Ireland can be found in The Burren.<ref name=\"Explore\" />{{rp|37}} [[Otter]]s live along the coast, as do [[Grey seal|grey seals]]. [[List of mammals of Ireland|porpoises,dolphins]] and [[Basking shark|basking sharks]] can be spotted off Black Head and various sections of the [[Cliffs of Moher]]. \n\nA wide range of bird species are also found in the Burren, including crows and ravens, [[peregrine falcon|peregrine falcons]], [[kestrel|kestrels]], various gulls, [[guillemot|guillemots]], [[razorbill|razorbills]], [[kittiwake|kittiwakes]], [[fulmar|fulmars]], [[puffin|puffins]] and [[European shag|shags]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Burren Landscape 2.jpg|thumb|225px|right|The Burren landscape with Galway Bay in the background]]\n\n===Prehistory===\n[[File:Poulnabrone_Portal_Tomb_640x480.jpg|thumb|Poulnabrone portal tomb]]\nPollen analysis indicates that in the [[Mesolithic]] period of 8000 to 7000 BC The Burren looked completely different from today, with most of the uplands covered in a mixture of deciduous, pine and yew trees. No clear evidence of Mesolithic settlements or camp sites in the area has yet been discovered. At the limits of the region, near [[Lake Inchiquin]] and at the so-called \"Doolin Axe Factory\", stone artifacts have been discovered that may be Mesolithic in origin. However, by the [[Neolithic]], c. 4000 BC, settlers had clearly arrived and began changing the landscape through deforestation, likely by overgrazing and burning, and the building of stone walls. These people also constructed Megalithic sites like the portal tomb known as [[Poulnabrone dolmen]] and the [[Court cairn|court tombs]] at Teergonean (near Doolin) and Ballyganner (near [[Noughaval]]). Overall, there are around 70 megalithic tombs in the Burren area, more than half of all of these structures found in Clare.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|7-8}}<ref name=\"Arch\">{{cite book|last=Carthy|first=Hugh|title=Burren Archaeology|publisher=The Collins Press|year=2011|isbn=9781848891050|page=}}</ref>{{rp|5}}<ref name=\"Waddell\">{{Citation | last =Waddell| first =John | contribution =The First People - the Prehistoric Burren| year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell |editor-first1 =J.W. |editor-last2 =Korff | editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =59-76|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas | id = }}</ref>{{rp|60}}\n\nThe most numerous type of prehistoric structure (apart from stone walls) in The Burren is the late-Neolithic/early-[[Bronze Age]] [[Wedge-shaped gallery grave|wedge tomb]], mostly dated to the period 2500 to 2000 BC. It accounts for around 90% of the region's megalithic tombs. Many examples of these are found on Roughan Hill near [[Kilnaboy]], including those at [[Parknabinnia (wedge tomb)|Parknabinnia]] and [[Creevagh (wedge tomb)|Creevagh]]. Others are located at [[Gleninsheen (wedge tomb)|Gleninsheen]] and Berneens (Rathborney) and Poulaphuca (Carran). Large stone cairns on many hills, such as the [[Poulawack Cairn]], also date from this period.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|8}}<ref name=\"Waddell\"/>{{rp|63}}\n\nThe economy at that time was likely based on pastoral farming in fairly small groups. As is still done today, the cattle were moved in a reverse of the usual seasonal pattern: cattle are moved to the uplands in the winter, allowing year round grazing.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|8}}\n\nEvidence of [[Beaker culture|Beaker pottery]] was found on Roughan Hill, but in general few signs of the actual settlements of the Neolithic people have been found. This may be due to the fact that their structures were lightly built (from wood or other non-permanent materials).<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|11}} \n\nDuring the Bronze Age, locals also built many ''[[Fulacht fiadh|Fulachtai fiadh]]'', remains of more than 300 survive in the region. Their exact function is still debated, but they probably served as places where water was heated by fire, either for cooking, brewing or bathing purposes.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|8}}\n\nHowever, in contrast to the quantity of archaeological evidence found, the population of The Burren likely declined noticeably between the late Neolithic and the end of the Bronze Age. This was likely largely due to a shift in the climate, possibly related to the volcanic eruption known as \"[[Hekla 4]]\". Around the end of the 3rd millennium BC temperatures dropped and the climate became wetter. Heavy rainfall combined with previous clearing activity to cause serious soil erosion in the uplands. Evidence suggests that much of the soil cover over the limestone karst was in fact removed during the Middle and Late Bronze Age. This reduction in the area of fertile land put pressure on population numbers and probably increased conflicts over scarce resources. Building of new stone walls largely came to an end \u2013 there is a gap in documented building between the late Neolithic/early Bronze Age and early Christian periods. By the end of the Bronze Age, the uplands were largely depopulated.<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|10}}\n\nNevertheless, like the [[Mooghaun North Hoard]] found near Newmarket-on-Fergus, the discovery of a golden Bronze Age gorget in [[Rathborney|Gleninsheen townland]] indicates the (at least temporary) local presence of a late Bronze Age society that was rich, mobile and well-connected via trade networks with other regions.<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|13}} \n\nLike in many places of Ireland, datable [[Iron Age]] sites are rare in The Burren. This may be due to the use of dwellings that did not leave durable traces (wooden buildings or even tents). Some of the extant [[ringfort|r\u00e1ths, cashels or cahers]] may actually have Iron Age origins. However, few have been excavated and those that have been the subject of research, like [[Cahercommaun]], [[Caherconnell Stone Fort|Caherconnel]], [[Cahermore ringfort|Cahermore]] or [[Ballyallaban ringfort|Ballyallaban]], are thought to be early Medieval or later in origin. The large enigmatic enclosure of Turlough Hill (see [[Oughtmama]]) may be Iron Age or earlier. Definite regional findings from this era are limited to a few bronze horse bridles discovered near Corofin and at Ballyalla ([[Kilshanny]]).<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|9}}<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|16}}\n\n===Medieval===\n[[File:Ucht M\u00e1ma Middle and West Churches NW 2015 09 02.jpg|thumb|Early Christian churches at Oughtmama]]\n[[File:Corecomroe Abbey Ruhende Statue.jpg|thumb|Tomb in the sanctuary of Corcomroe Abbey with effigy of Conor O'Brien, King of Thomond]]\n\nIn the Iron Age and early Medieval times, the region was controlled by a family or tribe known as the ''Corco Modhruadh'', meaning \"seed\" or \"people of Modhruadh\". They were one of dozens of minor tribes in Ireland at that time, which occupied a discrete area (''tuath'') and were joined by a common bloodline or origin myths. By the time Christianity arrived locally, their territory had shrunk somewhat, encompassing what later became the Baronies of Burren and Corcomroe as well as some parts of Inchiquin barony (see below).<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|9}}<ref name=\"Gosling\"/>{{rp|78}}\n\nDuring the 5th and 6th centuries, the region appears to have been ruled from the Aran Islands by the ''E\u00f3ganacht \u00c1rann'', a minor branch of the [[E\u00f3ganachta|E\u00f3ganacht dynasty of Munster]].<ref name=\"Gosling\">{{Citation|last =Gosling|first =Paul|contribution =The Burren in Early Historic Times|year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell|editor-first1 =J.W.|editor-last2 =Korff|editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =77-91|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas|id = }}</ref>{{rp|78}}\n\nThe history of these years is uncertain, but after the decline of the ''E\u00f3ganacht \u00c1rann'' the local ''Corco Modhruadh'' likely fell under the control of the ''[[U\u00ed Fiachrach Aidhne]]'', a tribe from what is now southern Galway, who prospered in the 7th century. The local tribes were then probably subjects of the ''[[E\u00f3ganacht Locha L\u00e9in]]'' until their influence declined in the early 9th century. Whether the ''Corco Modhruadh'' still existed as a distinct group at that point is uncertain, as they and their neighbours ''[[Corcu Baiscind]]'' may have been assimilated into or conquered by the ''[[D\u00e9isi|D\u00e9isi Tuisceart]]'' of eastern Clare, who won a major battle against the ''Corco Modhruadh'' in 744. By the 9th century, the ''Corco Modhruadh'' had been driven into the Burren uplands.<ref name=\"Gosling\"/>{{rp|78}} \n\nThe Burren area is notable for the presence of several potential or likely \"early\" (i.e. pre-12th-century) ecclesiastical or monastic sites. These include Kilfenora, Kilnaboy, [[Temple Cronan]] and the churches of Oughtmama. A broader definition of The Burren would also include [[Dysert O'Dea Monastery]] near Corofin and Kilmacduagh. The large number of extant cashels, almost 500 of which have been identified in The Burren (out of around 45,000 in Ireland), also indicates the presence of a sizeable (early) medieval population that supported and used these churches.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|11}}<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|19}}\n\nAt the end of the first millennium, the ''[[D\u00e1l gCais]]'' expanded into the region, against the resistance of the incumbent [[U\u00ed Lochlainn]] and [[O'Conor]] families. The later regionally dominant [[O'Brien dynasty]] traced its origins to them. Evidence of Viking activity in the region is scant. They settled at Limerick, but in the Burren only a few artifacts of Scandinavian design have been found, centred mostly on Cahercommaun, which apparently was a major producer of wool at the time. A Viking arrowhead was found at the ringfort and a Viking hollow-bead necklace (likely dating from 820 to 850 AD) was discovered in nearby Glencurran Cave.<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|21-4}}\n\nEither at the end of the 12th or early in the 13th century, [[Cistercian]] monks came to the area and established ''Sancta Maria de Petra Fertili'', now known as [[Corcomroe Abbey]].<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|12}}\n\nIn the 12th century, the ''Corco Modhruadh''/Corcomroe territory was made into the newly created [[Diocese of Kilfenora]], of 13 parishes, and the church at Kilfenora became a cathedral.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|9-10}} \n\nAt some point around the 12th century, the territory of \"Corcomroe\" was divided in two for administrative purposes: ''Corco Modhruadh Iartharach'' (\"Western Corcomroe\") and ''Corco Modhruadh Oirthearach'' (\"Eastern Corcomroe\"), also known as ''Boireann'' which in the late 16th century became the English administrative Baronies of [[Corcomroe (barony)|Corcomroe]] and [[Burren (barony)|Burren]], respectively.<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|27}}\n\nThe end of the Medieval period was a difficult era for people in the area. Like much of Europe, the region suffered from the [[Great Famine of 1315\u201317|Great Famine]] (1315-7) and the [[Black Death]]. In addition, infighting between the Gaelic lords contributed to a socio-economic decline of the region. This was also reflected in a regional hiatus in large construction projects during the 13th and most of the 14th century.<ref name=\"Arch\"/>{{rp|30}}\n\n===Early Modern===\nFor a long-time the [[Norman invasion of Ireland|Anglo-Norman incursions into Ireland]] had little direct impact on the region. As late as at the [[Battle of Dysert O'Dea]] in 1318 some of the local clans allied to defeat a Norman army led by [[Richard de Clare, Steward of Forest of Essex|Richard de Clare]]. The people and their rulers thus continued to live in fortified houses, often inside the cashels, mostly retaining their [[Gaelic Ireland|Gaelic culture]]. One example of this are the [[Early Irish law|Brehon]] law schools of the O'Davorans at [[Cahermacnaghten]] or the MacClancys at Doolin.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|11-4}}\n\nOnly in the 15th and 16th centuries did the [[tower houses]] as exemplified today by places like [[Newtown Castle]], [[Shanmuckinish Castle]], [[Doonagore Castle]] or [[Ballinalacken Castle]] become widespread. Norman-type castles, such as the one built at [[Quin Abbey|Quin]], were absent in the Burren.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|11-4}} T.J. Westropp counted the remains of around 70 tower houses in the Baronies of Inchiquin, Corcomroe and Burren, with 21 of them located in the latter. Only around half of those 21 survive to any height in the 21st century. The distribution of the tower houses indicates that they were built close to the barony borders, which also represented the boundaries of the territories controlled by clans or families (see below). 11 of the 21 tower houses in the Barony of Burren lie within 1 km of its borders.<ref name=\"Gosling2\">{{Citation|last =Gosling|first =Paul|contribution =The Burren in Medieval Times|year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell|editor-first1 =J.W.|editor-last2 =Korff|editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =119-34|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas|id = }}</ref>{{rp|127,129}}\n\nThe O'Loughlin (\u00d3 Lochlainn) clan ruled ''Boireann'' down to the mid-17th century from their chief residence at [[Gregans Castle]] (the tower house, not the house of the same name). The chief of the family was known in later times as the 'Prince of Burren' and clan members were buried in the family tomb near the altar of Corcomroe Abbey. Their kinsmen, the O'Conor (\u00d3 Conchubhair), clan ruled ''Corco Modhruadh Iartharach'' from [[Dough Castle]] near [[Liscannor]]. The villages and towns found within the medieval territory of Boireann include Lisdoonvarna, Ballyvaughan, New Quay (Newquay) / Burrin (Burren), [[Noughaval]], Bealaclugga (Bellharbour), [[Carran|Carron]] and Fanore / Craggagh.\n\nBoth clans were eventually subjects of the O'Briens, the rulers of [[Thomond]]. Especially in the southwest, the O'Briens sometimes extended their direct influence, taking over houses and territories for themselves. They controlled the castles at [[Dromoland Castle|Dromoland]] and [[Leamaneh Castle|Leamaneh]] and later became the [[Baron Inchiquin|Barons Inchiquin]].<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|12}}\n\n==Culture==\nThe Burren has a long history of traditional Irish music. It is particularly known for the \"West Clare Style\" of [[concertina]] playing, and music festivals in [[Doolin]] and [[Corofin, County Clare|Corofin]].  The area also has a long history as a source of artistic inspiration, and has hosted a number of art galleries.\n\nThe Burren has inspired many non-fiction books, often accompanied by extensive illustration of the landscape.  A series of [[detective fiction]] novels, written by Cora Harrison, features the Burren's [[brehon]] judge (fictional) in the early 1500s, when the area still existed as a distinct Gaelic administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://severnhouse.com/author/Cora+Harrison/9419|title=Severn House|website=severnhouse.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122235021/http://severnhouse.com/author/Cora+Harrison/9419|archivedate=2018-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==Economic activity==\nThe leading economic activities in the Burren are agriculture and tourism.\n\n===Tourism===\nThe Burren has a reputation beyond Ireland, and, most notably with the Cliffs of Moher, but also with the major [[show caves]], [[dolmens]] such as at [[Poulnabrone]] and other prehistoric sites, and centres of cultural activity, attracts tourists from a wide range of countries.  There are a range of hotels, hostels, bed and breakfast facilities, and other accommodation providers.\n\nTourism presents some challenges in such an environmentally sensitive area, as it creates mostly seasonal employment, results in a large share of local houses being used only in the summer, and puts additional strain on environmental resources, thus exacerbating the effect of a significant increase in the number of houses in some areas during the 1990s and 2000s.  This has been a thread in the development and preservation activities previously discussed, and has driven the growth of local ecotourism, and the \"Leave No Trace\" local campaigns.  Concerns have also arisen about the level of day-tourism, especially by coaches, as opposed to overnight-staying tourists, who generate significantly more revenue.\n\n====Ecotourism in the Burren====\n[[Ecotourism]] is an important factor in The Burren, with many organisations involved, including the Burren Ecotourism Network. A key goal is to deal with the challenge of protecting the vulnerable landscape, while at the same time having it provide a fair income for the local inhabitants and allowing it to cope with increased visitor numbers. [[Sustainability|Sustainable]] ecotourism and independent \"'Ecotourism Certification\" for companies are intended to deal with those conflicting demands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theburrencentre.ie/burren-ecotourism/|title=Burren EcoTourism {{!}} The Burren Centre|website=www.theburrencentre.ie|access-date=2 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820015209/http://www.theburrencentre.ie/burren-ecotourism/|archivedate=20 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Gastro-tourism====\nA Burren Food Trail was launched in 2013, and has more than 20 members offering hospitality, and / or food and drink products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burren.ie/food-dining/burren-food-trail/|title=Burren Food Trail - Visit the Burren|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028220623/http://www.burren.ie/food-dining/burren-food-trail/|archivedate=2017-10-28}}</ref> The trail won the Irish prize in the European Destination of Excellence - Tourism and Local Gastronomy competition in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.failteireland.ie/footer/media-centre/the-burren-food-trail-is-cream-of-the-crop.aspx|title=Failte Ireland - The Burren Food Trail is Cream of the Crop|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129140453/http://www.failteireland.ie/footer/media-centre/the-burren-food-trail-is-cream-of-the-crop.aspx|archivedate=2018-01-29}}</ref> In association with the food trail events such as a Slow Food festival and a Food Fayre are organised.  The Food Fayre, part of the Burrenbeo-coordinated Winterage Festival around the October public holiday weekend, and run by the Burren Ecotourism Network and the Burren Food Trail team, reached its sixth year in 2017.\n\n===Agriculture===\nDue to climate and landscape, and techniques evolved over thousands of years, the Burren has a history as a productive agricultural landscape.  Arable farming is limited, and the main animals kept are cattle and goats.\n\nAs summarized by local landscape organisation, the Burrenbeo Trust<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heritagecouncil.ie/our-work-with-others/burren-beo-trust|title=Burren Beo Trust|website=Heritagecouncil.ie|}}</ref>, the traditional local system of cattle husbandry \"involves exploiting the unusual attributes afforded by the region's limestone geology. Up until quite recently, hardy native breeds of beef cattle were used to graze upland grasslands between the months of October and April, requiring scarcely any dietary supplement prior to their removal to finishing grass elsewhere.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/life-society/farming/farming-in-ireland-overvi/farming-in-the-burren/|title=Farming in the Burren|website=www.askaboutireland.ie|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122181644/http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/life-society/farming/farming-in-ireland-overvi/farming-in-the-burren/|archivedate=2018-01-22}}</ref> Thus the agricultural methods used but also protected the landscape.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://burrenbeo.com/the-burren/natural-heritage/agriculture/|title=Agriculture - Burrenbeo Trust|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124070640/https://burrenbeo.com/the-burren/natural-heritage/agriculture/|archivedate=2018-01-24}}</ref>\n\n====Challenges====\nSince the 20th century the spread of intensive farming techniques (including sometimes heavy use of nitrate fertilisers) along with the possibilities offered by heavy equipment to transform limestone pavement into pasture has posed new challenges for the ecosystem and its diversity. Research conducted in the 1990s suggests that by the end of that decade the area of limestone pavement had halved since pre-Famine times, c. 1840, while from the 1970s to the 1990s alone, about 4% of pavements were converted into pasture or covered by roads. \n\nDespite the intensification of agriculture on the uplands{{cn|date=January 2018}}, population numbers fell from around 4,000 at the beginning of the 20th century to roughly 2,500 by the time of the 1991 Census, before rising once more. The number of farmers fell by 8% in the 1990s and average farm size increased to {{convert|100|ha|acre}} by 2001.<ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|39-40}}<ref name=\"Roden\"/>{{rp|41}}<ref name=\"Dunford\">\n{{Citation | last =Dunford| first =Brendan| contribution =Agricultural Practices and Natural Heritage| year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell |editor-first1 =J.W. |editor-last2 =Korff | editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =234-8|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas | id = }}</ref>{{rp|236}} \n\nA particular issue arose from the increasing spread of brush, notably hazel, but also blackthorn and hawthorn. These colonised more of the limestone area as a result of reduced grazing by cattle and goats. The increasing industrialization of agriculture and the introduction of different breeds of cattle led to shifts in cattle-raising practices \u2013 away from winter grazing, which kept down new growth, and towards supplementary feeding.{{cn|date=January 2018}} In addition, in the past saplings were often pulled from fields by hand to maintain grazing areas. Trees also used to be harvested for firewood, hazel rods were used for thatching as well as for fence- and basket-making. As these practices ceased, the brush advanced. This notably reduces biodiversity in the affected areas.<ref name=\"Dunford\"/>{{rp|236-8}}\n\n====BurrenLIFE====\nIn response to under-grazing, loss of husbandry and land management traditions, and abandonment and consolidation of farms, the BurrenLIFE program, coordinated by the geopark, launched a new sustainable farming initiative.  This began with twenty farms, representative of the diversity of local agriculture, for each of which a specific plan of costed actions was devised.  After refinement, the initiative was extended to 320 farmers over two phases, and another 130 are expected to join a final phase.  Typical recommendations enacted included scrub clearance, restoration of drystone walls, reduction in silage usage and a return to winter grazing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/eu-life-nature-award-burren-life-project-3423137-Jun2017/|title=A new project is saving the unique landscape of the Burren|first=Hayley|last=Halpin|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606122056/http://www.thejournal.ie/eu-life-nature-award-burren-life-project-3423137-Jun2017/|archivedate=2017-06-06}}</ref>\n\n===Balancing needs===\nFor the past decades, the government and private groups have attempted to square the demands of local farmers, tourists and the environment.  In particular, sometimes outdated or leaky septic tanks used by rural houses have contributed to the damage done to groundwater by agricultural practices.{{cn|date=January 2018}} In a limestone environment, the use of percolation and septic tanks may in fact not be a viable alternative to sewage treatment.{{cn|date=January 2018}} However, this is still lacking in much of the area. The sewage of the village of Ballyvaughan, for example, is still pumped untreated into the sea.<ref name=\"ClareFM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clare.fm/news/disappointment-clare-waste-water-treatment-issues-wont-be-dealt-until-2019|title=Disappointment as Clare Waste Water Treatment Issues Won't Be Dealt With Until 2019|publisher=Clare FM|date=24 November 2016|accessdate=3 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104000108/http://www.clare.fm/news/disappointment-clare-waste-water-treatment-issues-wont-be-dealt-until-2019|archivedate=4 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Explore\"/>{{rp|40}}<ref name=\"Broad\">\n{{Citation | last =Broad| first =Richard| contribution =Beyond the Tourist Boom| year = 2001|title =The Book of the Burren|editor-last1 =O'Connell |editor-first1 =J.W. |editor-last2 =Korff | editor-first2 =Anne|volume = |pages =232-4|place = |publisher =Tir Eolas | id = }}</ref>{{rp|233}}\n\n===Development initiatives===\nCommunity and local authority programs have been launched over decades, notably a County Council initiative of the mid-2000s, which became ''Burren Connect'' in 2006, and led, in 2011, to the geopark,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sustainability-leaders.com/interview-carol-gleeson-burren-geopark-ireland/|title=Interview with the Geopark Manager on Burren Connect and its predecessor and successor|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122235103/https://sustainability-leaders.com/interview-carol-gleeson-burren-geopark-ireland/|archivedate=2018-01-22}}</ref> which in turn secured funding for the Geopark LIFE program.  The Burrenbeo Trust, Burren Ecotourism Network and [[Burren Way]] Committee are other examples.\n\n==Designations==\nMost of the Burren is today designated as a [[List of Special Areas of Conservation in the Republic of Ireland|Special Area of Conservation]], including almost all upland, and much of the lowland and northern shore areas.<ref name=\"BP\">{{cite web|url=http://burrenprogramme.com/the-programme/objectives/|title=The Burren Programme|publisher=Burren Programme|accessdate=28 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229100446/http://burrenprogramme.com/the-programme/objectives/|archivedate=29 December 2016}}</ref>  There are also designated Areas of Scientific Interest and Natural Heritage Areas.\n\n===Geopark===\nThe [[Burren and Cliffs of Moher Geopark]], formed in 2011 on the basis of earlier community and local authority work, is part of the [[Global Geoparks Network|Global Geoparks Network (GGN)]] and recognised by [[UNESCO]] since that year. Encompassing an expansively defined Burren, including the Cliffs of Moher, it is managed by the [[Clare County Council]] and supported by [[Failte Ireland]] and the [[Geological Survey of Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burrengeopark.ie/the-organisation/|title=Our Organisation - Burren and Cliffs of Moher Geopark - Ireland|website=www.burrengeopark.ie|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628194749/http://www.burrengeopark.ie/the-organisation/|archivedate=2017-06-28}}</ref><ref name=\"Geo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalgeopark.org/aboutGGN/list/IrelandRepublic/6619.htm/|title=Burren and Cliffs of Moher Geopark|publisher=Global Geoparks Network|accessdate=28 December 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925102341/http://www.globalgeopark.org/aboutGGN/list/IrelandRepublic/6619.htm|archivedate=25 September 2016}}</ref> The boundary of the Geopark extends from the vicinity of New Quay on Galway Bay, southeast to the Tubber area, then southwest to Corrofin then roughly west towards Doolin and includes the coastal strip containing the Cliffs of Moher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burrengeopark.ie/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Map-of-the-Burren-and-Cliffs-of-Moher-Geopark.pdf|title=Map of the Burren and Cliffs of Moher Geopark|publisher=Burren Geopark|accessdate=25 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201080735/http://www.burrengeopark.ie/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Map-of-the-Burren-and-Cliffs-of-Moher-Geopark.pdf|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref>  The geopark supports education and community engagement and sustainable tourism and other development, and employs a full-time geologist, Dr. [[Eamon N. Doyle]].\n\n===National Park===\nThe '''Burren National Park''' is one of six [[National Parks in the Republic of Ireland|National Parks]] in the country. Taking in a modest sampling of the southeastern Burren, about {{convert|1500|ha|acre}}, it is made up of land purchased by the Irish government to be set aside for conservation purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burrennationalpark.ie/|title=Burren National Park|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320212025/http://www.burrennationalpark.ie/|archivedate=2017-03-20}}</ref> After a prolonged controversy (see [[Mullaghmore, County Clare|Mullaghmore]] and the [[Burren Action Group]]), the planned construction of a visitor centre was shelved. The National Park currently has an information point at [[Corofin, County Clare|Corofin]]. It is also associated with the preservation area at nearby [[Dromore, County Clare|Dromore Wood]].<ref name=\"NPH\"/>\n\n==Sport and leisure==\nThe Burren's many limestone cliffs, particularly the sea-cliffs at [[Ailladie]], are popular with [[climbing|rock-climbers]]. For [[caving|cavers]], there are a number of charted caves in the area, notably [[Pollnagollum]]. Doolin is a popular \"base camp\" for cavers, and is home to one of the two main cave-rescue stores of the [[Irish Cave Rescue Organisation]].\n\nThe Burren is popular with walkers and trails include the [[Burren Way]], often taken over a five day period, and the Cliffs of Moher Coastal Walk of {{convert|18|km|mi}}.\n\nThe Burren also has a range of local [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] clubs, [[Association Football|soccer]] clubs and other sporting groups.  While the landscape is challenging for maintenance of [[golf]] clubs, there are facilities near Gort and [[Lahinch Golf Club|Lahinch]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:The Burren.jpg|The Burren landscape\nFile:Burren_karst_meadow.jpg|Karst meadow\nFile:Flowers in the burren.jpg|Native flowers and rock formations\nFile:Karst_dome.jpg|Karst dome near Kilkeedy Parish - eastern part of The Burren\nFile:Burren_fence_made_of_rock.jpg|The Burren fence\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Burren Action Group]]\n* [[Wild Atlantic Way]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Notes==\n# {{note|BBC}} [https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A642610 BBC: The Flowers of the Burren, County Clare, Ireland]\n# {{note|clarelibrary}} A similar quote \"''The Burren affordeth not a piece of timber sufficient to hang a man, water in any one place to drown a man, or earth enough in any one part to bury him.''\" can be found in \"The Journal of [[Thomas Dineley]]\", 1681, in the National Library of Ireland. Extracts from his journal, including his account of the Clare section of his journey, were published in the ''Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries'', 6 (1867). These appear in an online version in \"The History and Topography of the County of Clare\" by James Frost Part II. History of Thomond Chapter 28 [http://www.clarelibrary.ie/eolas/coclare/history/dineley_1681/1681_burren.htm Barony of Burren]\n\n==Bibliography==\n===General, Geology, Landscape===\n*Feehan, J., Korff, A. & O'Connell, J.W., ''The Book of the Burren'', Irish Books and Media, 1991\n*D\u2019Arcy & Hayward. ''The Natural History of The Burren''.\n*D'Arcy, Gordon: ''The Breathing Burren'', Cork: Collins Press, 2016\n*Clements, Paul: ''Burren Country: Travels Through an Irish Limestone Landscape'', Cork: Collins Press, 2011 (reprint)\n*[[Sarah Poyntz|Poyntz, Sarah]]: ''Burren Villages'', Cork: Mercier Press, 2006\n*Hennessy, R., McNamara, M., & Hoctor, Z., 2010 ''Stone, Water & Ice: A 